\mt1 ECCLESIASTICUS 
\c 1  
\cl CHAPTER 1 
\p  
\v 1 All wisdom is of \sls (or from)\sls* the Lord God, and was ever with him, and is before the world. 
\p  
\v 2 Who numbered the gravel of the sea, and the drops of rain, and the days of the world? 
\p  
\v 3 Who measured the highness \add [or the height]\add* of heaven, and the breadth of \sls (the)\sls* earth, and the depth of the sea? Who ensearched \sls (or searched for)\sls* the wisdom of God, that goeth before all things? 
\p  
\v 4 Wisdom was formed first of all things, and the understanding of prudence, from the world, \em that is, from without beginning\em*. 
\p  
\v 5 The well of wisdom is the son of God in high things; and the entering of that \em wisdom\em* is \sls (the)\sls* everlasting commandments. \add [The well of wisdom \+sls (is)\+sls* the word of God in heights; and the in-going of it \+sls (is)\+sls* everlasting commandments.]\add* 
\p  
\v 6 To whom was the root of wisdom showed? and who knew the subtleties thereof? 
\p  
\v 7 To whom was the lore \add [or the discipline]\add* of wisdom showed, and made open? and who understood the multiplying of the entering thereof, \em that is, of the work thereof\em*? 
\p  
\v 8 One is the highest Creator \add [or the maker \+sls (out)\+sls* of nought]\add* of all things, almighty, and a mighty king, and worthy to be dreaded full much, sitting on the throne of that \em wisdom\em*, and God having lordship. 
\p  
\v 9 He formed it in the Holy Ghost, and he saw, and numbered, and he measured \sls (it)\sls*. And he shedded \add [or poured]\add* out it \add [up]\add* on all his works, 
\p  
\v 10 and on each flesh by his gift \add [or and upon all flesh after his gift]\add*; he giveth it to them that love him. 
\p  
\v 11 The dread of the Lord \em is\em* glory, and glorying \add [or joying]\add*, and gladness, and a crown of full out joying. 
\p  
\v 12 The dread of the Lord shall delight the heart; and shall give gladness and joy into \add [the]\add* length of days. 
\p  
\v 13 To him that dreadeth God, it shall be well in the last things, or in the last days; and he shall be blessed in the day of his death. Forsooth they to whom \em wisdom\em* appeareth in sight, \em that is, by \+sls (the)\+sls* revelation of prophecy\em*, love it in sight, and in \sls (the)\sls* knowing of his great things. The love of God \em is\em* honourable wisdom. 
\p  
\v 14 The beginning of wisdom \em is\em* the dread of the Lord; and it is formed together in the womb with faithful men, and it goeth with chosen women, and it is known with just \add [or rightwise]\add* men and faithful. 
\p  
\v 15 The dread \sls (or fear)\sls* of the Lord \em is\em* religiosity of cunning, \sls (or knowing, or knowledge)\sls*. Religiosity shall keep, and shall justify the heart; and shall give mirth and joy. It shall be well to him that dreadeth God; and he shall be blessed in the days of his comfort \add [or \+sls (the)\+sls* ending of him]\add*. 
\p  
\v 16 The fullness of wisdom \em is\em* for to dread God; and fullness \em is\em* of the fruits thereof. 
\p  
\v 17 It shall fill each gift \add [or each house]\add* of him of \sls (or for)\sls* generations, and \sls (the)\sls* receipts of \sls (or the recep-tacles with)\sls* the treasures thereof. 
\p  
\v 18 The crown of wisdom \em is\em* the dread of the Lord, and filleth peace \add [or ful-filling peace]\add*, and the fruit of health. And he saw, and numbered it; for-sooth ever either be the gifts of God. 
\p  
\v 19 Wisdom shall part the cunning \sls (or the knowing)\sls* and understanding of prudence; and it enhanceth the glory of them, that hold it. 
\p  
\v 20 The root of wisdom is for to dread God; forsooth the branches thereof \em be\em* long enduring \add [or long living]\add*. Understanding and religiosity of cunning, \sls (or knowing, or knowl-edge)\sls*\em be\em* in the treasures of wisdom; but wisdom \em is\em* abomination to sinners. 
\p  
\v 21 The dread of the Lord putteth away sin, for he that is without dread \em of God\em*, may not be \add [or shall not be able to be]\add* justified; 
\p  
\v 22 for why the wrathfulness of his pride \add [or willfulness]\add* is the destroying of him. 
\p  
\v 23 A patient man shall suffer \em the dis-eases of a proud man\em* till into \sls (a)\sls* time; and afterward there shall be yielding of mirth. 
\p  
\v 24 Good wit shall hide the words of him till into a time; and the lips of many men shall tell out the wit of him. 
\p  
\v 25 In the treasures of wisdom is signifying of cunning \sls (or of knowing)\sls*; but the worshipping of God is \sls (an)\sls* abomination to a sinner. 
\p  
\v 26 A! \sls (or O)\sls* son, coveting wisdom, keep thou rightfulness \add [or rightwise-ness]\add*, and God shall give it to thee. 
\p  
\v 27 For why the dread of the Lord \em is\em* wisdom, and cunning \sls (or knowing)\sls*, \add [or discipline]\add*, and that that is well pleasant \sls (or well-pleasing)\sls* to him \em is\em* faith and mildness \sls (or meekness)\sls*; and \em God\em*\add [or it]\add* shall \add [full]\add*-fill the treasures of him. 
\p  
\v 28 Be thou not rebel\sls (lious)\sls*, and unbelieveful to the dread of the Lord; and nigh \sls (or approach)\sls* thou not to him in \add [or with]\add*\sls (a)\sls* double heart. 
\p  
\v 29 Be thou not an hypocrite in the sight of men; and be thou not slandered in \sls (or caused to stumble by)\sls* thy lips. 
\p  
\v 30 Take thou keep \sls (or care)\sls* to those \add [things]\add*, lest thou fall, and bring dishonor to thy soul; and lest God show thy privates \sls (or thy secrets)\sls*, \add [or hid things]\add*, and hurtle thee down in the midst of the synagogue, \em that is, of \+sls (the)\+sls* gathering together of faithful men\em*; for thou nighedest wickedly \add [or maliciously]\add* to the Lord, and thine heart was full of guile and of falseness. 
\c 2  
\cl CHAPTER 2 
\p  
\v 1 Son, nighing to the service of God, stand thou in rightfulness \add [or rightwiseness]\add*, and dread; and make ready \add [or prepare]\add* thy soul to \sls (or for)\sls* temptation. 
\p  
\v 2 Bear down thine heart, and suffer, and bow down thine ear, and take the words of understanding, and haste thou not into the time of death \add [or oppressing]\add*. 
\p  
\v 3 Suffer thou the sustainings of God; be thou joined to God, and abide thou, \sls (so)\sls* that thy life wax, \sls (or grow, or increase)\sls* in the last time. 
\p  
\v 4 Take thou all thing that is set to thee, and suffer thou in sorrow, and have thou patience in thy lowness \add [or meekness]\add*. 
\p  
\v 5 For why gold and silver is proved in fire; forsooth men worthy to be received \em be proved\em* in the chimney of lowness \add [or of meekness]\add*. 
\p  
\v 6 Believe thou to God, and he shall recover thee; and \sls (ad)\sls*dress \sls (or direct)\sls* thou thy way, and hope thou into him. Keep thou his dread, and wax thou eld therein \add [or in him wax old]\add*. 
\p  
\v 7 Ye that dread the Lord, abide his mercy, and bow ye not away from him, lest ye fall down \add [or lest ye fall]\add*. 
\p  
\v 8 Ye that dread the Lord, believe to \sls (or in)\sls* him, and your meed \sls (or your reward)\sls* shall not be voided \add [away]\add*. 
\p  
\v 9 Ye that dread the Lord, hope into him, and mercy shall come to you into delighting. 
\p  
\v 10 Ye that dread the Lord, love him, and your hearts shall be lightened or enlightened. Sons, behold ye the nations of men, and know ye, that no man hoped in the Lord, and was shamed \sls (or confounded)\sls*; \em none\em* dwell-ed \add [or abode still]\add* in his behests \sls (or commandments)\sls*, and was forsaken; either who inwardly called him, and he despised him? 
\p  
\v 11 For why God is piteous \sls (or com-passionate)\sls*, and merciful, and he shall forgive sins in the day of trib-ulation; and he is \sls (the)\sls* defender to \sls (or of)\sls* all men, that seek him in truth. 
\p  
\v 12 Woe \em to the\em* double in heart, and with cursed lips, and mis-doing \add [or evil-doing]\add* hands; and to a sinner entering \add [or going]\add* into the land by two ways. 
\p  
\v 13 Woe to them that be dissolute of \add [or unstable in]\add* heart, that believe not to God; and therefore they shall not be defended of \sls (or by)\sls* him. 
\p  
\v 14 Woe to them that have lost patience, and that have forsaken rightful \add [or right]\add* ways, and have turned away \add [or aside]\add* into shrewd \sls (or depraved)\sls* ways. And what shall they do, when the Lord shall begin to behold \sls (upon them)\sls*? 
\p  
\v 15 They that dread the Lord, shall not be unbelieveful to his word; and they that love him, shall keep his way\sls (s)\sls*. 
\p  
\v 16 They that dread the Lord, shall inquire \sls (of)\sls*\add [or inwardly seek]\add* those things, that be well pleasant \sls (or well-pleasing)\sls* to him; and they that love him, shall be filled with his law. 
\p  
\v 17 They that dread the Lord, shall make ready \add [or prepare]\add* their hearts, and shall hallow their souls in his sight. They that dread the Lord, shall keep his commandments, and they shall have patience till to the beholding of him; 
\p  
\v 18 and shall say, If we do not penance, we shall fall into the hands of the Lord, and not into the hands of men. For by the greatness of him, so and his mercy is with him. The sons of wisdom \em be\em* the church of just \add [or rightwise]\add* men, and the nation of them \em is\em* obedience and love. 
\c 3  
\cl CHAPTER 3 
\p  
\v 1 Dearworthy sons, hear ye the doom of the father; and do ye so, \sls (so)\sls* that ye be safe \sls (or be saved)\sls*. 
\p  
\v 2 For why God honoured the father in \sls (or over the)\sls* sons, and he seeketh, and hath made steadfast the doom of the mother into \sls (or over the)\sls* sons. 
\p  
\v 3 He that loveth God, shall pray for \sls (his)\sls* sins, and he shall abstain himself from those \add [or from them]\add*, and he shall be heard in the prayer of days. 
\p  
\v 4 And as he that treasureth, so he that honoureth his mother. 
\p  
\v 5 He that honoureth his father, shall be made merry in sons, and he shall be heard in the day of his prayer. 
\p  
\v 6 He that honoureth his father, shall live by \add [or with]\add* longer life; and he that obeyeth to the father, shall refresh the mother, \em that is, shall comfort her\em*. 
\p  
\v 7 He that dreadeth the Lord, honoureth father and mother; and he shall serve in work, and word, and in all patience to them that engendered \add [or begat]\add* him, as to lords. 
\p  
\v 8 Honour thy father, \sls (so)\sls* that the blessing of God come to thee; and his blessing dwelleth in the last. 
\p  
\v 9 The blessing of the father maketh steadfast the houses of sons; but the cursing of the mother draweth out the foundaments \sls (or the foundations)\sls*\add [by the root]\add*. 
\p  
\v 10 Have thou not glory in the des-pising of thy father; for it is not glory to thee, but confusion \add [or shame]\add*. 
\p  
\v 11 For why the glory of a man \em is\em* of the honour of his father; and the shame of the son \em is\em* a father without honour. 
\p  
\v 12 Son, receive the eld \add [or the last age]\add* of thy father, and make thou not him sorry \add [or \+sls (have)\+sls* sorrow]\add* in his life; 
\p  
\v 13 and if he faileth in wit, give thou forgiveness, and despise thou not him in thy virtue \sls (or in thy strength)\sls*; 
\p  
\v 14 for why the alms-\add [deed\+sls (s)\+sls*]\add* of \sls (or for)\sls* the father shall not be \add [in]\add* forget-ting \sls (or forgotten)\sls*. For why good shall be restored to thee for the sin of the mother, and building \add [up]\add* shall be made to thee in rightfulness \add [or rightwiseness]\add*; 
\p  
\v 15 and it shall remember of thee in the day of tribulation, and thy sins shall be released \add [or loos\+sls (en)\+sls*ed]\add*, as ice in \sls (the)\sls* clearness, \em either heat\em*, of the sun. 
\p  
\v 16 He is of full evil fame, that forsaketh the father; and he that wratheth the mother, is cursed of \sls (or by)\sls* God. 
\p  
\v 17 Son, perform thy works in mild-ness \sls (or in meekness)\sls*, and thou shalt be loved over the glory of men. 
\p  
\v 18 In as much as thou art great, make thee meek in all things, and thou shalt find grace before God; 
\p  
\v 19 (This verse is omitted in the original text.) 
\p  
\v 20 for why the power of God alone is great, and he is honoured of \sls (or by)\sls* meek men. 
\p  
\v 21 Seek thou not higher things than thou \add [or thyself]\add*, and inquire \add [or search]\add* thou not \sls (about)\sls* stronger things than thou; 
\p  
\v 22 but ever\add [more]\add* think thou \sls (upon)\sls* those things, which God commanded to thee; and be thou not curious in \sls (or about the)\sls* full many works of him. For it is not needful to \sls (or for)\sls* thee to see with thine eyes those things, that be hid. 
\p  
\v 23 In superfluous things do not thou seek \add [or ensearch]\add* manyfold; and be thou not curious in \sls (the)\sls* many works of him; for why full many things above the wit of men be showed to thee. 
\p  
\v 24 For the suspicion of many men hath deceived them\sls (selves)\sls*, and with-held their wits in vanity. 
\p  
\v 25 (This verse is omitted in the original text.) 
\p  
\v 26 An hard heart shall have evil in the last time; and he that loveth peril shall perish therein. An heart that entereth \add [or going]\add* by two ways, \em that is, that hath the knowing of good in understanding, and malice in will\em*, shall not have prosperities, \em either rest\em*; and a man of shrewd \sls (or depraved)\sls* heart, shall be slandered in those \sls (or shall be caused to stumble by them)\sls*. 
\p  
\v 27 A wicked heart shall be grieved in sorrows; and a sinner shall heap to, or add to, \add [or lay to]\add*, to do sin. 
\p  
\v 28 Health \sls (or Deliverance)\sls* shall not be to the synagogue of proud men; for why the thick wood \add [or bush]\add* of sin shall be drawn out \add [or taken up]\add* by the root in them, and it shall not be understood, \em of \+sls (or by)\+sls* sinners who will not think on God’s dooms\em*. 
\p  
\v 29 The heart of a wise man is understood in wisdom, and a good ear shall hear wisdom with all covetousness. A wise heart and able to understand shall abstain itself from sins, and shall have prosperities in the works of rightfulness \add [or rightwise-ness]\add*. 
\p  
\v 30 Water quencheth \sls (a)\sls* fire burning, and alms-\add [deeds]\add* against-standeth sins. 
\p  
\v 31 And God, the beholder of him that yieldeth grace, \em that is, \+sls (that)\+sls* doeth alms-\+sls (deeds)\+sls*\em*, hath mind after-ward; and he shall find steadfastness in the time of his fall. 
\c 4  
\cl CHAPTER 4 
\p  
\v 1 Son, defraud thou not the alms-\add [deed\+sls (s)\+sls*]\add* of a poor man, and turn not over \sls (or away)\sls* thine eyes from a poor man \add [or from the poor]\add*. 
\p  
\v 2 Despise thou not an hungry man, and wrath thou not a poor man in his neediness. \add [The hungering soul not despise thou, and stir thou not out to wrath the poor in his mis-ease.]\add* 
\p  
\v 3 Torment thou not the heart of a needy man, and tarry thou not the gift to a man \em that is\em* set in anguish. \add [The heart of the helpless not torment thou, and draw thou not along \+sls (a)\+sls* gift to the man put in straits.]\add* 
\p  
\v 4 Cast thou not away the praying of a man set in tribulation, and turn not away thy face from a needy man. \add [The praying of the troubled not cast thou away, and turn thou not away thy face from the needy.]\add* 
\p  
\v 5 Turn not away thine eyes from a poor man for ire \add [or wrath]\add*, and give not \em occasion\em*, \add [or cause]\add*, to men ask-ing to curse thee \sls (from)\sls* behind. 
\p  
\v 6 For the prayer of him that curseth thee in the bitterness of soul, shall be heard; forsooth he that made him, shall hear him. 
\p  
\v 7 Make thee easy to speak to the congregation of poor men, and make meek thy soul to a priest, \em that is, do thou due reverence to an eld man\em*, and make meek thine head to a great man. 
\p  
\v 8 Bow down without sorrow thine ear to a poor man \add [or to the poor]\add*, and yield thy debt, and answer thou peaceably in mildness \sls (or with meekness)\sls*. 
\p  
\v 9 Deliver thou him that suffereth wrong from the hand of a proud man, and bear thou not heavily in thy soul \sls (when deeming)\sls*. 
\p  
\v 10 In deeming be thou merciful as a father to fatherless children, and \em be thou\em* for an husband to the mother of them; and thou shalt be as an obedient son of the Highest, and he shall have mercy on thee more than a mother \em hath mercy on her child\em*. 
\p  
\v 11 Wisdom inspireth \add [or inbreathed]\add* life to his \sls (or to its)\sls* sons, and receiveth men seeking him \sls (or it)\sls*, and shall go before \sls (them)\sls* in the way of rightfulness \add [or rightwiseness]\add*; 
\p  
\v 12 and he that loveth that \em wisdom\em*, loveth life, and they that wake to it, shall embrace the peaceableness, \add [or the gladness]\add*, \em either sweetness\em*, thereof. 
\p  
\v 13 They that hold it, shall inherit life; and whither it shall enter, God shall bless. 
\p  
\v 14 They that serve it, shall be obeying to the Holy \sls (One)\sls*; and God loveth them, that love it. 
\p  
\v 15 He that heareth it, deemeth folks; and he that beholdeth it, shall dwell trustily. 
\p  
\v 16 If a man believeth to it \add [or give faith to it]\add*, he shall dwell, and inherit it; and the creatures of them shall be in confirming, \em that is, the works of them shall be confirmed in good\em*. 
\p  
\v 17 For in temptation it goeth with him, and among the first it chooseth him. It shall bring in on him dread, and fear, and proving, and it shall torment him in the tribulation of his doctrine \add [or his teaching]\add*, till it tempt him in his thoughts, and \sls (it)\sls* believe to \sls (or in)\sls* his soul. 
\p  
\v 18 And it shall make him steadfast, and shall bring \sls (the)\sls* right way to him, and it shall make him glad; and shall make naked his privates to him \sls (or shall make open his secrets to him)\sls*, and shall treasure on him cunning \sls (or knowing)\sls*, and understanding of rightfulness \add [or rightwiseness]\add*. 
\p  
\v 19 Forsooth if he erreth, \em God\em*\add [or it]\add* shall forsake him, and shall betake him into the hands of his enemy. 
\p  
\v 20 Son, keep thou \add [or wait \+sls (on)\+sls*]\add*\sls (the)\sls* time, and eschew thou \add [or shun away]\add* from evil. Be thou not ashamed \sls (even)\sls* for thy life to say \sls (the)\sls* truth; 
\p  
\v 21 for why there is shame that bringeth sin, and there is shame that bringeth glory and grace. 
\p  
\v 22 Take thou not a face against thy face, \em that is, against thy soul\em*, neither a leasing \sls (or a lie)\sls* against thy soul. 
\p  
\v 23 Shame thou not thy neighbour in his fall\add [ing]\add*, neither withhold thou a word in the time of health. 
\p  
\v 24 Hide not thy wisdom in the fairness thereof; for why wisdom is known in \sls (the)\sls* tongue, and wit, and cunning \sls (or knowing)\sls*, and teaching in the word of a wise man; and stead-fastness \em is\em* in the works of rightfulness \add [or rightwiseness]\add*. 
\p  
\v 25 Against-say thou not \sls (or Say thou not against)\sls* the word of truth in any manner; and be thou ashamed of the leasing \sls (or lies)\sls* of thy mis-learning. 
\p  
\v 26 Be thou not ashamed to acknowl-edge thy sins; and make thee not subject to each man for sin. 
\p  
\v 27 Do not thou stand against \add [or withstand]\add* the face of the mighty, neither enforce \sls (or endeavor)\sls* thou against the stroke of the flood \sls (or the river)\sls*. 
\p  
\v 28 For rightfulness fight thou for \em the health of\em* thy soul, and till to the death strive thou for rightfulness; and God shall overcome thine enemies for thee. \add [For rightwiseness fight for thy soul, and unto death strive for rightwiseness; and God shall outfight, or overcome, for thee thine enemies.]\add* 
\p  
\v 29 Do not thou be swift in \sls (or with)\sls* thy tongue, and unprofitable and slack, \add [or sloth\+sls (ful)\+sls*]\add*, in \sls (or with)\sls* thy works. 
\p  
\v 30 Do not thou be as a lion in thine house, turning upside down thy menials, and oppressing them that be subject/s to thee. 
\p  
\v 31 Thine hand be not ready to take, and closed \sls (al)\sls*together to give. 
\c 5  
\cl CHAPTER 5 
\p  
\v 1 Do not thou take heed to wicked possessions, and say thou not, Sufficient life is to me \add [or There is to me sufficient life]\add*, \em that is, long is to coming to me, therefore I must get many things\em*; for it shall nothing profit in the time of vengeance, and of failing \add [or oppressing]\add*, \em either death\em*. 
\p  
\v 2 Pursue thou not the covetousness of thine heart in thy strength, \add [Not follow thou in thy strength the coveting of thine heart,]\add* 
\p  
\v 3 and say thou not, As I might, either, who shall make me subject for my deeds? For why God avenging shall avenge. 
\p  
\v 4 Say thou not, I have sinned, and what sorrowful thing befell to me? For the Highest is a patient yielder. 
\p  
\v 5 Of the forgiveness of sins, do not thou be without dread, neither heap thou, \add [or lay thou]\add*, sin upon sin. 
\p  
\v 6 And say thou not, The merciful doing of God is great \add [or The mercy of God is great]\add*; he shall have mercy on the multitude of my sins. For why mercy and ire nigheth soon from him, and his ire beholdeth on sinners. 
\p  
\v 7 Tarry thou not to be converted to the Lord, and delay thou not \add [or put thou it off]\add* from day into day. For why his ire shall come suddenly, and he shall lose \sls (or destroy)\sls* thee in the time of vengeance. 
\p  
\v 8 Do not thou be anguished in unjust \add [or unright]\add* riches; for those \add [or they]\add* shall not profit in the day of failing, \em either of death\em*, and of vengeance. 
\p  
\v 9 Winnow thee not into each wind, and go thou not into each way; for so a sinner is proved in \sls (or with a)\sls* double tongue. 
\p  
\v 10 Be thou steadfast in the way of the Lord, and in truth and cunning \sls (or the knowing)\sls* of thy wit; and the word of peace and of rightfulness \add [or of rightwiseness]\add* pursue thee perfectly. 
\p  
\v 11 Be thou mild \sls (or meek)\sls* to hear the word of God, \sls (so)\sls* that thou understand, and with wisdom bring thou forth a true answer. 
\p  
\v 12 If thou hast understanding, answer thy neighbor; else thine hand be on thy mouth, lest thou be taken \sls (or caught)\sls* in a word unwisely taught, and be ashamed. 
\p  
\v 13 Honour and glory \em is\em* in the word of a wise man; but the tongue of an unprudent man is his destroying. 
\p  
\v 14 Be thou not called a privy evil speaker in thy life, and be thou not taken in \sls (or with)\sls* thy tongue, and be ashamed. Shame and penance is on a thief, and worst shame, \em either cursing, is\em* on a man of \sls (or with a)\sls* double tongue. Forsooth hatred and enmity and despising \em is\em* to a privy backbiter. 
\p  
\v 15 Justify thou a little man and a great man \add [or the little and the great]\add* in like manner. 
\c 6  
\cl CHAPTER 6 
\p  
\v 1 Do not thou for a friend \sls (or instead of a friend)\sls* be made \sls (an)\sls* enemy to \em thy\em* neighbour; for why an evil man shall inherit upbraiding and despising, and each sinner envious and double-tongued. 
\p  
\v 2 Enhance thee not in the thought of thy soul, as a bull \em doeth\em*; lest thy virtue \add [or strength]\add* be hurtled down by folly, 
\p  
\v 3 and it eat thy leaves, and lose \sls (or destroy)\sls* thy fruits, and thou be left as a dry tree in \sls (the)\sls* desert \add [or \+sls (the)\+sls* wilderness]\add*. 
\p  
\v 4 Forsooth a wicked, \add [or shrewd, \+sls (or depraved)\+sls*]\add* soul shall lose \add [or destroy]\add* him that hath it, and it giveth him into the joy of the enemy, and it shall lead forth into the part of wicked men. 
\p  
\v 5 A sweet word multiplieth friends, and assuageth enemies; and a tongue well gracious shall be plenteous \add [or abound]\add* in a good man. 
\p  
\v 6 Many peaceable men be to thee, and \sls (or but)\sls* one \sls (out)\sls* of a thousand be a counsellor to thee. 
\p  
\v 7 If thou hast a friend, have him in temptation, \em that is, prove thou him in thine adversity\em*, and betake not lightly \add [or not lightly open, or trust]\add*, thyself to him. 
\p  
\v 8 For there is a friend by \sls (or for)\sls* his \sls (own)\sls* time, and he shall not dwell \add [or abide]\add* in the day of tribulation. 
\p  
\v 9 And there is a friend which is turned to enmity; and there is a friend, that shall show openly hatred, and chiding \add [or strife]\add*, and despisings. 
\p  
\v 10 Forsooth there is a friend, \sls (a)\sls* fellow of \sls (the)\sls* table, and \sls (he)\sls* dwell-eth not in the day of need. 
\p  
\v 11 If a friend dwelleth steadfast, he shall be as a man even with thee, and he shall do trustily in \sls (or with)\sls* thy menial \add [or homely]\add* things. 
\p  
\v 12 If he meeketh himself before thee, and hideth him\sls (self)\sls* from thy face, thou shalt have good friendship of one accord \add [or of one will]\add*. 
\p  
\v 13 Be thou parted from thine enemies, and take heed of thy friends. 
\p  
\v 14 A faithful friend \em is\em* a strong defending \add [or strong protection]\add*; for-sooth he that findeth him, findeth treasure. 
\p  
\v 15 No comparison is to a faithful friend; weighing of gold and of silver is not worthy against the goodness of his faithfulness. 
\p  
\v 16 A faithful friend \em is\em*\sls (the)\sls* medicine of life, and of undeadliness \sls (or of immortality)\sls*; and they that dread the Lord, shall find him. 
\p  
\v 17 He that dreadeth the Lord, shall have evenly good friendship; for why his friend shall be at the likeness of him. 
\p  
\v 18 Son, from thy youth take thou doctrine, and till to \add [thine]\add* hoar hairs thou shalt find wisdom. 
\p  
\v 19 As he that eareth \sls (or ploweth)\sls*, and that soweth, nigh thou to it, and abide thou \sls (for)\sls* the good fruits there-of. For thou shalt travail a little in the work thereof, and thou shalt eat soon of the generations thereof \add [or the gettings of it]\add*. 
\p  
\v 20 Wisdom is over-sharp or is full-sharp to untaught men, and an heart-less man shall not dwell therein. 
\p  
\v 21 As the virtue \sls (or the strength)\sls* of a stone, proving shall be in them; and they shall not tarry to cast away it \add [or to throw it afar]\add*. 
\p  
\v 22 Forsooth the wisdom of teaching is by the name thereof, and it is not open to many men; but it dwelleth with them, of whom it is known, till to the sight of God. 
\p  
\v 23 Son, hear thou, and take the counsel of understanding, and cast thou not away my counsel. 
\p  
\v 24 Set in thy foot into the stocks thereof, and thy neck into the bies, \sls (or the bands)\sls*, \add [or the collars]\add* thereof. 
\p  
\v 25 Make subject thy shoulder, and bear it, and be thou not annoyed \sls (or harmed)\sls* in the bonds thereof. 
\p  
\v 26 In all thy will go to it, and in all thy virtue keep the ways thereof \add [or of it]\add*. 
\p  
\v 27 Inquire thou \sls (of or about)\sls* it \add [or Ensearch it]\add*, and it shall be made open to thee; and thou made holding \em wisdom\em* forsake not it. 
\p  
\v 28 For in the last things thou shalt find rest therein, and it shall turn \add [or shall be turned]\add* to thee into delight-ing. 
\p  
\v 29 And the stocks thereof shall be to thee in defence \add [or protection]\add* of strength, and the foundaments of virtue, and the bie\sls (s)\sls*, \sls (or the bands)\sls*, \add [or the collars]\add* thereof, in\sls (to)\sls* a stole of glory. 
\p  
\v 30 For why the fairness of life is in wisdom, and the bonds thereof \em be\em* heal\sls (th)\sls*ful, \add [or wholesome]\add* binding. 
\p  
\v 31 Thou shalt wear it as a stole of glory, and thou shalt set \add [or shalt put]\add* on thee a crown of thanking. 
\p  
\v 32 Son, if thou takest heed to me, thou shalt learn wisdom; and if thou givest thy will, thou shalt be wise. 
\p  
\v 33 If thou bowest down thine ear, thou shalt take \sls (or receive)\sls* teaching; and if thou lovest for to hear, thou shalt be wise. 
\p  
\v 34 Stand thou in the multitude of prudent priests, and be thou joined of \sls (or in)\sls* heart to the wisdom of them; 
\p  
\v 35 \sls (so)\sls* that thou mayest hear each telling of God, and the proverbs of praising flee or fly not away from thee. 
\p  
\v 36 And if thou seest a wise man, wake thou to him, and thy foot \add [often]\add* tread on the grees \sls (or the steps)\sls* of his doors. 
\p  
\v 37 Have thou thought in \sls (or on)\sls* the commandments of God, and be thou most busy in his behests; and he shall give to thee \add [an]\add* heart, and covetous-ness of wisdom shall be given to thee. 
\c 7  
\cl CHAPTER 7 
\p  
\v 1 Do not thou do evils, and those shall not take \add [or catch]\add* thee. 
\p  
\v 2 Depart thou from wickedness \add [or Go away from the wicked]\add*, and evils shall fail from thee. 
\p  
\v 3 Sow thou not evils in the furrows of unrightfulness \add [or unrightwiseness]\add*, and thou shalt not reap those in sevenfold. 
\p  
\v 4 Do not thou seek of \sls (or from)\sls* a man \sls (the)\sls* leading \add [or the dignity of a leader]\add*, neither of a king the chair of honour. 
\p  
\v 5 Justify thou not thee \sls (or thyself)\sls* before God, for he is the knower of the heart; and do not thou desire to be seen wise with the king. 
\p  
\v 6 Do not thou seek to be made a judge, no but thou mayest break wickednesses by \sls (thy)\sls* virtue; lest thou dread the face of a mighty man, and set slander \sls (or a cause of stumbling)\sls* in thy swiftness. 
\p  
\v 7 Do not thou sin in \sls (or against)\sls* the multitude of a city, neither send thee, \sls (or thyself)\sls*, \sls (down)\sls* into the people; 
\p  
\v 8 neither bind thou \add [to]\add* double sins, for thou shalt not be guiltless in one. 
\p  
\v 9 Do not thou be a coward in thy soul, to pray; and despise thou not to do alms-\add [deeds]\add*. 
\p  
\v 10 Say thou not, God shall behold in the multitude of my gifts; and when I shall offer to God alder-Highest \add [or to the highest God]\add*, he shall take my gifts. 
\p  
\v 11 Scorn thou not a man in the bitterness of \sls (his)\sls* soul; for why God is the beholder, that maketh meek, and enhanceth \sls (or exalteth)\sls*. 
\p  
\v 12 Do not thou love a leasing \sls (or a lie)\sls* against thy brother; neither do thou in like manner against a friend. 
\p  
\v 13 Do not thou desire to lie any leasing \sls (or any lie)\sls*; for why the continuance thereof \add [or the busyness forsooth of them]\add* is not good. 
\p  
\v 14 Do not thou be a jangler \add [or full of words]\add* in the multitude of priests; and rehearse thou not a word in thy prayer. 
\p  
\v 15 Hate thou not travailous works, and earth-tilthing, \add [or churlish doing]\add* made of \sls (or from)\sls* the Highest. 
\p  
\v 16 Areckon thou not thee in the multitude of unlearned men. Have thou mind on ire \add [or wrath]\add*, for it shall not tarry. 
\p  
\v 17 Make thou meek greatly thy spirit, for why the vengeance of the flesh of an unpious man \em is\em* fire, and worm\sls (s)\sls*. 
\p  
\v 18 Do not thou trespass against thy friend delaying money; neither despise thou a full dearworth\sls (y)\sls* brother for gold. 
\p  
\v 19 Do not thou depart \add [or go away]\add* from a wise woman, and good, whom thou hast gotten in the dread of the Lord; for why the grace of her shame-fastness \em is\em* above gold. 
\p  
\v 20 Hurt thou not a servant working in truth, neither an hired man giving his life. 
\p  
\v 21 A witty, \sls (or a witting, or knowing)\sls* servant be dearworthy to thee as thy \sls (own)\sls* soul; defraud thou not him of freedom, neither forsake thou him \sls (when)\sls* needy. 
\p  
\v 22 Beasts be to thee? take thou heed to those \add [or them]\add*; and if those \add [or they]\add* be profitable, dwell those still at \add [or with]\add* thee. 
\p  
\v 23 Sons be to thee? teach thou them, and bow thou them \em under chastising\em* from their childhood. 
\p  
\v 24 Daughters be to thee? keep thou the body of them, and show thou not \sls (a)\sls* glad face to them. 
\p  
\v 25 Give thy daughter \em to marriage\em*, and thou doest a great work; and give thou her to a wise man. 
\p  
\v 26 If a woman is to thee after thy soul, cast her not away; and \sls (or but)\sls* betake thou not thee in all thine heart to an hateful \em woman\em*. 
\p  
\v 27 Honour thy father; and forget thou not the wailings of thy mother. 
\p  
\v 28 Have thou mind that thou haddest not been, no but by them, and yield thou to them as they \em did\em* to thee. 
\p  
\v 29 In all thy soul dread thou God, and hallow thou his priests. 
\p  
\v 30 In all thy virtue \sls (or strength)\sls* love thou him that made thee; and forsake thou not his ministers \add [or servants]\add*. 
\p  
\v 31 Honour thou God of \sls (or with)\sls* all thy soul; and honour thou priests, and cleanse thee with \sls (thine)\sls* arms, \em that is, by offerings gotten with thy travail\em*. Give thou to them the part of the first fruits, and of purging, as also it is commanded to thee; and of thy negligence purge thou thee with few men. Thou shalt offer to the Lord the gift of thine arms, and the sacrifice of hallowing, the beginnings, \em that is, the first fruits and dimes \+sls (or tithes)\+sls*\em*, of holy men \add [or holy things]\add*. 
\p  
\v 32 And \sls (ad)\sls*dress \sls (or direct)\sls*\add [or put forth]\add* thine hand to a poor man, \sls (so)\sls* that thy mercy and \sls (thy)\sls* blessing be performed. 
\p  
\v 33 Grace is given \add [or Grace of gift]\add* in the sight of each that liveth; and forbid thou not grace to a dead man. 
\p  
\v 34 Fail thou not in \sls (or to do)\sls* comfort to them that weep; and go thou with them that mourn. 
\p  
\v 35 Be thou not slow to visit a sick man \add [or the sick]\add*; for by these things thou shalt be made steadfast in love. 
\p  
\v 36 In all thy works have thou mind on \add [or have in mind]\add* thy last things; and thou shalt not do sin without end. 
\c 8  
\cl CHAPTER 8 
\p  
\v 1 Chide \add [or Strive]\add* thou not with a mighty man, lest thou fall into his hands. 
\p  
\v 2 Strive thou not with a rich man, lest peradventure he make \sls (a)\sls* play again-ward to \sls (or towards)\sls* thee \add [or he set strife to thee]\add*. For why gold and silver hath lost \sls (or destroyed)\sls* many men; and it stretcheth forth till to the heart\add [s]\add* of kings, and turneth \sls (them)\sls*. 
\p  
\v 3 Chide thou not with a man, a jangler, \add [or Strive thou not with a tonguey man]\add*, and lay thou not trees into his fire. 
\p  
\v 4 Commune thou not with an untaught man, lest he speak evil of thy kindred. 
\p  
\v 5 Despise thou not a man turning away himself from sin, neither upbraid thou him \add [nor put thou reproof to him]\add*; have thou mind, that all we be in corruption. 
\p  
\v 6 Despise thou not a man in his eld \sls (age)\sls*; for why \sls (some)\sls* of us men wax eld \add [or old]\add*. 
\p  
\v 7 Do not thou make joy of \sls (or over)\sls* thine enemy \sls (being)\sls* dead, witting that all we die \sls (or knowing that we all die)\sls*, and will \sls (or desire)\sls* not \sls (to)\sls* come into joy \em of \+sls (or with)\+sls* our enemies\em*. 
\p  
\v 8 Despise thou not the telling of wise priests, and be thou conversant \add [or \+sls (al)\+sls*together dwell]\add* in the proverbs of them; for of \sls (or from)\sls* them thou shalt learn wisdom, and teaching of understanding, and to serve without \sls (com)\sls*plaint to great men. 
\p  
\v 9 The telling of elder men pass not \sls (by)\sls* thee; for they have learned of \sls (or from)\sls* their fathers. For of \sls (or from)\sls* them thou shalt learn understanding; and in the time of need thou shalt give \add [an]\add* answer. 
\p  
\v 10 Kindle thou not the coals of sinners, and reprove them; and be thou not burnt with the flame of \add [the]\add* fire of their sins. 
\p  
\v 11 Stand thou not against the face of a man full of despising \add [or of the strifeful]\add*; lest he sit as an espyer to thy mouth. 
\p  
\v 12 Do not thou lend to a man stronger than thou \add [or than thyself]\add*; that \sls (or but)\sls* if thou hast lent, have thou it as lost. 
\p  
\v 13 Promise thou not above \add [or over]\add* thy power or virtue; that \sls (or but)\sls* if thou hast promised, bethink thou as yielding, \em for thou art holden to do thy might\em*, \sls (\+em that is, thou art held to pay it back\+em*)\sls*. 
\p  
\v 14 Deem thou not against a judge; for he deemeth after that, that is just. 
\p  
\v 15 Go thou not in the way with an hardy man, lest peradventure he aggregate \sls (or bring together all)\sls* his evils in \sls (or on)\sls* thee; for he goeth after his \sls (own)\sls* will \sls (or desire)\sls*, and thou shalt perish together with \sls (him through)\sls* his folly. 
\p  
\v 16 Make thou not chiding \add [or jangling]\add* with a wrathful man, and go thou not into \sls (a)\sls* desert with an hardy man; for why blood, \em that is, shedding out of innocent blood\em*, is as nought before him, and where none help is, \sls (or where there is no help)\sls*, he shall hurtle thee down. 
\p  
\v 17 Have thou not counsel with fools; for they may not \sls (or be not able to)\sls* love, no but those things that please them\sls (selves)\sls*. 
\p  
\v 18 Make thou not a counsel before a stranger; for thou knowest not, what he shall bring forth. 
\p  
\v 19 Make not thine heart known to each man \add [or To all men thine heart open thou not]\add*, \em but only to a very \+sls (or a true)\+sls* friend, and proved\em*; lest peradventure he bring to thee false grace, \em that is, feigned friendship\em*, and despise thee. 
\c 9  
\cl CHAPTER 9 
\p  
\v 1 Love thou not jealously the woman of thy bosom \add [or Be thou not jealous to the woman of thy bosom]\add*; lest she show on thee the malice of evil doctrine. 
\p  
\v 2 Give thou not to a woman the power of \sls (or over)\sls* thy soul; lest she enter in thy virtue, and thou be shamed \add [or confounded]\add*. 
\p  
\v 3 Behold thou not a woman of many wills \sls (or desires)\sls*, \em that coveteth now this man, now that man\em*; lest peradventure thou fall into the snares of her. 
\p  
\v 4 Be thou not customable with a danceress, neither hire thou her; lest peradventure thou perish in the speedy work of her. 
\p  
\v 5 Behold thou not a virgin \add [or a maiden]\add*; lest peradventure thou be caused to stumble in \sls (or by)\sls* the fairness of her. 
\p  
\v 6 Give thou not thy soul to whores in anything; lest thou lose thee, and thy soul, and thine heritage, \sls (or lest thou destroy thyself, and thy soul, and thy inheritance)\sls*. 
\p  
\v 7 Do not thou behold about in the lanes of the city; neither err thou \sls (or wander)\sls* in the large streets thereof. \add [Do thou not behold about in the ways of the city; nor err thou about in the streets of it.]\add* 
\p  
\v 8 Turn away thy face from a woman well-arrayed; and behold thou not about the fairness of another or of another \em man’s wife\em*. Many men have perished for the fairness of a woman; and thereby covetousness \add [or lust]\add* burneth on high as fire or burneth out as fire. Each woman which is an whore, \em either customable to fornication\em*, shall be defouled as a fen, or a turd, in the way. Many men wondering on the fairness of an alien woman were made reprovable, for why the speech of her burneth on high as fire. 
\p  
\v 9 Sit thou not in any manner with an alien woman, neither rest thou with her on a bed \add [or nor lie thou with her upon the arm]\add*; and jangle \add [or strive]\add* thou not with her in wine, lest peradventure thine heart bow \add [or she bow down thine heart]\add* into her, and thou fall \add [or slide]\add* into perdition by thy blood. 
\p  
\v 10 Forsake thou not an eld \add [or old]\add* friend; for a new friend shall not be like him. New wine \em is\em*\sls (like)\sls* a new friend; \sls (after)\sls* it shall wax eld \add [or old]\add*, and \sls (then)\sls* thou shalt drink it with sweetness. 
\p  
\v 11 Covet thou not the glory and riches of a sinner; for thou knowest not, what destroying of him shall come. \add [Love thou not the glory and riches of the sinner; forsooth thou knowest not, what be to come \+sls (of)\+sls* the turning upside-down of him.]\add* 
\p  
\v 12 The wrong of unjust \add [or unright-wise]\add* men please not thee, and know thou that a wicked man \add [or the unpious]\add* shall not please till to hells, \add [or unto hell]\add*, \sls (or the grave)\sls*. 
\p  
\v 13 Be thou far from a man that hath power to slay, \em that is, from a cruel tyrant\em*, and thou shalt not have suspicion of the dread of death; and if thou nighest to him, do not thou do any trespass \add [or anything do amiss]\add*, lest peradventure he take away thy life. Know thou the communing of death; for thou shalt enter into the midst of snares, and thou shalt go on the armours, \add [or arms]\add*, \sls (or weapons)\sls* of them that sorrow. 
\p  
\v 14 By thy virtue, keep thee \sls (away)\sls* from thy neighbour \em that may speak against thee to a tyrant\em*; and treat thou with wise men and prudent men. 
\p  
\v 15 Just \add [or Rightwise]\add* men be guests, \em or meat\em*-frères, \sls (or meal companions)\sls* to thee; and thy glorying be in the dread of God. 
\p  
\v 16 And the thought of God be to thee in wit, \em that is, apply thy wit to think on God\em*; and all thy telling-\add [out]\add*\em be\em* in the behests \sls (or about the commands)\sls* of the Highest. 
\p  
\v 17 Works shall be praised in \sls (or from)\sls* the hand of craftsmen, and the prince of the people in the wisdom of his word; forsooth in the wit of elder men \add [or of elders]\add* a word \em shall be praised\em*. 
\p  
\v 18 A man, a jangler, \add [or a tonguey man]\add*, is dreadful \add [or fearful]\add* in his city; and a foolhardy man in his word shall be hateful. 
\c 10  
\cl CHAPTER 10 
\p  
\v 1 A wise judge shall deem his people; and the princehood of a witty, \sls (or a witting, or a knowing)\sls* man shall be steadfast \add [or be stable]\add*. 
\p  
\v 2 After the judge of the people, so and his ministers \add [or the servants of him]\add*; and what manner man is the governor of the city, such \em be\em* also men dwelling therein. 
\p  
\v 3 An unwise king shall lose \sls (or destroy)\sls* his people; and \sls (or but)\sls* cities shall be inhabited by the wit of prudent men. 
\p  
\v 4 The power of \sls (the)\sls* earth \em is\em* in the hand of God, and all the wickedness of heathen men \add [or the Gentiles]\add* is abominable; and he shall raise \sls (up)\sls* a profitable governor at a time \add [or in \+sls (due)\+sls* time]\add* on it. 
\p  
\v 5 The power of man \em is\em* in the hand of God; and he shall set his honour on the face of a wise man in the law \add [or the scribe]\add*. 
\p  
\v 6 Have thou not mind on all the wrong of the neighbour; and do thou nothing in the works of wrong-\sls (doing)\sls*. 
\p  
\v 7 Pride is hateful before God and men; and all the wickedness of \sls (the)\sls* heathen men \add [or \+sls (the)\+sls* Gentiles]\add*\em is\em* abominable. 
\p  
\v 8 A realm is translated, \em either taken away\em*, \add [or borne over]\add*, from a folk into folk for unrightfulnesses, and wrongs, and despisings, and diverse guiles, \add [or for unrightwisenesses, and wrongs, and strives, and diverse treacheries]\add*. 
\p  
\v 9 Nothing is curseder than an avarice man. What \sls (or Why)\sls* art thou proud, thou earth and ashes? Nothing is worse, than for to love money, \add [or Nothing is more wicked, than to love money]\add*; for why this man hath, yea, his soul set to \sls (or for)\sls* sale, for in his life he hath cast away his innerest things, \add [or this forsooth hath his soul sellable, or able to be sold, for in his life he threw away his \+sls (most)\+sls* inward things]\add*. 
\p  
\v 10 Each power \em is\em* short life \sls (or short-lived)\sls*; long sickness \add [or infirmity]\add* grieveth the leech \sls (or the physician)\sls*. A leech \sls (or The physician)\sls* cutteth away \add [or cutteth off]\add* short sickness; so and a king is today \add [or today is]\add*, and tomorrow he shall die. 
\p  
\v 11 Forsooth when a man shall die, he shall inherit serpents, and beasts, and worms. 
\p  
\v 12 The beginning of \add [the]\add* pride of man \em was\em* to be apostate \add [or to go backward]\add* from God; for his heart went away from him that made him. 
\p  
\v 13 For why pride is the beginning of all sin \add [or For the beginning of all sin is pride]\add*; he that holdeth it, shall be filled with cursings, and it shall destroy him into the end. Therefore the Lord hath shamed the covents, or convents, \sls (or the gatherings)\sls* of evil men, and hath destroyed them unto the end. 
\p  
\v 14 God destroyed the seats \sls (or the thrones)\sls* of proud dukes; and made mild men to sit for them. 
\p  
\v 15 God made dry the roots of proud folks; and planted meek men of those folks. 
\p  
\v 16 The Lord destroyed the lands of folks \add [or Gentiles]\add*; and lost those \add [or destroyed them]\add* unto the foundament \sls (or unto the foundation of the earth)\sls*. 
\p  
\v 17 He made dry \em the roots\em* of them, and lost \sls (or destroyed)\sls* them; and made the mind of them \sls (or their memory)\sls* to cease from the earth. God lost the mind of proud men; and left the mind of meek men in wit, \sls (or God destroyed the memory of the proud; but left the memory of the humble)\sls*. 
\p  
\v 18 Pride was not made to \sls (or for)\sls* men; neither wrathfulness to \sls (or for)\sls* the nation of women, \em that is, to all men born of women\em*. 
\p  
\v 19 This seed of men that dreadeth God, shall be honoured; but this seed shall be dishonoured, that over-pass-eth \sls (or that passeth over)\sls* the commandments of the Lord. 
\p  
\v 20 In the midst of brethren the governor of them \em is\em* in honour; and they that dread God, shall be in his eyes, \em that is, shall be honourable, and please him\em*. 
\p  
\v 21 (This verse is omitted in the original text.) 
\p  
\v 22 The glory of rich men honoured and of poor men is the dread of God. 
\p  
\v 23 Do not thou despise a just \add [or the rightwise]\add* poor man; and do not thou magnify a rich sinful man. 
\p  
\v 24 The judge is great, and he is mighty in honour; and \sls (or but)\sls* he is not greater than that man that dread-eth God. \add [Great is a judge, and the mighty is in worship; and \+sls (or but)\+sls* he is not more than he that dreadeth God.]\add* 
\p  
\v 25 Free children serve a witty, \sls (or a witting, or a knowing)\sls* servant; and a prudent man and learned shall not grutch \sls (or grumble)\sls*, \em when he is\em* blamed, and an uncunning, \sls (or an unknowing, or an ignorant)\sls* man shall not be honored. 
\p  
\v 26 Do not thou enhance thee in thy work to be done; and do not thou be slow \add [or despair]\add* in the time of anguish. 
\p  
\v 27 He is better that worketh, and hath plenty \add [or aboundeth]\add* in all things, than he that hath glory, \sls (or boasteth)\sls*, and needeth bread. 
\p  
\v 28 Son, keep thy soul in mildness \sls (or in meekness)\sls*, \em that holdeth due measure, and refraineth \+sls (from)\+sls* excess\em*; and give thou honour to it, after his \sls (or its)\sls* merit. 
\p  
\v 29 Who shall justify him that sinneth against his \sls (own)\sls* soul? and who shall honour him that dishonoureth his \sls (own)\sls* soul? 
\p  
\v 30 A poor man hath glory by his learning and dread; and there is a man that is honoured for his chattel \add [or his substance]\add*. 
\p  
\v 31 Forsooth if a man hath glory in poverty, how much more in chattel \add [or substance]\add*? and he that hath glory in chattel \add [or in substance]\add*, dread poverty. 
\c 11  
\cl CHAPTER 11 
\p  
\v 1 The wisdom of a man made meek shall enhance his head; and shall make him to sit in the midst of great men. 
\p  
\v 2 Praise thou not a man in \sls (or for)\sls* his fairness; neither despise thou a man in \sls (or for)\sls* his sight. 
\p  
\v 3 A bee is little among birds; and his fruit hath the beginning of sweet-ness. 
\p  
\v 4 Have thou never glory in cloth-ing, and be thou not enhanced \sls (or exalted)\sls* in the day of thine honour; for why the works of the Highest alone \em be\em* wonderful, and his works \em be\em* glorious, and hid, and unseen. 
\p  
\v 5 Many tyrants have set in \sls (or upon a)\sls* throne; and a man of whom was no supposing bare the diadem \sls (or crown)\sls*. 
\p  
\v 6 Many mighty men be oppressed strongly; and glorious men be given into the hands of other men. \add [Many mighty men be oppressed greatly; and the glorious be taken into the hands of other men.]\add* 
\p  
\v 7 Before that thou ask, blame thou not any man; and when thou hast asked, blame thou justly \add [or chastise thou rightly]\add*. 
\p  
\v 8 Before that thou hear, answer thou not a word; and in the midst of elder men add thou not to speak. 
\p  
\v 9 Strive thou not, of \sls (or in)\sls* that thing that dis-easeth \add [or grieveth]\add* not thee; and stand thou not in the doom of sins \add [or \+sls (with)\+sls* sinners]\add*. 
\p  
\v 10 Son, thy deeds be not in many things; and if thou art rich, thou shalt not be without part of guilt. For if thou pursuest \add [or shalt follow]\add*\sls (after)\sls*, thou shalt not \add [over]\add*-take; and thou shalt not escape, if thou runnest before. 
\p  
\v 11 There is a man travailing, and hast\sls (en)\sls*ing, and sorrowing, and unpious; and by so much the more he shall not have plenty \add [or he shall not abound]\add*. 
\p  
\v 12 There is a man fade, \em that is, feeble, failing more than others\em*, needy of recovering, failing more in virtue, and plenteous in poverty; and the eye of God beheld him in good, and raised him \sls (up)\sls* from his lowness, \add [There is a man withered, needing recovering, more failing in virtue, and abounding in poorness; and the eye of God beheld him in good, and reared him \+sls (up)\+sls* from his lowness;]\add* 
\p  
\v 13 and enhanced his head; and many men wondered \add [or marvelled]\add* in \sls (or about)\sls* him, and honoured \add [or worshipped]\add* God. 
\p  
\v 14 Goods and evils, \em that is, prosperities and adversities\em*, life and death, poverty and honesty \sls (or honours or riches)\sls*, be of \sls (or from)\sls* God. 
\p  
\v 15 Wisdom, and learning, and cunning \sls (or knowing)\sls* of the law \em be\em* with the Lord; love \add [or loving]\add* and the ways of good men \em be\em* at, \add [or with]\add*, \sls (or from)\sls* him. 
\p  
\v 16 Error and darknesses be made together to \sls (or with)\sls* sinners; forsooth they that make full out joy in evil, wax eld \add [or old]\add* together into evils. 
\p  
\v 17 The gift of God dwelleth to \sls (or with)\sls* just \add [or rightwise]\add* men; and \sls (the)\sls* increasings of him shall have prosperities \add [into]\add* without end. 
\p  
\v 18 \em Some\em* man there is made rich in doing scarcely \add [or \+sls (in)\+sls* scarcely doing]\add*, and this \em is\em* the part of his meed, 
\p  
\v 19 in that that he saith, I have found rest to \sls (or for)\sls* me, and now I alone shall eat of my goods. And he know not that time passeth him, and death nigheth \sls (or approacheth)\sls*, and he shall leave all things to other men, and shall die \add [or and die]\add*. 
\p  
\v 20 Stand thou in thy testament, and speak thou \sls (al)\sls*together in it; and wax thou eld \add [or old]\add* in the work of thy behests \sls (or of thy commands)\sls*. 
\p  
\v 21 Dwell \add [or Abide]\add* thou not in the works of sinners; but trust thou in God, and dwell in thy place. For it is easy in the eyes of God, suddenly to make honest \sls (or rich)\sls* a poor man. 
\p  
\v 22 The blessing of God hast\sls (en)\sls*eth into the meed of a just man \add [or the rightwise]\add*; and the going forth of him maketh fruit in swift honour. 
\p  
\v 23 Say thou not, What is need to me \sls (or What do I need)\sls*? and what goods \sls (or good things)\sls* shall be \sls (for)\sls* me hereafter? 
\p  
\v 24 Say thou not, I am sufficient, and what shall I be made worse hereafter? 
\p  
\v 25 In the day of goods \sls (or good things)\sls*, be thou not unmindful of evils, and in the day of evils, be thou not unmindful of goods \sls (or good things)\sls*; \sls (On a good day do not forget the bad days, and on a bad day do not forget the good days;)\sls* 
\p  
\v 26 for it is easy before God to yield in the day of death, to each man after his ways. 
\p  
\v 27 The malice of one hour maketh forgetting of most lechery; and in the end of a man \em is\em* making naked of his works. 
\p  
\v 28 Praise thou not any man before his death; for why a man is known in \sls (or by)\sls* his sons. 
\p  
\v 29 Bring thou not each man into thine house; for why many treasons be of a guileful man. 
\p  
\v 30 For why as the entrails of stinking things break out, and as a partridge is led into a trap, \em either \+sls (a)\+sls* net\em*, and as a capret is led into a snare, so and the heart of proud men; and as a behold-er seeing the fall of his neighbour. 
\p  
\v 31 For he turneth goods \add [or good things]\add* into evils, and setteth treasons, and putteth a wem, \sls (or a spot, or a blemish)\sls* on chosen men. 
\p  
\v 32 Fire is increased of a sparkle \sls (or by a spark)\sls*, and blood is increased of \sls (or by)\sls* a guileful \sls (or treacherous)\sls* man; for why a sinful man setteth treason \add [or waiteth]\add* to \sls (or lieth in wait for)\sls* blood. 
\p  
\v 33 Take heed to thee from a guileful man, for he maketh \add [or forgeth]\add* evils; lest peradventure he bring in on thee scorning without end. 
\p  
\v 34 Receive thou an alien to thee, and he shall destroy thee in a whirl-wind, and he shall make thee alien \sls (or alienated)\sls* from thine own ways. 
\c 12  
\cl CHAPTER 12 
\p  
\v 1 If thou doest well, know thou to whom thou doest \sls (it)\sls*; and much grace shall be to \add [or there shall be much grace in]\add* thy goods \sls (or thy good doings)\sls*. 
\p  
\v 2 Do thou well to a just man \add [or to the rightwise]\add*, and thou shalt find great yielding; though not \add [or if not]\add* of \sls (or from)\sls* him, certainly of \sls (or from)\sls* the Lord. 
\p  
\v 3 It is not well to him that is customable \add [or is busy]\add* in evils, and to him that giveth not alms; for why the Highest both hateth sinners, and doeth mercy to them that do penance. 
\p  
\v 4 Give thou to a merciful man \add [or to the merciful]\add*, and receive thou not a sinner, \em that is, \+sls (one)\+sls* obstinate in sins; God\em* shall yield vengeance both to unfaithful men and to sinners, keep-ing them in the day of vengeance. Give thou to a good man, and receive thou not a sinner. 
\p  
\v 5 Do thou good \add [or well]\add* to a meek man, and give thou not to an unpious man, \em that is, \+sls (one)\+sls* obstinate in sin\em*; forbid thou \sls (thyself)\sls* to give loaves to him, lest in those \add [or \+sls (with)\+sls* them]\add*, he be\sls (come)\sls* mightier than thou. For \sls (then)\sls* thou shalt find double evils in all goods, whichever \add [or whatever]\add* thou doest to \sls (or for)\sls* him; 
\p  
\v 6 for why the Highest both hateth sinners, and shall yield vengeance to unfaithful men \add [or the unpious]\add*. 
\p  
\v 7 (This verse is omitted in the original text.) 
\p  
\v 8 A friend shall not be known in goods \sls (or in good times)\sls*, and an enemy shall not be hid in evils, \em that is, adversities\em*. 
\p  
\v 9 In the goods \sls (or the good times)\sls* of a man, his enemies \em be sorry\em*; and a friend is known in the sorrow and malice of him, \em that is, in \+sls (the)\+sls* adversity of him\em*. 
\p  
\v 10 Believe thou never to \add [or Not trust]\add* thine enemy; for his wickedness rusteth as \sls (or like)\sls* iron. 
\p  
\v 11 Though he be made meek, and go low, cast away thy soul \add [or throw away thy will]\add*, and keep thee from him. 
\p  
\v 12 Set thou not him beside thee, neither sit he at thy right side, lest he turn \sls (against thee)\sls*, and stand in thy place; lest peradventure he turn into thy place, and inquire \sls (about)\sls* thy chair, and in \sls (or at)\sls* the last time thou know \sls (or remember)\sls* my words, and be pricked in \sls (or with)\sls* my words. 
\p  
\v 13 Who shall do medicine to an enchanter smitten of \sls (or by)\sls* a serpent, and to all men that nigh to \sls (or approach)\sls* beasts, 
\p  
\v 14 and \em to him\em* that goeth with an evil man, and is wrapped \sls (up)\sls* in the sins of him? 
\p  
\v 15 In one hour he shall dwell with thee; soothly if thou bowest away, he shall not bear up. 
\p  
\v 16 The enemy maketh sweet in \sls (or with)\sls* his lips, and in his heart he setteth treason to overturn thee into the ditch. The enemy weepeth in \sls (or with)\sls* his eyes; and \sls (or but)\sls* if he find-eth \sls (the)\sls* time, he shall not be \add [full]\add*-filled of \sls (or with enough)\sls* blood. 
\p  
\v 17 If evils befall to thee, thou shalt find him the former \sls (or the first)\sls* there. The enemy shall weep before thine eyes, and he as helping shall under-mine thy feet. 
\p  
\v 18 He shall stir \add [or move]\add* his head, and he shall beat, \add [or flap, \+sls (or clap)\+sls* for joy]\add* with \sls (his)\sls* hand\sls (s)\sls*; and he shall speak privily many \em evils\em* of \sls (or about)\sls* thee, and shall change his cheer \sls (or his face)\sls*. 
\c 13  
\cl CHAPTER 13 
\p  
\v 1 He that toucheth pitch, shall be defouled of \sls (or by)\sls* it; and he that communeth with a proud man, shall \sls (be)\sls* clothe\sls (d)\sls*\sls (with)\sls*\add [or in]\add* pride\f + \fr 13:1 \ft \+em For why men be inclined to undue desire of (or for) their own excellence, wherein pride standeth, wherefore it cleaveth lightly (or easily) to a man\+em*.\f*. 
\p  
\v 2 He raiseth \add [or taketh]\add* a weight \add [up]\add* on himself, that communeth with a more honest \sls (or more honoured)\sls* man than himself; and be thou not fellow to a man richer than thou. What \sls (or How)\sls* shall a caldron commune to \sls (or with)\sls* a pot? for when those hurtle themselves together, \em the pot\em* shall be broken. 
\p  
\v 3 A rich man shall do unjustly, and shall gnash, \em as ready yet to do worse\em*; but a poor man hurt shall be still \add [or shall hold his peace]\add*. 
\p  
\v 4 If thou givest, he shall take \sls (from)\sls* thee; and if thou hast not, he shall forsake thee. 
\p  
\v 5 If thou hast, he shall live together with thee, and shall make thee void; and he shall not have sorrow on thee. 
\p  
\v 6 If thou art needful \add [or necessary]\add* to him, he shall deceive \add [or beguile]\add* thee; and he shall flatter, and shall give hope, telling to thee all goods \sls (or every good thing)\sls*; and shall say, What is need to thee \add [or What need is to thee]\add*? 
\p  
\v 7 And he shall shame thee in his meats, till he annihilate or extinguish thee twice and thrice, and at the last he shall scorn thee; afterward he shall see, and shall forsake thee, and he shall move his head to \sls (or at)\sls* thee. Be thou made meek to God, and abide thou his hands. 
\p  
\v 8 Take heed, lest thou be deceived, and be made low in folly. Do not thou be low in thy wisdom, lest thou be made low, and be deceived into folly. 
\p  
\v 9 When thou art called of \sls (or by)\sls* a mightier man, go thou away; for by this he shall more call thee. 
\p  
\v 10 Be thou not greatly pressing, lest thou be hurtled down; and be thou not far from him, lest thou go into forgetting. 
\p  
\v 11 Withhold thou not to speak with him evenly, \em that is, speak thou to him without reverence\em*, and believe thou not to his many words; for of \sls (or with)\sls* much speech he shall tempt thee, and he shall laugh privily, and shall ask thee of \sls (or about)\sls* thine hid things. 
\p  
\v 12 His cruel soul shall keep thy words, and he shall not spare of \add [or from]\add* malice, and of \add [or from]\add* bonds. 
\p  
\v 13 Beware to thee, and take heed diligently to thine hearing; for thou goest with thy destroying. But thou hearing those things, see as in sleep, and thou shalt wake. 
\p  
\v 14 In all thy life love thou God, and inwardly call thou him in thine health, \em that is, for thine health \+sls (or thy deliverance), (both)\+sls* temporal and everlasting\em*. 
\p  
\v 15 Each beast loveth \em a beast\em* like itself; so and each man \em oweth \+sls (or ought)\+sls* to love\em* his neighbour. 
\p  
\v 16 Each flesh shall be joined to \em flesh\em* like itself, and each man shall be fellowshipped to \em a man\em* like himself. 
\p  
\v 17 As a wolf shall commune some-time with a lamb, so a sinner with a just \add [or a rightwise]\add* man. 
\p  
\v 18 What communing \add [or communi-cation]\add*\em is\em* of an holy man to \sls (or with)\sls* a dog? either what good part \em is\em* of a rich man to \sls (or with)\sls* a poor man? 
\p  
\v 19 The hunting of a lion \em is\em* a wild ass in \sls (the)\sls* desert \add [or wilderness]\add*; so \sls (in)\sls* the pastures of rich men be poor men. 
\p  
\v 20 And as meekness is \sls (an)\sls* abomi-nation to a proud man, so and a poor man is \sls (an)\sls* abomination of \sls (or to)\sls* a rich man. 
\p  
\v 21 A rich man moved, \em that is, disturbed, either hurled\em*, is confirmed of \sls (or by)\sls* his friends; but a meek man, when he falleth, shall be cast \add [or put]\add* out, yea, of \sls (his)\sls* known men \sls (or by his friends)\sls*. 
\p  
\v 22 Many recoverers \sls (or helpers)\sls* be to a rich man deceived; he spake proudly, and they justified him. \sls (But)\sls* A meek man is deceived, furthermore also he is reproved; he spake wisely, and no place was given to him. 
\p  
\v 23 The rich man spake, and all men were still \add [or held their peace]\add*; and they shall bring \add [or shall bear]\add* his word till to the clouds. \sls (But)\sls* A poor man spake, and they say, Who is this? and if he offendeth \sls (or if he stumble)\sls*, they shall destroy him. 
\p  
\v 24 Chattel \add [or substance]\add* is good \em to him\em*, to whom is no sin in conscience; and the worst poverty is in the mouth of a wicked man \add [or the unpious]\add*. 
\p  
\v 25 The heart of a man changeth his face, either in good either in evil. Of hard and with travail, thou shalt find the step of a good heart, and a good face \sls (together)\sls*. 
\p  
\v 26 (This verse is omitted in the original text.) 
\c 14  
\cl CHAPTER 14 
\p  
\v 1 Blessed \em is\em* the man, that stood not by the word\sls (s)\sls* of \add [or from]\add* his mouth, and was not pricked in \sls (or with)\sls* the sorrow of trespass. 
\p  
\v 2 \em He is\em* blessed, that hath not sorrow of \sls (or in)\sls* his soul, and falleth not down \add [or away]\add* from his hope. 
\p  
\v 3 Chattel, \em that is, riches\em*, is without reason to a covetous man, and hard niggard, \sls (or stingy, or miserly)\sls*; and whereto \em is\em* gold to an envious man? 
\p  
\v 4 He that gathereth of his will un-justly, gathereth to \sls (or for)\sls* other men; and another man shall make waste \add [or do lechery]\add* in \sls (or with)\sls* his goods. 
\p  
\v 5 To what other man shall he be good, which is wicked to himself? and he shall not be merry in his goods. 
\p  
\v 6 Nothing is worse, than he that hath envy to himself; and this is the yielding of his malice. 
\p  
\v 7 And if he doeth good, he doeth \sls (it)\sls* unwittingly, and not willfully \sls (or willingly)\sls*; and at the last he showeth his malice. 
\p  
\v 8 The eye of an envious man is wicked, and turning away the face, and despising his soul. 
\p  
\v 9 The eye of the covetous man \em is\em* never filled; he shall not be filled into the part of wickedness, till he perform unrightfulness \add [or unrightwiseness]\add*, and make dry his soul. 
\p  
\v 10 An evil eye to evils, and the needy man shall not be filled of \add [or with]\add* bread; and he shall be in sorrow on \sls (or at)\sls* his table. 
\p  
\v 11 Son, if thou hast, do well with thyself, and offer thou worthy offerings to God. 
\p  
\v 12 Be thou mindful that death shall not tarry, and the testament of hells \add [or of hell]\add*, \em that is, the ordinance of God, of the death of each man\em*, which is showed to thee; for why the testament of this world shall die by death. 
\p  
\v 13 Before \sls (thy)\sls* death do thou good to \sls (or for)\sls* thy friend, and by thy mights \add [or strengths]\add* stretch thou forth, and give to a poor man. 
\p  
\v 14 Be thou not deceived \add [or beguiled]\add* of \sls (or from)\sls* a good day, and a little part of a good day pass not thee \sls (unfulfilled or unappreciated)\sls*. 
\p  
\v 15 Whether thou shalt not leave to other men thy sorrows, and \add [thy]\add* travails? 
\p  
\v 16 In the parting of lot give thou, and take, and justify thy soul. 
\p  
\v 17 Before thy death work thou rightfulness \add [or rightwiseness]\add*; for at hells, \add [or hell]\add*, \sls (or in the grave)\sls*, it is not to find meat. 
\p  
\v 18 Each man shall wax eld \add [or old]\add* as hay, and as a leaf bringing fruit in a green tree. Others be engendered, and others be cast \add [or fall]\add* down; so the generation of flesh and blood, another is ended, and another is born. 
\p  
\v 19 Each corruptible work shall fail in the end; and he that worketh it, shall go with it. And all \add [or each]\add* chosen work shall be justified; and he that worketh it, shall be honoured in \sls (or by)\sls* it. 
\p  
\v 20 Blessed \em is\em* the man, that shall dwell in wisdom, and that shall be-think in rightfulness \add [or rightwiseness]\add*, and shall think in wit \sls (about)\sls* the beholding of God. 
\p  
\v 21 Which \add [or Who]\add* thinketh out, \em either findeth out\em*, the ways of him in his heart, and shall be understanding in the hid things of him; 
\p  
\v 22 going as a searcher after it, and standing in the ways of it. 
\p  
\v 23 Which beholdeth by the windows thereof, and heareth in \sls (or at)\sls* the gates thereof; \add [Who beholdeth by the windows of it, and in the gates of it is hearing;]\add* 
\p  
\v 24 which \add [or who]\add* resteth nigh the house thereof, and setteth a stake in the walls thereof. \add [who resteth beside the house of it, and in the walls of it pitcheth a pale.]\add* 
\p  
\v 25 He shall set his little house at the hands of him, and goods \sls (or good things)\sls* shall rest in his little house, by \sls (the)\sls* enduring of the world; 
\p  
\v 26 he shall set his sons under the covering thereof \add [or the roof of it]\add*, and he shall dwell under the boughs \add [or branches]\add* thereof; 
\p  
\v 27 he shall be covered under the covering thereof \add [or the roof of it]\add* from heat, and he shall rest in the glory thereof. 
\c 15  
\cl CHAPTER 15 
\p  
\v 1 He that dreadeth God, shall do good \em works\em*; and he that holdeth rightfulness \add [or rightwiseness]\add*, shall take \sls (or receive)\sls* it, \em that is, wisdom\em*. 
\p  
\v 2 And it as a mother honoured shall meet him, and as a woman from virginity \add [or from maidenhood]\add* it shall take \sls (or shall receive)\sls* him. 
\p  
\v 3 It shall feed him with the bread of life, and of understanding; and it shall give drink to him with water of heal\sls (th)\sls*ful \add [or of wholesome]\add* wisdom; 
\p  
\v 4 it shall be made steadfast in him, and he shall not be bowed \sls (or turned away)\sls*\em from the evenness of rightfulness\em*. And it shall hold him, and he shall not be shamed \add [or confounded]\add*; 
\p  
\v 5 and it shall enhance him at \sls (or it shall exalt him above)\sls* his neighbours. And in the midst of the church he \add [or it]\add* shall open his mouth; and \em God\em* shall fill him with the spirit of wisdom, and of understanding, and shall clothe him with the stole of glory. 
\p  
\v 6 \em God\em* shall treasure on him mirth, and full out joying; and shall inherit him with \sls (an)\sls* everlasting name. 
\p  
\v 7 Fond men \add [or Men fools]\add* shall not take that \em wisdom\em*, and \sls (or but)\sls* witty men shall meet \sls (with)\sls* it. \sls (Yea)\sls*, Fond men \add [or Men fools]\add* shall not see it; 
\p  
\v 8 for why it goeth away far from pride, and guile \add [or treachery]\add*. Men leasing-mongers \add [or liars]\add* shall not be mindful thereof, and soothfast men be found therein; and shall have pros-perity unto the beholding of God. 
\p  
\v 9 Praising is not fair in the mouth of a sinner, for he is not sent of the Lord \sls (or it was not sent to him from the Lord)\sls*. 
\p  
\v 10 For why wisdom went forth from God; forsooth praising shall stand nigh \sls (to)\sls* the wisdom of God, and it shall be plenteous \add [or abound]\add* in a faithful mouth, and the Lord shall give it to him. 
\p  
\v 11 Say thou not, It goeth away by God; for why do thou not those things \sls (or why do thou do those things)\sls*, which \em God\em* hateth. \add [Thou shalt not say, By God it is away; those things forsooth it hateth, thou shalt not do.]\add* 
\p  
\v 12 Say thou not, He made me for to err; for why wicked \add [or unpious]\add* men be not needful to him. 
\p  
\v 13 The Lord hateth all cursedness of error, and it \sls (also)\sls* shall not be amiable \add [or loveful]\add* to them, that dread him. 
\p  
\v 14 At the beginning God made \add [or ordained]\add* man, and left him \sls (or let him go)\sls* in the hand of his counsel. 
\p  
\v 15 He added his commandments, and laws; if thou wilt keep the commandments, those \add [or they]\add* shall keep thee, and keep pleasant \sls (or pleasing)\sls* faith without end. 
\p  
\v 16 He hath set to thee water and fire; \sls (ad)\sls*dress, \sls (or direct)\sls*, \add [or put forth]\add* thine hand to that, that thou wilt. 
\p  
\v 17 Before man is life and death, good and evil; that, that pleaseth him, shall be given to him. 
\p  
\v 18 For why the wisdom of God is much, and he is strong in power, and seeth all men without ceasing. 
\p  
\v 19 The eyes of the Lord \em be\em* to them, that dread him; and he knoweth all the travail \add [or all the work]\add* of man. 
\p  
\v 20 He commanded not to any man to do wickedly \add [or unpiously]\add*; and he gave not to any man space to do sin. 
\c 16  
\cl CHAPTER 16 
\p  
\v 1 For he coveteth not the multitude of sons unfaithful and unprofitable. 
\p  
\v 2 Be thou not glad in wicked \add [or unpious]\add* sons, if they be multiplied; neither delight thou on \sls (or in)\sls* them, if the dread of God is not in them. 
\p  
\v 3 Believe thou not to \sls (or in)\sls* the life of them, and behold thou not into the travails of them. For why better is one dreading God, than a thousand wicked \add [or unpious]\add* sons. And it is more profitable to die without sons, than to leave wicked \add [or unpious]\add* sons. 
\p  
\v 4 A country shall be inhabited of \sls (or by)\sls* one witty man; and it shall be made \sls (a)\sls* desert of \sls (or by)\sls* three wicked men. 
\p  
\v 5 Mine eye saw many other things, and mine ear heard stronger things than these. 
\p  
\v 6 Fire shall burn on high in the synagogue of sinners, and ire shall burn on high in a folk unbelieveful. 
\p  
\v 7 Eld \add [or Old]\add* giants that were destroyed, trusting on their virtue \sls (or in their own strength)\sls*, prayed not for their sins; 
\p  
\v 8 and \em God\em* spared not the pilgrim-age of them, \em that is, their life, which is a pilgrimage \+sls (here)\+sls* on earth\em*, but he killed \add [or smote]\add* them, and cursed them, for the pride of their word\sls (s)\sls*. 
\p  
\v 9 He had not mercy on them, and he lost \add [or destroying]\add* all the folk enhancing \sls (or exalting)\sls* themselves in their sins. 
\p  
\v 10 And as \em he killed\em* six hundred thousand of footmen, that were gather-ed together in the hardness of their heart\sls (s)\sls*, \em that is, rebelty \+sls (or in rebellion)\+sls* against God\em*; 
\p  
\v 11 and if one had been hard-nolled, \sls (it is a)\sls* wonder if he had been guilt-less. For why mercy and ire \add [or wrath]\add* is with him; prayer is mighty, and shedding out ire \add [or pouring out wrath]\add*. 
\p  
\v 12 By, \add [or After]\add*, \sls (or According to)\sls* his mercy, so \em is\em* the chastising of each man; he is deemed by, \add [or he deemeth a man after]\add*, \sls (or according to)\sls* his works. 
\p  
\v 13 A sinner in \sls (or with his)\sls* raven shall not escape; and the sufferance of him that doeth mercy shall not tarry. 
\p  
\v 14 All mercy shall make \sls (a)\sls* place to \sls (or for)\sls* each man, after the merit of his works, and after the understanding of his pilgrimage. 
\p  
\v 15 (This verse is omitted in the original text.) 
\p  
\v 16 (This verse is omitted in the original text.) 
\p  
\v 17 Say thou not, I shall be hid from God; and from the highest, \em that is, heaven\em*, who shall have mind on me? \em Say thou not\em*, I shall not be known in \sls (such)\sls* a great \sls (number of)\sls* people; for why which \add [or what]\add* is my soul in so great a \sls (number of)\sls* creature\sls (s)\sls*? 
\p  
\v 18 Lo! heaven, and the heavens of heavens, the great ocean, \add [or \+sls (the)\+sls* deepness]\add*, and all \add [the]\add* earth, and those things that be in those \add [or in them]\add*, shall be moved in his sight \sls (or by his presence)\sls*; 
\p  
\v 19 \sls (the)\sls* mountains \sls (al)\sls*together, and \sls (the)\sls* little hills, and the foundaments \sls (or the foundations)\sls* of \sls (the)\sls* earth; and when God beholdeth those \add [or them]\add*, those \add [or they]\add* shall be shaken \sls (al)\sls*to-gether with trembling. 
\p  
\v 20 And in all these things the heart is unwise, and \sls (or but)\sls* each heart is understood of \sls (or by)\sls* him. And \sls (or But)\sls* who understandeth his ways? 
\p  
\v 21 and a tempest, which the eye of man saw not? For why full many works of him be in hid things, 
\p  
\v 22 but who shall tell out the works of his rightfulness, either \add [or]\add* who shall suffer \sls (them)\sls*? For why the testament is far from some men; and the asking of men is in the ending. 
\p  
\v 23 He that is made little in heart, thinketh \sls (upon)\sls* vain things; and a man unprudent and a fool thinketh \sls (upon)\sls* fond things \add [or follies]\add*. 
\p  
\v 24 Son, hear thou me, and learn thou teaching \add [or discipline]\add* of wit, and give thou attention to my words in thine heart; 
\p  
\v 25 and I shall say teaching in equity, and I shall seek to tell out wisdom. And give thou attention to my words in thine heart; and I say in equity of spirit the virtues, which God hath set on his works at the beginning \add [or that God put into his works from the beginning]\add*, and in truth I tell out the cunning \sls (or the knowing)\sls* of him. 
\p  
\v 26 In the doom of God \em be\em* his works from the beginning; and in the ordinance of those, he parted \add [or severed]\add* the parts of those \add [or them]\add*, and \em he parted\em* the beginnings of those \add [or them]\add* in his folks. 
\p  
\v 27 He adorned without end the works of them; they hungered not, neither travailed, and they ceased not of their works. 
\p  
\v 28 Each shall not make strait \add [or anguish]\add* the next to him, till into without end. Be thou not unbelieve-ful to the word of him. 
\p  
\v 29 After these things God beheld into the earth, and filled it with his goods \sls (or his good things)\sls*. 
\p  
\v 30 Forsooth the soul of each living thing told before his face; and that \em soul is\em* again the turning again of those things. 
\c 17  
\cl CHAPTER 17 
\p  
\v 1 God formed man \sls (out)\sls* of \sls (the)\sls* earth; and after his image he made man. 
\p  
\v 2 And again he turned man into that \em image\em*; and after himself he clothed him with virtue, \sls (or with power, or strength)\sls*. 
\p  
\v 3 He gave to him the number of days, and \sls (a short)\sls* time; and he gave to him power of \sls (or over)\sls* those things that be on \sls (the)\sls* earth. 
\p  
\v 4 He setted \add [or put]\add* the dread of man on all flesh, and he was lord of beasts and of flying birds \add [or fowls]\add*. 
\p  
\v 5 He formed of man an help like him\add [self]\add*; 
\p  
\v 6 he gave to them counsel, and tongue, and eyes, and ears, and heart to think out \sls (things)\sls*; and he filled them with \add [the]\add* teaching \add [or discipline]\add* of understanding. 
\p  
\v 7 He made to them the cunning \sls (or the knowing)\sls* of spirit, he filled the heart of them with wit \sls (or understand-ing)\sls*; and he showed to them evils and goods. 
\p  
\v 8 He setted the eye of them \sls (or He set his eye)\sls* on the hearts of them, to show to them the great things of his works, \sls (so)\sls* that they praise \sls (al)\sls*to-gether the name of hallowing; 
\p  
\v 9 and to have glory in his marvels \add [or to glory in the marvellous things of him]\add*, \sls (so)\sls* that they tell out the great things of his works. 
\p  
\v 10 (This verse is omitted in the original text.) 
\p  
\v 11 He added to them teaching; and he inherited them with the law of life. 
\p  
\v 12 He ordained an everlasting testament \sls (or covenant)\sls* with them; and he showed to them his rightfulness, and dooms. 
\p  
\v 13 And the eye\sls (s)\sls* of them saw the great things of his honour, and the ears of them heard the honour of \sls (his)\sls* voice; 
\p  
\v 14 and he said to them, Take heed to you from all wicked thing. And he commanded to them, to each man of his neighbour. 
\p  
\v 15 The ways of them be ever before him; those \add [or they]\add* be not hid from his eyes. 
\p  
\v 16 (This verse is omitted in the original text.) 
\p  
\v 17 On each folk he made sovereign a governor; and Israel was made the open part of God. 
\p  
\v 18 (This verse is omitted in the original text.) 
\p  
\v 19 And all the works of them \em be\em* as the sun in the sight of God; and his eyes behold without ceasing in \sls (or on)\sls* the ways of them. 
\p  
\v 20 Testaments were not hid from the wickedness of them; and all the wickednesses of them \em were\em* in the sight of God. 
\p  
\v 21 (This verse is omitted in the original text.) 
\p  
\v 22 The alms of a man \em is\em* as a bag \add [or a little sack]\add* with him, and it shall keep the grace of a man as the apple of the eye; 
\p  
\v 23 and afterward \em man\em* shall rise again, and it shall yield to them a yielding, to each \em man\em* into \sls (or onto)\sls* the head of them; and \sls (it)\sls* shall \sls (re)\sls*turn into the lower parts of \sls (the)\sls* earth. 
\p  
\v 24 Forsooth it gave to men repenting the way of rightfulness \add [or rightwise-ness]\add*, and confirmed men failing to suffer, and ordained to them the part of truth. 
\p  
\v 25 \sls (Re)\sls*turn thou to the Lord, and forsake thy sins; pray thou before the face of the Lord, and make thou less hurtings \add [or the occasions of guilts]\add*. 
\p  
\v 26 Turn thou again to the Lord, and turn thou away from thine unrightful-ness \add [or unrightwiseness]\add*, and hate thou greatly cursing, \em that is, cursed sin\em*. 
\p  
\v 27 And know thou the rightfulnesses \add [or rightwisenesses]\add*, and \sls (the)\sls* dooms of God; and stand thou in the part of good purpose, and of prayer of \sls (or to)\sls* the highest God. Go thou into the parts of the holy world, with men living \add [or with men alive]\add*, and giving acknowledging to God. 
\p  
\v 28 Dwell thou not in the error of wicked men. Acknowledge thou before death; acknowledging \add [or confession]\add* perisheth from a dead man, as nothing. Living thou shalt acknowl-edge, living and whole thou shalt acknowledge, and shalt praise God; and thou shalt have glory in the merciful doings of him. 
\p  
\v 29 The mercy of God \em is\em* full great, and his help to them that convert to him. \add [How great the mercy of God, and the mitigation, or help, of him to men converting to him.]\add* 
\p  
\v 30 For why not all things may be or be able to be in men; for why the son of man is not undeadly \sls (or immortal)\sls*, and malices pleased into vanity. 
\p  
\v 31 What \em is\em* clearer \add [or more clear]\add* than the sun? and this shall fail; either \add [or]\add* what \em is\em* worse than that, that flesh and blood thought out? and of this he shall be reproved. 
\p  
\v 32 He beholdeth the virtue of \add [the]\add* highness of heaven; and all men \em be\em*\sls (but)\sls* earth and ashes. 
\c 18  
\cl CHAPTER 18 
\p  
\v 1 He that liveth without beginning and end, made \sls (out)\sls* of nought all things together; 
\p  
\v 2 God alone shall be justified, 
\p  
\v 3 and he dwelleth a King unover-come \add [or unvanquished]\add* without end. 
\p  
\v 4 Who shall suffice to tell out his works? for why who shall seek \sls (out)\sls* the great \add [worthy]\add* things of him? 
\p  
\v 5 But who shall tell out the virtue \sls (or the strength)\sls* of his greatness? either \add [or]\add* who shall lay to for to tell out his mercy? 
\p  
\v 6 It is not to make less, neither to lay to; neither it is to find the great things of God. \add [There is not to lessen, nor to add \+sls (to)\+sls*; nor there is to find the great worthy things of God.]\add* 
\p  
\v 7 When a man hath ended, then he shall begin \add [or beginneth]\add*; and when he hath rested, \sls (then)\sls* he shall work. 
\p  
\v 8 What is a man, and what is the glory of him? and what is good, either \add [or]\add* what is the wicked thing of him? 
\p  
\v 9 The number of the days of men, \em that be\em* commonly \add [or as much \+sls (as)\+sls*]\add* an hundred years, 
\p  
\v 10 be areckoned as the drops of the water of the sea; and as the stone \sls (or a stone)\sls* of gravel, so a few years in the day of everlastingness \add [or the spiritual world]\add*. 
\p  
\v 11 For this thing God is patient in \sls (or with)\sls* them, and sheddeth \add [or he shall pour]\add* out on them his mercy. 
\p  
\v 12 He saw the presumption, \add [or \+sls (the)\+sls* pride]\add*, of their heart, for it was evil; and he knew the destroying of them, for it was wicked, \add [or shrewd, \+sls (or depraved)\+sls*]\add*. Therefore he filled his mercy in them, and showed to them the way of equity. 
\p  
\v 13 The merciful doing of man \em is\em* about his neighbour; but the mercy of the Lord \em is\em* over each \add [or upon all]\add* flesh. He that hath mercy, and teach-eth, and chastiseth as a shepherd his flock, 
\p  
\v 14 do \em he\em* mercy, taking the teaching of merciful doing; and he that hast\sls (en)\sls*-eth in the dooms thereof \add [or of him]\add*. 
\p  
\v 15 Son, in goods \add [or good things]\add* give thou not \sls (com)\sls*plaint, and in \sls (or with)\sls* each gift give thou not heaviness of an evil word. 
\p  
\v 16 Whether dew shall not cool heat? so and a word \em is\em* better than \sls (a)\sls* gift. 
\p  
\v 17 Lo! whether a word \em is\em* not above \add [or over]\add* a good gift? but ever either \em is\em* with a man justified \add [or a justified man]\add*. 
\p  
\v 18 A fool shall upbraid sharply \add [or shall give reproof]\add*; and the gift of an untaught man maketh \sls (the)\sls* eyes to fail. 
\p  
\v 19 Before the doom make thou ready rightfulness to thee; and learn thou, before that thou speak. Before sickness give thou \add [or take]\add* medicine; 
\p  
\v 20 and before the doom ask thyself, and thou shalt find mercy in the sight of God. 
\p  
\v 21 Before sickness make thee meek, and in the time of sickness show thy living. \add [Before sickness meek thee, and in the time of infirmity show thou thy conversation or thy living.]\add* 
\p  
\v 22 Be thou not hindered to pray ever\add [more]\add*, and dread thou not to be justified till to \add [or unto the]\add* death; for why the meed of God dwelleth without end. 
\p  
\v 23 Before prayer make ready \add [or prepare]\add* thy soul; and do not thou be as a man that tempteth God, \em that is, that a man betake himself to peril, and believe that that he may do reasonably, and \+sls (then)\+sls* abide to be delivered of \+sls (or by)\+sls* God\em*. 
\p  
\v 24 Have thou mind of \sls (or remember the)\sls* ire \add [or wrath]\add* in the day of ending; and make thou in living \add [or conversation]\add* the time of yielding. 
\p  
\v 25 Have thou mind of \sls (or remember)\sls* poverty in the day of abundance \add [or the time of plenty]\add*; and the need of poverty in the time \add [or day]\add* of riches. 
\p  
\v 26 From the morrowtide unto the eventide the time shall be changed; and all these things \em be\em* swift \add [or hasted]\add* in the eyes of God. 
\p  
\v 27 A wise man shall dread in all things; and in the days of trespasses he shall flee from uncunning \sls (or unknowing)\sls*, \em either sloth\em*. 
\p  
\v 28 Each fell, \add [or witty, \+sls (or witting, or knowing)\+sls*]\add* man, \em that is, attentive to eschew evils, by God’s dread\em*, know-eth wisdom; and to him that findeth it, he shall give acknowledging \sls (to it)\sls*. 
\p  
\v 29 Witty, \sls (or Witting, or knowing)\sls* men in words also they did wisely, and understood truth, and rightful-ness \add [or rightwiseness]\add*; and besought proverbs and dooms. 
\p  
\v 30 Go thou not after thy covetous-nesses; and be thou turned away from thy will. \add [After thy lusts go thou not; and from thy will turn thee away.]\add* 
\p  
\v 31 If thou givest to thy soul the covetousnesses thereof \add [or \+sls (its)\+sls* lusts]\add*, it shall make thee into joy to thine enemies. 
\p  
\v 32 Delight thou not in companies \sls (or crowds)\sls*, neither in little \em companies\em*\add [or in small things]\add*; for why the sinning \add [or the trespassing]\add* of them is continual. 
\p  
\v 33 Be thou not mean in the striving of love \add [or for money]\add*, and something is \add [not]\add* to thee in the bag; for why thou shalt be envious to thy \sls (own)\sls* soul. 
\c 19  
\cl CHAPTER 19 
\p  
\v 1 A drunken workman shall not be made rich; and he that chargeth not little \em sins\em*\add [or despiseth little things]\add*, falleth down \em into grievouser sins\em*, little and little. 
\p  
\v 2 Wine and women make to be apostates, yea, wise men, \add [or Wine and women make also wise men to go backward]\add*; and they reprove witty, \sls (or witting, or knowing)\sls* men. And he that joineth himself to whores, shall be wicked; 
\p  
\v 3 rot and worms shall inherit him, and he shall be set on high into more ensample, and his soul shall be taken away from \sls (the)\sls* number \em of chosen men\em*. 
\p  
\v 4 He that believeth soon, is un-stable \add [or light]\add* in heart, and shall be made less; and he that trespasseth against his \sls (own)\sls* soul, shall be had furthermore. 
\p  
\v 5 He that joyeth in wickedness, shall be cursed; and he that hateth blaming \add [or correction]\add*, shall be made less in life; 
\p  
\v 6 and he that hateth jangling \add [or much speech]\add*, quencheth malice. He that sinneth against his \sls (own)\sls* soul, shall \add [not]\add* repent \add [or do penance]\add*; and that is merry in malice, shall be cursed \add [or reproved]\add*. 
\p  
\v 7 Rehearse thou \sls (or Repeat)\sls* not an hard word, and wicked; and thou shalt not be made less. 
\p  
\v 8 Do not thou tell thy wit to friend and \sls (or)\sls* to \sls (an)\sls* enemy; and if trespass is to thee, do not thou make \sls (it)\sls* naked. 
\p  
\v 9 For he shall hear thee, and shall keep thee, and he as defending the sin shall hate thee; and so he shall be ever\sls (more)\sls* with thee. 
\p  
\v 10 Thou hast heard a word against thy neighbour; die it \sls (al)\sls*together in \sls (or with)\sls* thee, and trust thou that it shall not break thee. 
\p  
\v 11 A fool travaileth greatly of \sls (or in)\sls* the face of a word, as the sorrow of \sls (the)\sls* bearing of a young child \add [or \+sls (the)\+sls* wailing of the birth of a child]\add*. 
\p  
\v 12 An arrow fastened \add [or fixed]\add* in the hip of a dog, so a word in the heart of a fool. 
\p  
\v 13 Reprove thou \add [or Chastise]\add* a friend, lest peradventure he understand not, and say, I did \sls (it)\sls* not; either if he hath done \sls (it)\sls*, lest he add to do \sls (it)\sls* again. 
\p  
\v 14 Reprove thou \add [or Chastise]\add* a neigh-bour, lest peradventure he say \sls (it)\sls* not; and if he saith \add [or said]\add*\sls (it)\sls*, lest per-adventure he rehearse \sls (or repeat it)\sls*. 
\p  
\v 15 Reprove thou \add [or Chastise]\add* a friend, for why trespassing is done often; and believe thou not to each word. 
\p  
\v 16 There is a man that falleth \add [or that slideth]\add* by his tongue, but not of will, \em that is, wittingly and of \+sls (or on)\+sls* purpose\em*. For why who is he, that trespasseth not in \sls (or with)\sls* his tongue? 
\p  
\v 17 Reprove thou \add [or Chastise]\add* a neighbour, \em betwixt thee and him\em*, before that thou menace \add [or threaten]\add*\sls (him)\sls*; and give thou place to the dread of the Highest. 
\p  
\v 18 (This verse is omitted in the original text.) 
\p  
\v 19 (This verse is omitted in the original text.) 
\p  
\v 20 For why all wisdom \em is\em* the dread of God, and in that \em wisdom\em* for to dread God; and the ordinance \add [or the disposing]\add* of \sls (the)\sls* law \em is\em* in all wisdom. 
\p  
\v 21 (This verse is omitted in the original text.) 
\p  
\v 22 And the teaching of wickedness is not wisdom; and the prudence of sins is not good thought. \add [And wisdom is not the discipline of shrewdness \+sls (or depravity)\+sls*; and good thinking is not the prudence of sins.]\add* 
\p  
\v 23 There is wickedness of prudence, and cursedness \em is\em* therein; and there is an unwise man, which is made little in wisdom. \add [There is shrewdness \+sls (or depravity)\+sls* of prudence, and in it cursing; and there is an unwise man, that is less\+sls (en)\+sls*ed in wisdom.]\add* 
\p  
\v 24 Better is a man that hath little wisdom, and failing in wit, in the dread of God, than he that hath plenty of \add [or aboundeth in]\add* wit, and breaketh the law of the Highest. 
\p  
\v 25 There is \sls (a)\sls* certain subtlety \add [or slyness]\add*, and it is wicked. And there is a man, that sendeth out a certain word, telling out \sls (the)\sls* truth. 
\p  
\v 26 There is a man that meeketh himself wickedly \em to deceive men the more\em*; and his inner things be full of guile. \add [There is, that shrewdly meeketh himself; and the entrails of him be full of treachery.]\add* 
\p  
\v 27 And there is a just \add [or rightwise]\add* man, that maketh low greatly \add [or under-putteth]\add* himself of \sls (or by)\sls* much meek-ness; and there is a just \add [or rightwise]\add* man, that boweth the face, and feign-eth him\sls (self)\sls* to see not that, that is unknown. 
\p  
\v 28 \sls (Even)\sls* Though \add [or And if]\add* he is forbidden of \sls (or by the)\sls* feebleness \add [or infirmity]\add* of strengths to do sin; if he findeth \sls (the)\sls* time to do evil, he shall do evil. 
\p  
\v 29 A man is known by \sls (his)\sls* sight \sls (or by his appearance)\sls*; and a witty, \sls (or a witting, or a knowing)\sls* man is known by meeting of face. 
\p  
\v 30 The clothing of \sls (the)\sls* body, and the laughing of teeth, and the enter-ing \add [or the going in]\add* of a man, tell out of him. 
\c 20  
\cl CHAPTER 20 
\p  
\v 1 There is false reproving in the ire of a man full of despising \add [or There is lying correction in \+sls (the)\+sls* wrath of the wrongful]\add*; and there is doom which is not proved to be good; and there is a still man, and he is prudent. 
\p  
\v 2 It is full good to reprove \add [or How good \+sls (it)\+sls* is to reprove]\add*, \em more\em* than to be wroth, and to forbid not a man acknowledging in prayer. 
\p  
\v 3 The covetousness of a gelding hath defouled the maidenhood of a young woman, so \sls (or is as)\sls* he that maketh wicked doom by violence. \add [The lust of the gelding deflowered the young woman, or \+sls (made her)\+sls* bereft of her maidenhood, so he that doeth by force wicked doom.]\add* 
\p  
\v 4 It is full good, that a man \em that is\em* reproved, show openly penance; for so thou shalt escape willful sin. \add [How good \+sls (it)\+sls* is, the chastised to show penance; so forsooth thou shalt flee away \+sls (from)\+sls* willful sin.]\add* 
\p  
\v 5 There is a still man, which is found wise; and he \sls (that)\sls* is hateful, which is foolhardy to speak. 
\p  
\v 6 Soothly there is a still man, not having wit of speech; and there is a still man, knowing the season of coven-able, \sls (or of suitable, or opportune)\sls* time. 
\p  
\v 7 A wise man shall be still till to \sls (the right)\sls* time; but a jolly, \add [or reck-less, or wild]\add* man and \sls (an)\sls* unprudent man shall not keep time. 
\p  
\v 8 He that useth many words, hurteth his \sls (own)\sls* soul; and he that taketh power to himself unjustly \add [or wrongfully]\add*, shall be hated. 
\p  
\v 9 There is going forth in evils to a man unlearned \add [or undisciplined]\add*; and there is finding into \sls (im)\sls*pairing \add [or into harm]\add*. 
\p  
\v 10 There is a gift, which is not profitable; and there is a gift, whose yielding is double. 
\p  
\v 11 There is making less for glory; and there is a man, which shall raise the head from meekness. 
\p  
\v 12 There is a man, that again-buyeth many \em sins\em* for \sls (a)\sls* little price, and restoreth those \add [or them]\add* in sevenfold. 
\p  
\v 13 A wise man in words maketh himself amiable \add [or lovable]\add*; but the graces of fools shall be shed \add [or poured]\add* out. 
\p  
\v 14 The gift of an unwise man shall not be profitable to thee; for his eyes be sevenfold, \em that is, his intent is manyfold and diverse\em*. 
\p  
\v 15 He shall give little things \add [or Few things he shall give]\add*, and he shall up-braid many things; and the opening of his mouth is enflaming. Today a man lendeth, and tomorrow he asketh \sls (for)\sls*\add [it]\add*\sls (again)\sls*; and such a man is hateful. 
\p  
\v 16 A friend shall not be to a fool, and grace shall not be to his goods. For they that eat his bread, be of false tongue, \em that is, flatterers praising his follies\em*; 
\p  
\v 17 how often, and how many men shall scorn him?\sls (!)\sls* For he parteth \add [or he dealed]\add* not by even wit that, that was worthy to be had; in like manner and that, that was not worthy to be had. 
\p  
\v 18 The falling \add [or sliding]\add* of a false tongue \em is\em* as he that falleth in \sls (or on)\sls* the pavement; so the falls of evil men shall come hastily. 
\p  
\v 19 A man without grace \em is\em* as a vain fable; and it shall be customable in the mouth of unlearned men. \add [An unkind man as a vain fable; and it shall be often in the mouth of the undisciplined.]\add* 
\p  
\v 20 A parable, \em that is, a true sentence and great\em*, shall be reproved \sls (when it cometh out)\sls* of the mouth of a fool; for he saith not it \add [or he saith it not]\add* in his \sls (or its)\sls* time. 
\p  
\v 21 There is a man, that is forbidden to do sin, for \sls (or because of)\sls* poverty; and he shall \sls (not)\sls* be pricked in his rest. 
\p  
\v 22 There is a man, that shall lose \sls (or destroy)\sls* his \sls (own)\sls* soul for shame; and for the unprudence of a person he shall lose it. Forsooth he shall lose \sls (or destroy)\sls* himself for the taking \sls (or the favouring)\sls* of a person. 
\p  
\v 23 There is a man, that for shame promiseth to a friend; and \sls (then)\sls* he hath gotten \add [or won]\add* him\sls (self)\sls*\sls (an)\sls* enemy without cause, \add [or willfully, \+sls (or willingly)\+sls*]\add*. 
\p  
\v 24 Leasing \sls (or Lying)\sls*\em is\em* a wicked shame in a man; and it shall be cus-tomably \add [or busily]\add* in the mouth of unlearned men \add [or the undisciplined]\add*. 
\p  
\v 25 Better, \em or less evil\em*, is a thief than the customableness of a man, a leas-ing-monger, \em that is, a man accustomed to lying\em*, \add [or a liar]\add*; forsooth both they \sls (or both of them)\sls* shall inherit perdition. 
\p  
\v 26 The manners of men leasing-mongers \add [or liars]\add*\em be\em* without honour; and their shame \em is\em* with them without ceasing. 
\p  
\v 27 A wise man in words shall bring forth himself; and a prudent man shall please great men. 
\p  
\v 28 He that worketh his land, shall make high the heap of fruits; and he that worketh rightfulness, shall be enhanced \sls (or exalted)\sls*. Soothly he that pleaseth great men, shall escape wickedness. 
\p  
\v 29 Presents and gifts blind the eyes of judges; and as \sls (one)\sls* dumb in the mouth it \add [or he]\add* turneth away the chastisings of them. 
\p  
\v 30 Wisdom hid, and treasure unseen, what profit \em is\em* in ever either? 
\p  
\v 31 He is better, that hideth his unwisdom, than a man that hideth his wisdom. 
\p  
\v 32 (This verse is omitted in the original text.) 
\c 21  
\cl CHAPTER 21 
\p  
\v 1 Son, thou hast done sin? \add [or Son, hast thou sinned?]\add* add thou \sls (to it)\sls* not again; but beseech thou for the former \em sins\em*, that those \add [or they]\add* be forgiven to thee. 
\p  
\v 2 As from the face of a serpent \add [or a shadow adder]\add* flee thou sins; and if thou nighest \sls (or approachest)\sls* to them, those \add [or they]\add* shall take thee. The teeth of a lion \em be\em*\sls (as)\sls* the teeth there-of, that slay the souls of men. 
\p  
\v 3 All wickedness \em is\em* as a sharp sword on either side; health is not to the wound thereof \add [or of it]\add*. 
\p  
\v 4 Chidings and wrongs shall destroy chattel \add [or substance]\add*; and an house that is over-rich, shall be destroyed by pride; so the chattel \add [or substance]\add* of a proud man shall be drawn up by the root. 
\p  
\v 5 The prayer of a poor man shall come from the mouth unto \sls (the)\sls* ears \em of God\em*; and doom shall come to him hastily. 
\p  
\v 6 He that hateth reproving, is \sls (in)\sls* a step of the sinner; and \sls (or but)\sls* he that dreadeth God, shall be turned \add [or converted]\add* to \sls (him in)\sls* his heart. 
\p  
\v 7 A mighty man with an hardy tongue is known afar; and a witty \sls (or a witting or a knowing)\sls* man can or knoweth how to keep himself \add [or to slide]\add* from that \em man\em*. 
\p  
\v 8 He that buildeth his house with other men’s costs, \em is\em* as he that gather-eth his stones in winter. 
\p  
\v 9 Sheaves, or stubble, \add [or flax top\+sls (s)\+sls*]\add*, gathered together \em is\em* the synagogue of sinners; and the ending of them \em is\em* the flame of fire. 
\p  
\v 10 The way of sinners \em is\em* set \sls (al)\sls*to-gether \add [or planted]\add* with stones; and in the end of them \em be\em* hells\f + \fr 21:10 \ft \+em It is said ‘hells’ in plural number, for many places be there\+em*.\f*, \add [or hell]\add*, and darknesses, and pains. 
\p  
\v 11 He that keepeth rightfulness, shall hold the wit \sls (or the understanding)\sls* thereof. The perfection of God’s dread \em is\em* wisdom and wit. 
\p  
\v 12 He shall not be taught, which is not wise in \sls (what is)\sls* good. Forsooth unwisdom is, which is plenteous in evil; and wit is not, where \sls (there)\sls* is bitterness. \add [He shall not be learned, that is not wise in good. There is forsooth unwisdom, that aboundeth in evil; and there is not wit, where is bitterness.]\add* 
\p  
\v 13 The cunning, \sls (or knowing, or the knowledge)\sls* of a wise man shall be plenteous as flowing \sls (water)\sls*; and the counsel of him dwelleth as a well of life. 
\p  
\v 14 The heart of a fool \em is\em* as a broken vessel; and it shall not hold any wisdom. 
\p  
\v 15 Whatever wise word a cunning \sls (or a knowing)\sls* man heareth, he shall praise \sls (it)\sls*, and lay to \sls (or add to it)\sls*. A lecherous man heard \sls (it)\sls*, and it shall displease him; and he shall cast \add [or throw]\add* it away behind his back. 
\p  
\v 16 The telling of a fool \em is\em* as a burden in \sls (or on)\sls* the way; for why grace shall be found in \sls (or on)\sls* the lips of a wise man. 
\p  
\v 17 The mouth of a prudent man is sought in the church; and \em men\em* shall think \sls (on)\sls* his words in their hearts. 
\p  
\v 18 As an house destroyed, so \em is\em* wisdom to a fool; and the cunning \sls (or the knowing)\sls* of an unwise man \em is\em* words that may not be or be not able to be told out \add [or \+sls (that be)\+sls* untellable]\add*. 
\p  
\v 19 Stocks in \sls (or on)\sls* the feet \em is\em* teach-ing \add [or doctrine]\add* to a fool; and as bonds of hands on the right hand. 
\p  
\v 20 A fool enhanceth his voice in laughing; but a wise man shall laugh scarcely still. 
\p  
\v 21 Teaching \em is\em* a golden ornament to a prudent man; and as an ornament of the arm \add [or an arm-circle]\add* in \sls (or on)\sls* the right arm. 
\p  
\v 22 The foot of a fool \em is\em* light \sls (or easily)\sls* into the house of a neighbour; and a wise man shall be ashamed of the person of a mighty man. 
\p  
\v 23 A fool beholdeth from the window into the house; but a learned man shall stand withoutforth. 
\p  
\v 24 It \em is\em* folly of a man to harken by the door; and a prudent man shall be grieved by despising \add [or with strife]\add*. 
\p  
\v 25 The lips of unprudent men shall tell fond things \add [or follies]\add*; but the words of prudent men shall be weigh-ed in a balance. 
\p  
\v 26 The heart of fools \em is\em* in their mouth; and the mouth of wise men \em is\em* in their heart. 
\p  
\v 27 When a wicked man curseth the devil, he curseth his own soul. 
\p  
\v 28 A privy backbiter shall defoul his soul, and in all things he shall be hated, and he that dwelleth, shall be hated; a still man and wise shall be honoured. 
\c 22  
\cl CHAPTER 22 
\p  
\v 1 A slow man is \sls (as)\sls* stunned in \sls (or as)\sls* a stone of clay; and all men shall speak on \add [or of]\add* the \add [great]\add* despising of him. 
\p  
\v 2 A slow man is \sls (as)\sls* stunned of \sls (or as)\sls* the dung of oxes \add [or the drit of oxen]\add*; and each man that toucheth him, shall shake the hands. 
\p  
\v 3 The shame of a father is of a son unlearned \add [or undisciplined]\add*; but a fond \add [or a fool\+sls (ish)\+sls*]\add* daughter shall be in decreasing \add [or diminishing]\add*\em of the honour of father and mother\em*. 
\p  
\v 4 A prudent daughter \em is\em* heritage to her husband; for she that shameth \em her husband\em*, is in despising \add [or in reproof]\add* of \sls (or by)\sls* the father. 
\p  
\v 5 A bold \em woman, that is, shame-less\em*, shameth the father and husband, and shall not be made less than unfaithful men; forsooth she shall not be honoured of \sls (or by)\sls* ever either. 
\p  
\v 6 Melody in mourning \em is\em* uncoven-able \sls (or unsuitable)\sls* telling; beatings and teaching, \add [or scourges and doc-trine]\add*, \sls (be)\sls* in all time with wisdom. 
\p  
\v 7 He that teacheth a fool, \sls (is)\sls* as he that glueth together a tilestone, \add [or a sherd, \+sls (or shard)\+sls*]\add*. He that telleth a word to him that heareth not, \em is\em* as he that raiseth a man sleeping from a grievous \add [or heavy]\add* sleep. 
\p  
\v 8 He that telleth wisdom to a fool, speaketh with a man sleeping; and in the end of the telling he shall say, Who is this? 
\p  
\v 9 (This verse is omitted in the original text.) 
\p  
\v 10 (This verse is omitted in the original text.) 
\p  
\v 11 Weep thou on \sls (or for)\sls* a dead man, for why his light \add [or the light of him]\add* failed; and weep thou on \sls (or for)\sls* a fool, for he failed of wit. Weep thou a little on \sls (or for)\sls* a dead man, for he hath rested. Forsooth the life of a full wicked man \em is\em* full wicked, more than the death of a fool. 
\p  
\v 12 The mourning of \sls (or for)\sls* a dead man \em is\em* seven days; but \em the mourning\em* of \sls (or for)\sls* a fool and of \sls (or for)\sls* a wick-ed man \em is\em* all the days of their life. 
\p  
\v 13 Speak thou not much with a fool, and go thou not with an unwise man. Keep thee from him, \sls (so)\sls* that thou have not dis-ease \add [or grief]\add*; and thou shalt not be defouled in the sin of him. Bow thou away from him, and thou shalt find rest; and be thou not annoyed \sls (or harmed)\sls* by his folly. 
\p  
\v 14 What shall be made heavier than lead? and what other name than a fool \em is\em* to it \add [or to him]\add*? 
\p  
\v 15 It is lighter \sls (or easier)\sls* to bear gravel, and salt, and a gobbet of iron, than a man unprudent \add [or an impru-dent man]\add*, and a fool, and unfaithful. 
\p  
\v 16 As an heap \add [or \+sls (a)\+sls* joining]\add* of trees, bound together in the foundament of the building, shall not be unbound \add [or unloosed]\add*, so and an heart confirmed in the thought of counsel. 
\p  
\v 17 The thought of a wise man shall not be made shrewd \sls (or depraved)\sls* in any time, neither dreaded. 
\p  
\v 18 As chaffs in high places, and sand without meddling of him \add [or and mor-tar without due cost]\add*, set against the face of the wind, shall not dwell; so and a dreadful heart in the thought \add [or in the thinking]\add* of a fool against-standeth not against the fierceness of dread. As adorning, \em either pargeting\em*, full of gravel in a clear wall, so and a fearedful heart in the thought of a fool \add [or the trembling heart in the thinking of a fool]\add* shall not dread in any time; so and he that dwelleth ever\add [more]\add* in the behests \sls (or the commands)\sls* of God. 
\p  
\v 19 He that pricketh the eye, shall lead out tears; and he that pricketh the heart, bringeth forth wit. 
\p  
\v 20 He that casteth \add [or throwing]\add* a stone to \sls (or at)\sls* birds, shall cast down those \add [or them]\add*; so and he that doeth wrong to a friend, departeth \add [or loseth]\add* friendship. 
\p  
\v 21 Though thou bringest forth a sword to a friend, despair thou not; for there is going again to the friend. 
\p  
\v 22 If he openeth a sorrowful mouth, dread thou not; for why there is according, except \sls (for)\sls* despising, and shame, and pride, and showing \add [or opening]\add* of private\sls (s)\sls*, \sls (or of secrets)\sls*, and a treacherous wound; in all these things a friend shall fly \add [or flee]\add* away. 
\p  
\v 23 Have thou faith with a friend in his poverty, \sls (so)\sls* that thou be glad also in his goods. In the time of his tribulations, dwell thou \add [or abide still]\add* faithful to him, \sls (so)\sls* that also thou be even-heir in the heritage of him. 
\p  
\v 24 Heat and smoke of fire \em is\em* made high before the fire of a chimney; so and cursings, and despisings, and menaces, \add [or curses, and wrongs, and threats]\add*, \em come\em* before blood. 
\p  
\v 25 I shall not be ashamed for to greet \add [or to salute]\add* a friend, and I shall not hide me from his face; 
\p  
\v 26 \sls (even)\sls* though \add [or and if]\add* evils come to me by him, I shall suffer. Each man that shall hear, shall keep warily himself from him. 
\p  
\v 27 Who shall give keeping to \sls (or keep watch over)\sls* my mouth, and a certain sealing on my lips, \sls (so)\sls* that I fall not by those, and that my tongue lose \sls (or destroy)\sls* not me? \add [Who shall give to my mouth ward, and upon my lips a certain mark, that I fall not from them, and my tongue lose me?]\add* 
\c 23  
\cl CHAPTER 23 
\p  
\v 1 Lord, Father, and lordly governor of my life, forsake thou me not in the thought \add [or the thinking]\add* and \sls (the)\sls* counsel of them, \em that is, of fools and unfaithful men\em*; neither suffer \sls (or allow)\sls* thou me to fall in that shame. 
\p  
\v 2 Who setteth above in my thought\sls (s)\sls* beatings, and in mine heart the teaching of wisdom, that in the uncunnings, \sls (or unknowings, or ignorances)\sls* of them he spare not me, and that the trespasses of them appear not? \add [Who putteth upon in my thinking scourges, and in mine heart doctrine of wisdom, that to the unknowings of them he spare not to me, and appear not the guilts of them?]\add* 
\p  
\v 3 Lest mine uncunnings, \sls (or my unknowings, or ignorances)\sls* increase, and my trespasses be multiplied, and my sins be plenteous \add [or abound]\add*; and lest I fall in the sight of mine adversaries, and mine enemy have joy. 
\p  
\v 4 Lord, Father, and God of my life, forsake thou not me in the thought\sls (s)\sls* of them. Give thou not to me enhancing of mine eyes, \em yea, suffer not \+sls (or do not allow)\+sls* that pride be lord over me\em*; 
\p  
\v 5 and turn thou away from me all shrewd \sls (or depraved)\sls* desire. 
\p  
\v 6 Do thou away from me the covetousnesses of the womb, and the covetousnesses of lechery \add [or of lust]\add* take me not; and give thou not me \sls (over)\sls*\sls (in)\sls*to a soul unreverent and undiscreet or unsavoury. 
\p  
\v 7 Sons, hear ye the teaching of \sls (the)\sls* mouth; and he that keepeth it, shall not perish by his lips, neither shall be caused to stumble in worst works. 
\p  
\v 8 A sinner and proud man shall be taken \add [or caught]\add* in his vanity; and a cursed man shall be caused to stumble in those \add [or in them]\add*. 
\p  
\v 9 Thy mouth be not customable \sls (or accustomed)\sls* to swearing; for why many fallings \em be\em* therein. \add [To swearing use not thy mouth; many forsooth fallings be in it.]\add* 
\p  
\v 10 Forsooth the naming of God be not customable \add [or continual]\add* in thy mouth, and be thou not meddled to, \add [or mingled, \+sls (or mixed with)\+sls*]\add* the names of saints; for thou shalt not be guiltless of them. 
\p  
\v 11 For as a servant \em that is\em* asked busily, shall not want \sls (or lack)\sls* wan-ness, \add [or envy]\add*; so each man swearing and naming shall not be purged of sin in all. A man swearing much shall be filled with wickedness; and venge-ance shall not go away from his house. And if he deceiveth a brother, his trespass shall be above \add [or upon]\add* him; and if he feigneth, he shall trespass doubly \add [or double]\add*. And if he sweareth in vain, he shall not be justified; for why his house shall be filled with worst yielding. 
\p  
\v 12 Also again-ward another speech is into death; be it not found in the heritage of Jacob. For why all these things shall be done away from merciful men; and they shall not delight in trespasses. 
\p  
\v 13 Thy mouth be not customable \sls (or accustomed)\sls* to unreverent speech; for why a word of sin is in it. \add [To the undisciplined speech use not thy mouth; forsooth there is in it the word of sin.]\add* 
\p  
\v 14 Have thou mind on \sls (or Think upon)\sls* thy father and mother; for \sls (or when)\sls* thou standest in the midst of great men. Lest peradventure God forget thee in the sight of them; and lest thou made a fool by thus customableness \add [or busyness]\add*, suffer shame, \em either scorning\em*, \add [or reproof]\add*, and haddest rather to be not born, and curse the day of thy birth. 
\p  
\v 15 A man customable in \sls (or accustomed to using)\sls* the words of shame \add [or reproof]\add*, in all \sls (his)\sls* days shall not be taught. 
\p  
\v 16 Two kinds be plenteous \add [or abound]\add* in sins, and the third bring-eth ire and perdition. An hot soul burn-ing as fire shall not be quenched, till it swallow something; and a wicked man in the mouth of his flesh shall not fail, till he kindle \sls (a)\sls* fire. 
\p  
\v 17 Each bread \em is\em* sweet to a lecher-ous man; he shall not be made weary, trespassing till to the end. 
\p  
\v 18 Each man that passeth \add [or that over-goeth]\add* his bed, doeth despite against his soul, and saith, Who seeth me? Darknesses \sls (en)\sls*compass me, and \sls (the)\sls* walls cover me, and no man behold-eth me. Whom dread I? The Highest shall not have mind on my sins. 
\p  
\v 19 And he understandeth not, that the eye of him, \em that is, of God\em*, seeth all things; for why the dread of such a man putteth away from him\sls (self)\sls* the dread of God, and the eyes of men that dread him \em put away from him God’s dread\em*. And he knew not, that the eyes of the Lord be much more clearer than the sun, and behold all the ways of men, and the depth of the sea, and they behold the hearts of men into hid parts. 
\p  
\v 20 For why all things were known to the Lord, before that they were made \add [or formed]\add*\sls (out)\sls* of nought; so and after the making, he beholdeth all things. 
\p  
\v 21 This \em man\em* shall be punished in the streets of the city; he shall be driven away as an horse colt, and he shall be taken \add [or caught]\add*, where he hopeth not. And he shall be shame to all men; for he understood not the dread of the Lord. 
\p  
\v 22 So and each woman forsaking her husband shall do sin, and ordaining heritage, \em that is, \+sls (an)\+sls* heir of her husband\em*, of \sls (or by)\sls* an alien matrimony. 
\p  
\v 23 For first she was unbelieveful in the law of the Highest, and the second time she forsook her husband; and the third time she was defouled in adultery, and ordained to him sons of \sls (or by)\sls* another man. 
\p  
\v 24 She, this \em woman\em*, shall be brought into the church, and men shall behold on her sons. 
\p  
\v 25 Her sons shall not give \add [or take]\add* roots, and her branches shall not give fruit. 
\p  
\v 26 They shall leave the mind \sls (or the memory)\sls* of her into cursing, and the shame of her shall not be done away. 
\p  
\v 27 And they that be left shall know, that nothing \em is\em* better than the dread of God, and nothing \em is\em* sweeter than to behold in the commandments of the Lord. 
\p  
\v 28 It is great glory to pursue \add [or to follow]\add* the Lord; for why length of days shall be taken of \sls (or received from)\sls* him. 
\c 24  
\cl CHAPTER 24 
\p  
\v 1 Wisdom shall praise his soul, and he shall be honoured in God; and he shall have glory in the midst of his people. 
\p  
\v 2 And he shall open his mouth in the churches of the Highest; and he shall have glory in the sight of his virtue \sls (or his power)\sls*. And he shall be enhanced in the midst of his people; and he shall \add [much]\add* wonder in holy fullness, \em either plenty\em*. And in the multitude of chosen men he shall have praising; and among blessed men he shall be blessed, and say, 
\p  
\v 3 I, the first engendered \add [or \+sls (be)\+sls*got-ten]\add* before each creature, came forth from \add [or \+sls (out)\+sls* of]\add* the mouth of the Highest. I \sls (was)\sls* made in \sls (the)\sls* heavens, that \sls (or where)\sls* light never failing rose up, and as a cloud I covered all \sls (the)\sls* earth, 
\p  
\v 4 I dwelled in highest things, and my throne \sls (is)\sls* in a pillar of \add [a]\add* cloud. 
\p  
\v 5 I alone went about the compass \add [or the circle]\add* of heaven, and I pierced the depth of the sea; 
\p  
\v 6 and I went in the waves of the sea, and I stood in \sls (or on)\sls* all the land \add [or all \+sls (the)\+sls* earth]\add*. And I had the first dignity in each people, and in each folk; and I trod by virtue \sls (or power)\sls* on the necks of all excellent men and meek \add [or all high and low]\add*; 
\p  
\v 7 and in all these \em men\em* I sought rest, and I shall dwell in the heritage \sls (or inheritance)\sls* of the Lord. 
\p  
\v 8 Then the Creator \add [or the former]\add* of all \add [things]\add* commanded, and said to me; and he that formed me, rested in my tabernacle; and he said to me, Dwell thou in Jacob, and take thou heritage in Israel, and send thou roots in\sls (to)\sls* my chosen men \add [or my chosen]\add*. 
\p  
\v 9 I was engendered from the begin-ning and before worlds, and I shall not fail unto the world to coming; \add [From the beginning and before worlds I am formed, and unto the world to come I shall not cease to be;]\add* 
\p  
\v 10 and I ministered \add [or served]\add* in an holy dwelling before him. And so I was made steadfast in Zion, 
\p  
\v 11 and in like manner I rested in a city hallowed, and my power \em was\em* in Jerusalem. \add [and in an hallowed city \+sls (in)\+sls* like manner I rested, and in Jerusalem \+sls (was)\+sls* my power.]\add* 
\p  
\v 12 And I rooted in a people honour-ed; and the heritage thereof into the parts of my God, and my withholding in the plenty or the fullness of saints. 
\p  
\v 13 I was enhanced as a cedar in Lebanon, and as a cypress tree in the hill of Zion. 
\p  
\v 14 I was enhanced as a palm tree in Cades or in Kedesh, \sls (or in Engedi)\sls*, and as the planting of \sls (a)\sls* rose in Jericho. And as a fair olive tree in fields; and I was enhanced as a plane \add [or a platan]\add* tree besides \sls (the)\sls* water in streets. 
\p  
\v 15 As canel and balm giving great smell, I gave odour; as chosen myrrh I gave the sweetness of odour. And as storax, and galbanum, and ungulam, and gum, and as Lebanon not cut down, I made hot \add [or I smoked]\add* my dwelling place; and mine odour as balm \add [or balsam]\add* not meddled, \add [or mingled, \+sls (or mixed)\+sls*]\add*. 
\p  
\v 16 I as terebinth stretched forth my boughs \add [or branches]\add*; and my boughs \add [or branches]\add*\em be\em* boughs \sls (or branches)\sls* of honour, and of glory \add [or grace]\add*. 
\p  
\v 17 I as a vine made fruit the sweet-ness of odour; and my flowers \em be\em* the fruits of honour, and of honesty \sls (or of riches)\sls*. 
\p  
\v 18 I \em am\em* a mother of fair love, and of dread, and of knowing, and of holy hope. In me \em is\em* all grace of way, and of truth; in me \em is\em* all hope of life and of virtue. 
\p  
\v 19 All ye that covet me, pass \sls (or come)\sls* to me; and be ye filled of \sls (or with)\sls* my generations. 
\p  
\v 20 For why my spirit \em is\em* sweet above \add [or over]\add* honey; and mine heritage \em is\em* above \add [or over]\add* honey, and honey-comb. My mind \em is\em* in\sls (to)\sls* the gener-ation of worlds \sls (or I shall always be remembered)\sls*. 
\p  
\v 21 They that eat me, shall hunger yet \add [or yet shall hunger]\add*; and they that drink me, shall thirst yet \add [or yet shall thirst]\add*. 
\p  
\v 22 He that heareth me, shall not be shamed; and they that work in me, shall not do sin; and they that declare me, shall have everlasting life. 
\p  
\v 23 All these things \em is\em* the book of life, and the testament of the Highest, and the knowing \add [or acknowledging]\add* of \sls (the)\sls* truth. Moses commanded a law in the commandments of rightful-nesses \add [or the behests of rightwise-nesses]\add*, and \sls (for an)\sls* heritage to the house of Jacob, and \sls (the)\sls* promises to Israel. 
\p  
\v 24 He setted, \em that is, ordained, either promised\em*, to David, his child, to raise \add [up]\add* of \sls (or from)\sls* him a king most strong, and sitting without end in the throne of honour. 
\p  
\v 25 Which \em king\em* filleth wisdom, as Pishon \em sheddeth out water\em*; and as Tigris in the days of new things. 
\p  
\v 26 Which, as Euphrates, \add [full]\add*-filleth wit; which multiplieth, as \sls (the)\sls* Jordan in the time of harvest \add [or reap\+sls (ing)\+sls*]\add*. 
\p  
\v 27 Which sendeth teaching as \sls (the)\sls* light; and is nigh \em all men\em*, as Gihon in the day of vintage. 
\p  
\v 28 Which maketh perfectly first to know that \em wisdom\em*\add [or That perform-eth first to know it]\add*; and a feebler man shall not ensearch it. 
\p  
\v 29 For why the thought\sls (s)\sls* thereof shall be \sls (as)\sls* plenteous of \sls (or as)\sls* the sea, \em that is, his knowing is more plenteous than the sea\em*; and his counsel in the great ocean \add [or in the great deepness]\add*\em is uncomprehensible\em*. I wisdom shedded \add [or poured]\add* out floods; I as a way, \em that is, a strong running\em*, of full great water \add [or water without measure]\add* of the flood. 
\p  
\v 30 I as the flood Dorix, and as a water conduit I went out of \add [or from]\add* paradise. 
\p  
\v 31 I said, I shall water my garden of plantings; and I shall greatly fill the fruit of my child-bearing. And lo! a plenteous way of water is made to \sls (or for)\sls* me; and my flood nighed to the sea. 
\p  
\v 32 For I \sls (en)\sls*lighten teaching as the cheer morrowtide \add [or morrowtide light]\add* to all men; and I shall tell out it unto far. I shall pierce all the lower \add [or nether]\add* parts of \sls (the)\sls* earth, and I shall behold all that sleep; and I shall \sls (en)\sls*lighten all that hope in the Lord. 
\p  
\v 33 Yet I shall shed \add [or pour]\add* out teach-ing as prophecy, and I shall leave it to them that seek wisdom; and I shall not fail into the generations \add [or pro-genies]\add* of them, till into the holy world. 
\p  
\v 34 See ye, that I travailed not to me alone, but to all that seek out \sls (the)\sls* truth. 
\c 25  
\cl CHAPTER 25 
\p  
\v 1 In three things it is pleased to my spirit, which be approved before God and men; \add [the]\add* according of brethren, and \sls (the)\sls* love of neighbours, \add [and]\add* a man and woman well consenting to themselves. 
\p  
\v 2 My soul hated three species, \sls (or kinds)\sls*, and I am grieved greatly to \sls (or by)\sls* the soul of them; a poor man proud, and a rich man \sls (that is a)\sls* liar, and an eld \add [or old]\add* man \sls (that is)\sls* a fool and unwitty \sls (or unwise)\sls*, \add [or doted]\add*. 
\p  
\v 3 How shalt thou find in thine eld \sls (age)\sls* those things, which thou gather-ed not in thy youth? 
\p  
\v 4 Doom \em of discretion is\em* full fair in hoariness, \em either \+sls (an)\+sls* eld man\em*, \add [or How fair the doom in hoariness]\add*, and to priests to know counsel. 
\p  
\v 5 Wisdom \em is\em* full fair to eld \add [or old]\add* men, and glorious understanding, and counsel. 
\p  
\v 6 The crown of eld men \em is\em* in much cunning, \sls (or knowing, or knowledge)\sls*; and the glory of them \em is\em* the dread of God. 
\p  
\v 7 I magnified nine things unsus-pect\sls (ed)\sls* of the heart; and I shall say the tenth thing by tongue to men. A man which living is merry in sons \add [or A man that is joyed in sons living]\add*, and seeing the destroying of his enemies. 
\p  
\v 8 \em He is\em* blessed that dwelleth with a witty \sls (or with a wise)\sls* woman, and he that fell not \add [or not slidden]\add* by his tongue, and he that served not to men unworthy to himself. 
\p  
\v 9 \em He is\em* blessed that findeth a very \sls (or a true)\sls* friend, and he that telleth out rightfulness to an ear hearing. 
\p  
\v 10 \em He is\em* full great that findeth wisdom and cunning \sls (or knowing)\sls*; but \em he is\em* not above \add [or over]\add* him that dreadeth God\f + \fr 25:10 \ft \+em The dread of God is the more (or the most) good, and passeth all (other) goods beforesaid\+em*.\f*. 
\p  
\v 11 The dread of God hath set itself above \add [or over]\add* all things. Blessed \em is\em* the man to whom it is given to have the dread of God; to whom shall he be likened, that holdeth that dread? 
\p  
\v 12 The dread of God \em is\em* the beginning of his love; forsooth the beginning of faith is to be fast-joined thereto \add [or to him]\add*. 
\p  
\v 13 The sorrow of \sls (the)\sls* heart is each wound; and the wickedness of a woman is all malice\f + \fr 25:13 \ft \+em That is, as the sorrow of heart passeth each wound of (the) body, so the malice of a woman passeth all the malice of a man\+em*. (This verse, and those which follow to the end of this chapter, are only found in some early copies of this book, and are more reflective of that author’s bitter personal experience, than of divine inspiration. And, of course, it goes without saying, that anyone could fashion a list of comparable grievances regarding life with a wicked man. T.P.N.)\f*. \em A leech \+sls (or A physician)\+sls*\em* shall see each wound, and \sls (or but)\sls* not the wound of \sls (the)\sls* heart; and all wickedness, and \sls (or but)\sls* not the wickedness of a woman; 
\p  
\v 14 and each covering \add [or all hid thing]\add*, \em that is, \+sls (the)\+sls* colouring of malice\em*, and not the covering \add [or the hid thing]\add* of haters; and each \add [or all]\add* vengeance, and not the vengeance of enemies. 
\p  
\v 15 None head is worse \add [or wickeder]\add* than the head of an adder dwelling in \sls (a)\sls* shadow; and none ire \add [or wrath]\add* is above \add [or over]\add* the ire of a woman. 
\p  
\v 16 It shall please more to dwell with a lion and a dragon, than to dwell with a wicked woman. 
\p  
\v 17 The wickedness of a woman changeth her face; and she blinded her cheer \sls (or her face)\sls* as a bear \em doeth\em*, and she shall show as a sack\sls (cloth)\sls* in the midst of \sls (her)\sls* neighbours. 
\p  
\v 18 Her husband \add [greatly]\add* wailed; and his \em wicked wife\em* heard, and sighed a little, \add [or hearing \+sls (her)\+sls*, sighed a little]\add*. 
\p  
\v 19 All malice \em is\em* short on \sls (or is little compared to)\sls* the malice of a woman; the part \add [or the lot]\add* of sinners, \em that is, the pain of hell\em*, fall on her. 
\p  
\v 20 As a going-up \sls (or an ascent)\sls* full of gravel in \sls (or to)\sls* the feet of an eld \add [or old]\add* man, so \em is\em* a woman \sls (that is)\sls* a great jangler to a peaceable \add [or quiet]\add* man. 
\p  
\v 21 Behold thou not the fairness of a woman, and covet thou not a woman for \sls (her)\sls* fairness. 
\p  
\v 22 The ire and unreverence of a woman \em to her husband is\em* a great shame \sls (or reproof)\sls*. If a woman hath the first dignity \add [or \+sls (the)\+sls* mastery]\add*, \em either chief governail\em*, she is contrary to her husband. 
\p  
\v 23 A low heart, and \sls (a)\sls* sorrowful face, and \sls (a)\sls* wound of death, \em is\em*\sls (from)\sls* a wicked woman. Feeble hands and knees unbound, \sls (resulteth from)\sls* a woman that blesseth not her husband. 
\p  
\v 24 The beginning of sin was made of \sls (or by)\sls* a woman; and all we die by her. 
\p  
\v 25 Give thou not issue to thy water, yea, not a little issue; neither to a wicked woman freedom, \add [or leave]\add*, of going forth \add [or going out]\add*. 
\p  
\v 26 If she goeth not at thine hand, she shall shame thee in the sight of \sls (thine)\sls* enemies. Cut her away from thy fleshes, lest ever\add [more]\add* she mis-use thee. 
\c 26  
\cl CHAPTER 26 
\p  
\v 1 The husband of a good woman is blessed; for why the number of their years \em is\em* double \add [or the number for-sooth of the years of him double]\add*. 
\p  
\v 2 A strong woman, \em that is, against sins\em*, delighteth her husband; and \sls (he)\sls* shall \add [ful]\add* fill in peace the years of his life. 
\p  
\v 3 A good woman \em is\em* a good part \sls (or partner)\sls*; in the good part of them that dread God, she shall be given to a man for \add [his]\add* good deeds. 
\p  
\v 4 Forsooth \sls (if)\sls* the heart of a rich man and \sls (or)\sls* of a poor man \em is\em* good; in all time their cheer \sls (or his face)\sls*\em is\em* glad. 
\p  
\v 5 Mine heart dreaded of three things, and my face dreaded \add [or was afeared]\add* in \sls (or of)\sls* the fourth thing. Betraying of a city, and the gathering together of people, \em that is, in conspiring of the people against the prince\em*, and false challenge; all \sls (these)\sls* things \sls (be more)\sls* grievous on \sls (or worse than)\sls* death. 
\p  
\v 6 The sorrow of heart, and mourn-ing, \em is\em* a jealous woman. In a jealous woman \em is\em*\sls (a)\sls* beating \add [or scourge]\add* of \sls (the)\sls* tongue, and she communeth with all men. 
\p  
\v 7 As a yoke of oxes \add [or oxen]\add* which is moved, so and a wicked woman; he that holdeth her, \em is\em* as he that taketh \add [or caught]\add*\sls (hold of)\sls* a scorpion. 
\p  
\v 8 A drunken woman \em is\em* great ire, and despising \add [or strife]\add*; and her filth-\sls (hood)\sls*\add [or nakedness]\add* shall not be covered. 
\p  
\v 9 The fornication of a woman \em is\em* in the raising of \sls (her)\sls* eyes; and \add [she]\add* shall be known in \sls (or by)\sls* the eyelids of her. 
\p  
\v 10 Make thou firm the keeping in \sls (or of)\sls* a daughter not turning away her-self; lest she mis-use herself, if she findeth \sls (an)\sls* occasion. 
\p  
\v 11 Be thou ware of all unreverence of her eyes; and wonder thou not, if she despiseth thee. 
\p  
\v 12 As a way-goer thirsting shall open the mouth at a well, and shall drink of each water next; and \em the foresaid daughter\em* shall sit against each pale, and shall open the arrow case against each arrow \add [or against all arrow\+sls (s)\+sls* shall open the quiver]\add*, till she fail. 
\p  
\v 13 The grace of a busy woman shall delight her husband; and shall make fat his bones. 
\p  
\v 14 The cunning \sls (or the knowing)\sls* of her is the gift of God. A wise woman and a still \sls (one)\sls* is not \sls (ex)\sls*changing of \sls (or with)\sls* a learned \add [or the taught]\add* soul. 
\p  
\v 15 Grace \add [up]\add* on grace is an holy woman, and shamefast. Forsooth all weighing is not worth a continent soul. 
\p  
\v 16 As the sun rising in the world in the highest things of God, so the fairness of a good woman \em is\em* into the ornament, or the adornment, of her house. 
\p  
\v 17 A lantern shining on an holy candlestick, and the fairness of a face on \sls (or in)\sls*\add [the]\add* steadfast age, \em that is, as such a lantern lighteneth the church, and such a face maketh fair ripe age, so a good woman maketh fair her house\em*. 
\p  
\v 18 Golden pillars on silvern founda-ments \sls (or foundations)\sls*, and steadfast feet on the soles of a steadfast \add [or a stable]\add* woman. Everlasting founda-ments on a firm stone, and the behests, \sls (or the commands)\sls*, \add [or the commandments]\add* of God in the heart of an holy woman. 
\p  
