\p  
\v 28 In two things mine heart was made sorry \add [or is made sorrowful]\add*, and in the third thing wrathfulness came to me. A man warrior failing by neediness, and a wise man despised. And God hath made him ready to \sls (or for)\sls* the sword, that passeth over \add [or over-goeth]\add* from rightfulness \add [or rightwiseness]\add* to sin. 
\p  
\v 29 Two species appeared hard and perilous to me; a merchant is deliver-ed of hard from his negligence, and a taverner shall not be justified of \add [or from]\add*\sls (the)\sls* sins of lips. 
\c 27  
\cl CHAPTER 27 
\p  
\v 1 Many men have trespassed for neediness; and he that seeketh to be made rich, turneth away his eye. 
\p  
\v 2 As a stake \add [or a pale]\add* is fastened in the midst of a heap \add [or a joining]\add* of stones, so and \em a man\em* shall be anguished by sins betwixt the midst of selling and buying. Trespass shall be all-broken with him that trespasseth. 
\p  
\v 3 If thou holdest not thee diligently in the dread of the Lord, thine house shall soon be turned upside down. 
\p  
\v 4 As dust shall dwell in the holes of a riddle, so the anguish of a man \em shall dwell\em* in the thought\sls (s)\sls* of him. 
\p  
\v 5 A furnace proveth the vessels of a potter; and the temptation of tribu-lation \em proveth\em* just \add [or rightwise]\add* men. 
\p  
\v 6 As churl-like travail \add [or earth-working]\add* about a tree showeth the fruit thereof, so a word of thought \em showeth\em* the heart of man. 
\p  
\v 7 Praise thou not a man before a word \em fully ended\em*; for why this is the temptation, \em that is, \+sls (the)\+sls* proving\em*, of men. 
\p  
\v 8 If thou pursuest rightfulness \add [or followest rightwiseness]\add*, thou shalt take it; thou shalt clothe it as a long cloth, \sls (or a cloak)\sls*, \add [or an aube]\add* of honour, and thou shalt dwell with it, and it shall defend thee without end, and in the day of knowing thou shalt find steadfastness. 
\p  
\v 9 Volatiles \add [or Fowls]\add* come together to \em birds\em* like themselves; and truth shall \sls (re)\sls*turn again to them that work it. 
\p  
\v 10 \sls (As)\sls* a lion setteth espies \add [or wait-eth \+sls (or lieth in wait)\+sls*]\add* ever\add [more]\add* to hunting; so sins to them that work wickedness. 
\p  
\v 11 An holy man dwelleth in wisdom, as the sun \em dwelleth\em*; for why a fool is changed as the moon. 
\p  
\v 12 In the midst of unwise men keep thou a word to \sls (the)\sls* time; but be thou busy in the midst of them that think \sls (upon)\sls* the law of God. 
\p  
\v 13 The telling of sinners \em is\em* hateful; and the laughing of them \em is\em* in the trespasses of sin. 
\p  
\v 14 Speech swearing much shall make \sls (for)\sls* standing up of hairs, for astonishing, to the head; and unrever-ence thereof \add [or \+sls (the)\+sls* irreverence of it]\add* is stopping of \sls (the)\sls* ears. 
\p  
\v 15 The shedding out of blood \em is\em* in the chiding \add [or jangling]\add* of proud men; and the cursing of them \em is\em* grievous hearing, \em for in their chiding they blaspheme God often, and it is full grievous to faithful ears to hear such blasphemy of God\em*. 
\p  
\v 16 He that showeth openly the privates \sls (or the secrets)\sls* of a friend, loseth \sls (or destroyeth)\sls* faithfulness; and he shall not find a friend to his soul. 
\p  
\v 17 Love thou a neighbour, and be thou joined with him in faith. For \sls (or But)\sls* if thou showest openly the privates \sls (or the secrets)\sls* of him, thou shalt not perfectly pursue after him. 
\p  
\v 18 For as a man that loseth his friend, so he that loseth the friendship of his neighbour. 
\p  
\v 19 And as a man that letteth go a bird from \add [or out of]\add* his hand, so thou that hast forsaken thy neighbour, and thou shalt not take \sls (or get)\sls* him \sls (again)\sls*. 
\p  
\v 20 Thou shalt not pursue \add [or follow]\add* him, for he is far absent \add [or far he is away]\add*; for he escaped as a capret from a snare, for the soul of him is wounded. 
\p  
\v 21 Thou shalt no more be able to bind him together; but of \sls (or after)\sls* evil saying is according. Soothly to show openly the privates \sls (or the secrets)\sls* of a friend, is despair of a soul unblessed \add [or unfaithful]\add*. 
\p  
\v 22 He that twinkleth with the eye, maketh \add [or forgeth]\add* wicked things; and no man shall cast him away. 
\p  
\v 23 In the sight of thine eyes he shall defoul his mouth, and he shall wonder on thy words; but at the last he shall turn waywardly \add [or pervert]\add* his mouth, and in his word he shall give slander \add [or in \+sls (or regarding)\+sls* thy words he shall give slander]\add*. 
\p  
\v 24 I \add [have]\add* heard many things, \em that is, evils\em*, and I made \sls (them)\sls* not even to him, \em yea, I areckoned not another malice even to the malice of this man\em*; and the Lord shall hate him. 
\p  
\v 25 If a man casteth a stone on high it shall fall on his \sls (own)\sls* head; and the guileful wound of a guileful \add [or treach-erous]\add* man shall part wounds. 
\p  
\v 26 And he that diggeth a ditch, shall fall into it; and he that setteth a stone to a neighbour, shall offend therein \add [or shall stumble in it]\add*; and he that setteth a snare to another man, shall perish therein. 
\p  
\v 27 If a man maketh worst \add [or wicked]\add* counsel, it shall be turned \add [up]\add* on him; and he shall not know from whence it shall come to him. 
\p  
\v 28 The scorning and despising of proud men and vengeance shall set espy to him, as a lion doeth. 
\p  
\v 29 They that delight in the fall of just \add [or rightwise]\add* men, shall perish by a snare; forsooth sorrow shall waste them, before that they die. 
\p  
\v 30 Ire \add [or Wrath]\add* and madness or rage, ever either be abominable; and a sinful man shall hold those \add [or them]\add*. 
\c 28  
\cl CHAPTER 28 
\p  
\v 1 He that will be avenged, shall find of \sls (or from)\sls* the Lord vengeance; and he keeping shall keep his sins \em to be punished harder by his rightfulness\em*. 
\p  
\v 2 Forgive thou to thy neighbour that annoyeth \sls (or harmeth)\sls* thee, and then \sls (thy)\sls* sins shall be released \add [or be forgiven]\add* to thee \sls (after)\sls* praying. 
\p  
\v 3 A man keepeth ire \add [or wrath]\add* to \sls (or for a)\sls* man; and seeketh he of \sls (or from)\sls* God medicine \sls (or remedy)\sls*? 
\p  
\v 4 He hath no mercy on a man like himself; and \sls (yet)\sls* beseecheth he the Highest for his own sins? 
\p  
\v 5 He the while he is flesh, reserveth ire; and asketh he of God mercy? who shall pray for his sins? 
\p  
\v 6 Have thou mind on the \add [or thy]\add* last things, and cease thou \add [or leave \+sls (off)\+sls*]\add* to be \sls (anyone’s)\sls* enemy. For why failing and death nigh not in the commandments \em of God\em*, \add [or Rotten-ness forsooth and death, stand on in the behests of him]\add*. 
\p  
\v 7 Have thou mind on \add [or Remem-ber]\add* the dread of the Lord, and be not wroth to the neighbour. Have thou mind on the testament of the Highest, and despise thou the ignorance of thy neighbour. 
\p  
\v 8 Abstain thee from strife, and thou shalt decrease, \em either abridge\em*, \sls (thy)\sls* sins. For why a wrathful man kindleth strife; 
\p  
\v 9 and a sinful man, \em that is, a sower of discords\em*, shall disturb \sls (or shall trouble)\sls* friends, and he shall send in enmity in the midst of men having peace. 
\p  
\v 10 For why after the trees of the wood, so \add [the]\add* fire shall burn on high; and after the might of a man, so his wrathfulness shall be, and after his chattel \add [or his substance]\add* he shall enhance his ire. 
\p  
\v 11 Hasty striving \add [or An hasted strife]\add* shall kindle fire, and hasty chiding shall shed out blood; and a tongue bearing witnessing shall bring death. 
\p  
\v 12 If thou blowest, as fire it shall burn on high; and if thou spittest thereon, it shall be quenched; ever either, \em that is, a word kindling ire, and a word refraining it\em*, come forth \sls (out)\sls* of the mouth. 
\p  
\v 13 A privy backbiter, and a double-tongued man, \em yea, he that speaketh fair before a man, and evil behind him, is\em* cursed; for he disturbed \sls (or troubled)\sls* many men having peace. 
\p  
\v 14 The third tongue hath stirred many men, and hath scattered them from folk into folk. It hath destroyed walled cities of rich men, and hath mined down \sls (or undermined)\sls* the houses of great men. It hath cut down the virtues of peoples, and hath unknit strong folks. 
\p  
\v 15 The third tongue hath cast out wedded, or honest, women, and hath \sls (de)\sls*prived them of their travails. 
\p  
\v 16 He that beholdeth \em the third tongue\em*, shall not have rest; neither shall have a friend, in whom he shall rest. 
\p  
\v 17 The wound of \add [a]\add* beating maketh wanness; but the wound of \sls (the)\sls* tongue shall make less \add [or break]\add* the bones. 
\p  
\v 18 Many men fell down by the sharp-ness of \sls (the)\sls* sword; but not so \sls (many)\sls*, \sls (or not as many)\sls* as they that perished \add [or died]\add* by their tongue. 
\p  
\v 19 \em He is\em* blessed that is covered from a wicked, \add [or shrewd, \+sls (or depraved)\+sls*]\add* tongue; and he that passed not in the wrathfulness thereof, and he that drew not the yoke thereof, and was not bound in the bonds thereof. 
\p  
\v 20 For why the yoke thereof is an iron yoke, and the bond thereof is a brazen bond. 
\p  
\v 21 The death thereof \em is\em* the worst death; and hell \em is\em* more profitable, \em that is, the pain of hell is less evil\em*, then it. 
\p  
\v 22 The perseverance thereof shall not dwell, but it shall hold the ways of unjust men; in his flame it shall not burn just \add [or rightwise]\add* men. 
\p  
\v 23 They that forsake God, shall fall into it; and it shall burn greatly in them, and it shall not be quenched; and as a lion it shall be sent into them, and as a \sls (leo)\sls*pard it shall hurt them. 
\p  
\v 24 Beset thine ears with thorns, and do not thou hear a wicked tongue; and make thou doors to \sls (or for)\sls* thy mouth, and locks to \sls (or for)\sls* thine ears. Well thou \add [or melt together]\add*, \em or temper thou\em*, thy gold, and thy silver; 
\p  
\v 25 and make thou a balance to \sls (or for)\sls* thy words, and rightful bridles to \sls (or for)\sls* thy mouth. 
\p  
\v 26 And take heed, lest peradventure thou slide in \sls (or with thy)\sls* tongue, and fall in the sight of enemies, set-ting treason, \add [or waiting, \+sls (or lying in wait)\+sls*]\add* to \sls (or for)\sls* thee, and thy fall be uncurable \add [or unhealable]\add* into death. 
\c 29  
\cl CHAPTER 29 
\p  
\v 1 He that doeth mercy, lendeth to his neighbour; and he that is full mighty in hand, keepeth the commandments. 
\p  
\v 2 Lend thou to thy neighbour in the time of his need; and again yield thou to a neighbour in his time. 
\p  
\v 3 Confirm thou a word, and do thou faithfully with him; and in all time thou shalt find that, that is needful to thee. 
\p  
\v 4 Many men guessed borrowing as finding, and gave dis-ease \add [or grief]\add* to those men that helped them. 
\p  
\v 5 Till they take \sls (or receive)\sls*, they kiss the hands of the giver; and in promises they make meek their voice. And in \sls (or at)\sls* the time of yielding, he shall ask \sls (for more)\sls* time, \add [or delay-ing]\add*, and he shall speak words of annoy\sls (ance)\sls*, \sls (or of hurt)\sls*, and of grutchings \sls (or grumblings)\sls*, and he shall challenge falsely, \add [or plead \+sls (for)\+sls*, or complain \+sls (about)\+sls*]\add* the time, \em to tarry the paying of \+sls (the)\+sls* debt\em*. 
\p  
\v 6 Forsooth if he may yield, he shall be adversary \add [or enemy]\add*; of a shilling scarcely he shall yield the half \add [or scarcely of the whole he shall yield the half]\add*, and he shall reckon that as \sls (re)\sls*funding. Else he shall defraud him in \sls (or of)\sls* his money, and \em the lender\em* shall have him \sls (as)\sls* an enemy without cause. And he shall yield to him, \em that is, to the lender\em*, wrongs and cursings; and for honour and benefice, he shall yield to him despising. 
\p  
\v 7 Many men lend not, not for cause of wickedness, but they dreaded to be defrauded without cause \add [or will-fully]\add*. 
\p  
\v 8 Nevertheless on \sls (or for)\sls* a meek man in soul, \em that is, a full poor debtor\em*, be thou stronger; and for alms-\add [deed\+sls (s)\+sls*]\add* draw thou not him \sls (along)\sls*. 
\p  
\v 9 For the commandment \em of God\em* take \sls (or receive)\sls* thou a poor man; and for his neediness leave thou not him void \sls (or do not let him go away empty-handed)\sls*. 
\p  
\v 10 Lose thou money for a brother and friend, and hide thou not it under a stone, into perdition. 
\p  
\v 11 Put thy treasure in the command-ments of the Highest; and it shall profit to thee more than gold. 
\p  
\v 12 \sls (En)\sls*close thou alms in the bosom of a poor man; and this \em alms\em* shall pray for thee \em to be delivered of \+sls (or by)\+sls* God\em* from all evil. The alms of a man \em is\em* as a bag \add [or a little sack]\add* with him; and it shall keep the grace of \add [a]\add* man, \em that is, God’s grace, given to man\em*, as the apple of the eye. And afterward it shall rise again, and shall yield to them a yielding, to each man into \sls (or onto)\sls* the head of them. 
\p  
\v 13 Above \add [or Over \+sls (or Better than)\+sls*]\add* the shield of a mighty man, and above \add [or over \+sls (or better than)\+sls*]\add* a spear it shall fight against thine enemy. 
\p  
\v 14 A good man maketh faith to \sls (or for)\sls* his neighbour \em in becoming \+sls (a)\+sls* borrow \+sls (er)\+sls*, \+sls (or a guarantor)\+sls*, for him in need\em*; and he that loseth, shall leave shame to him. 
\p  
\v 15 Forget thou not the grace of the borrower \sls (or of the guarantor)\sls*; for he gave his life for thee. 
\p  
\v 16 A sinful man \add [or The sinner]\add* and unclean fleeth the promiser. A sinner areckoneth to himself the good words of the borrower \sls (or of the guarantor)\sls*; 
\p  
\v 17 and the unkind man in wit forsaketh a man delivering him. 
\p  
\v 18 A man promiseth for his neighbour; and when \em he\em* hath lost reverence, \em that is, shamefastness before God and man, the borrower\em* shall be forsaken of \sls (or by)\sls* him. Worst \add [or Most shrewd \+sls (or depraved)\+sls*]\add* promise, \em by which the neighbour promised falsely to deliver his borrow\em*, hath lost \add [or spoiled]\add* many loving men, and hath moved them as the waves of the sea. It going in compass made mighty men to pass over \add [or to go out \+sls (or to go away)\+sls*]\add*; and \sls (then)\sls* they wandered about among alien folks. 
\p  
\v 19 A sinner breaking \add [or overpass-ing]\add* the commandment of the Lord shall fall into a wicked promise; and he that endeavoureth to do many things, shall fall into doom. 
\p  
\v 20 Recover thy neighbour by thy virtue \sls (or according to thy power)\sls*; and take heed to thyself, lest thou fall \sls (in the same manner)\sls*. 
\p  
\v 21 The beginning of \sls (the)\sls* life of a man \em is\em* water, and bread, and clothing, and \sls (a)\sls* house covering filth-\add [hood]\add*\sls (or nakedness)\sls*. 
\p  
\v 22 Better is the lifelode \sls (or the liveli-hood)\sls* of a poor man under the cover-ing of spars, than \add [plenteous]\add* shining feasts in pilgrimage without \sls (a)\sls* house, 
\p  
\v 23 The least thing pleaseth thee for a great thing, and thou shalt not hear the shame \add [or reproof]\add* of pilgrimage. 
\p  
\v 24 \em It is\em*\sls (a)\sls* wicked life to seek harbour from house into house; and where he shall be harboured, he shall not do trustily, neither he shall open the mouth. 
\p  
\v 25 He shall be harboured, and he shall feed, and give drink to unkind men; and yet he shall hear bitter things. 
\p  
\v 26 Pass, thou that art harboured, \add [or Go, guest]\add*, and array a table; and give thou meats to other men, \sls (of)\sls* those things that thou hast in the hand. 
\p  
\v 27 Go thou out from the face of the honour of my friends, for the friend-ship, \em either affinity\em*, of mine house \add [or for \+sls (the)\+sls* need of mine house]\add*; by harbouring thou art made a brother to me. 
\p  
\v 28 These things \em be\em* grievous to a man having wit; the reproving of house, and the despising of the usurer \add [or the lender]\add*. 
\c 30  
\cl CHAPTER 30 
\p  
\v 1 He that loveth his son, giveth busily beatings to him, \sls (so)\sls* that he be glad in his last thing, and \sls (so)\sls* that \em the son\em* touch not the doors of neighbours. 
\p  
\v 2 He that teacheth his son, shall be praised in \sls (or for)\sls* him; and shall have glory in him in the midst of \sls (his)\sls* menials. 
\p  
\v 3 He that teacheth his son, sendeth the enemy into envy; and in the midst of friends he shall have glory in that \em son\em*. 
\p  
\v 4 \sls (And though)\sls* The father of him is dead, and \sls (yet)\sls* he is as not dead; for he hath left after him \em a son\em* like him. 
\p  
\v 5 He saw in his life, and was glad in \sls (or over)\sls* him; and in his death he was not sorry \add [or sorrowed not]\add*, neither was ashamed before \sls (his)\sls* enemies. 
\p  
\v 6 For he left a defender of the house against \sls (his)\sls* enemies; and \sls (one)\sls* yielding grace to \sls (his)\sls* friends. 
\p  
\v 7 For \em defending\em* the souls \sls (or the lives)\sls* of \em his\em* sons, he shall bind together his wounds; and his entrails \add [or the bowels of him]\add* shall be disturbed \sls (or troubled)\sls* on each voice. 
\p  
\v 8 An horse untamed, \em either unchastised\em*, shall escape hard, and a son unchastised shall escape heady \sls (or become headstrong)\sls*. 
\p  
\v 9 Flatter thou the son, and he shall make thee dreading; play thou with him, and he shall make thee sorry \add [or sorrow\+sls (ful)\+sls*]\add*. 
\p  
\v 10 Laugh thou not with him \em of \+sls (or about)\+sls* his follies\em*, lest thou have sorrow together, and at the last thy teeth shall be astonished. 
\p  
\v 11 Give thou not power to him in youth, and despise thou not his thoughts. 
\p  
\v 12 Bow thou \sls (down)\sls* his neck in youth, and beat thou his sides, while he is a young child; lest peradventure he wax hard \add [or inwardly harden]\add*, and believe not to thee, and he shall be \sls (a)\sls* sorrow of \sls (or to thy)\sls* soul to thee. 
\p  
\v 13 Teach thy son, and work in him; lest thou offend into the filth of him \sls (or lest his filthy behaviour offend thee)\sls*. 
\p  
\v 14 Better is a poor man whole, and strong in mights \add [or strengths]\add*, than a rich man feeble, and beaten with malice. 
\p  
\v 15 The health of \sls (the)\sls* soul \sls (or of the body)\sls*\em is\em* in the holiness of rightfulness \add [or rightwiseness]\add*, and it is better than any gold and silver; and a strong body \em is better\em* than full much chattel \add [or than money without measure]\add*. 
\p  
\v 16 No chattel is above the chattel of \sls (the)\sls* health of \sls (the)\sls* body; and no liking is above the joy of \sls (the)\sls* heart. \add [There is not money over the money of the health of \+sls (the)\+sls* body; and there is not liking over the joy of \+sls (the)\+sls* heart.]\add* 
\p  
\v 17 Better is death than \sls (a)\sls* bitter life, and everlasting rest \em is better\em* than sickness dwelling continually \add [or enduring]\add*. 
\p  
\v 18 Goods hid in a closed mouth \em be\em* as settings forth of meats set about a sepulchre. 
\p  
\v 19 What shall sacrifice profit to an idol? for why it shall not eat, neither shall smell. So he that is driven away from the Lord, 
\p  
\v 20 and beareth the meeds \sls (or rewards)\sls* of wickedness, \add [or of shrewdness, \+sls (or of depravity)\+sls*]\add*, seeing with eyes, and wailing inwardly, as a gelding embracing a virgin \add [or a maiden]\add*, and sighing. 
\p  
\v 21 Give thou not sorrow to thy soul, \em that is, unreasonable sorrow, that annoyeth \+sls (or harmeth)\+sls* both body and soul\em*, and torment not thyself in \sls (or with)\sls* thy \sls (own)\sls* counsel, \em as they do that despair through sorrow, and then slay themselves\em*. 
\p  
\v 22 Mirth of heart, this is the life of man, and \em is\em*\sls (a)\sls* treasure of holiness without failing; and full out joying of a man is long life \add [or long living]\add*. 
\p  
\v 23 Have thou mercy on thy soul, and please thou God; and hold together and gather together thine heart in the holiness of him, and put far away sorrow from thee. For why sorrow hath slain many men; and none health is therein \add [or there is not profit in it]\add*. 
\p  
\v 24 Envy and wrathfulness shall make \sls (for)\sls* less days \add [or Envy and wrath shall lessen days]\add*; and thoughts shall bring eldness before the time. 
\p  
\v 25 A shining \add [or bright]\add* heart \em is\em* good in meats, \sls (or for meals or digestion)\sls*; for why meats thereof be made diligently. 
\c 31  
\cl CHAPTER 31 
\p  
\v 1 Waking of honesty shall make fleshes to fail, \sls (or Waiting for, or Watching over riches shall make the flesh to pine away)\sls*; and \sls (the much)\sls* thought thereof shall take away sleep. 
\p  
\v 2 Thought\sls (s)\sls* of before-knowing turn-eth away wit; and grievous sickness maketh sober the soul. 
\p  
\v 3 A rich man travailed in the gather-ing of \sls (his)\sls* chattel \add [or \+sls (his)\+sls* substance]\add*; and in his rest he shall be filled with his goods. 
\p  
\v 4 A poor man travailed in \sls (the)\sls* decreasing \add [or the less\+sls (en)\+sls*ing]\add* of \sls (his)\sls* lifelode; and in the end he is made needy. \sls (A poor man worked hard, even though his livelihood continued to decrease; and in the end, he is still needy.)\sls* 
\p  
\v 5 He that loveth gold, shall not be justified; and he that pursueth \add [or followeth]\add*\sls (after)\sls* wasting \sls (or corrup-tion)\sls*, shall be \add [full]\add*-filled thereof. 
\p  
\v 6 Many men be given into the fallings of gold, \em that is, many men felled into sins for gold\em*; and the perdition \add [or the loss]\add* of them was made in the fairness thereof \add [or of it]\add*. 
\p  
\v 7 A tree of offension, \sls (or of offence, or a stumbling block)\sls*, is the gold of them that make sacrifice; woe to them that pursue \add [or follow]\add* it, and each unprudent man shall perish therein. 
\p  
\v 8 Blessed is a rich man, which is found without wem \em of covetousness and avarice\em*; and that went not after gold, neither hoped in money, and treasures. 
\p  
\v 9 Who is this, and we shall praise him? for he did marvels in his life. 
\p  
\v 10 Which \add [or Who]\add* is proved, \sls (or tried, or tested)\sls* therein \add [or in \+sls (or by)\+sls* it]\add*, and is found perfect, and ever-lasting glory shall be to him? which might trespass, and trespassed not, and do evils, and did not. 
\p  
\v 11 Therefore his goods be estab-lished in the Lord; and all the church of saints shall tell out his alms-deeds. 
\p  
\v 12 Thou hast set at a great board \sls (or a bountiful table)\sls*; open thou not first thy cheek on it, \em that is, begin thou not to eat first\em*. \add [And]\add* Say thou not, whether those be many things, that be on it. 
\p  
\v 13 Have thou mind \sls (or Remember)\sls*, that an evil eye is \sls (a)\sls* wayward, \add [or shrewd, \+sls (or depraved)\+sls*]\add*\sls (thing)\sls*. What thing worse, than an eye is made? therefore of all his face he \sls (or it)\sls* shall weep, when he seeth. 
\p  
\v 14 Stretch thou not forth first thine hand; and thou defouled by envy, be ashamed. Be thou not oppressed of \sls (or by)\sls* wine in a feast. 
\p  
\v 15 Understand of thyself the things, that be of thy neighbour. \add [Understand what be of thy neighbour, of thyself.]\add* 
\p  
\v 16 Use thou as a discreet and temperate man these things that be set forth to thee; and \sls (so)\sls* be thou not hated, when thou eatest \sls (too)\sls* much. 
\p  
\v 17 Cease thou first because of learn-ing, \em either nurture\em*; and do not thou be outrageous \add [or do thou not be too much]\add*, lest peradventure thou offend. 
\p  
\v 18 And if thou hast set in the midst of many men, stretch not forth \add [or not stretch thou out]\add* thine hand sooner than they; and ask thou not first for to drink. 
\p  
\v 19 A little wine is full\sls (y)\sls* sufficient to a learned man; and in sleeping thou shalt not travail for that \em wine\em*, and thou shalt not feel travail. 
\p  
\v 20 Waking, and choler, \em either bitter moisture\em*, and gnawing \add [or anguish]\add* to an undiscreet and untemperate man. But the sleep of health \em is\em* in a scarce \sls (or a moderate)\sls* man; he shall sleep unto the morrowtide; and his soul \sls (or his body)\sls* shall delight with him. 
\p  
\v 21 And if thou art constrained in eating \add [too]\add* much, rise thou from the midst, and spew thou; and it shall refresh thee, and thou shalt not bring sickness to thy body. 
\p  
\v 22 Son, hear thou me, and despise thou not me; and at the last thou shalt find \sls (that)\sls* my words \sls (be true)\sls*. In all thy works be thou swift; and all sickness shall not come to thee. 
\p  
\v 23 The lips of many men shall bless a shining man in loaves; and the witnessing of his truth \em is\em* faithful. 
\p  
\v 24 The city shall grutch \sls (or grumble)\sls* in the worst bread; and the witness-ing of wickedness thereof is sooth \sls (or true)\sls*. 
\p  
\v 25 Do not thou excite \add [or stir \+sls (up)\+sls*]\add* them that be diligent \add [or busy]\add* in \sls (or with)\sls* wine; for why wine hath destroyed many men. 
\p  
\v 26 Fire proveth hard iron; so wine drunken in drunkenness shall reprove the hearts of proud men. 
\p  
\v 27 Even life to men \em is\em* wine \em drunken\em* in soberness; if thou drinkest it meas-urably, thou shalt be sober. What is the life which is made less by wine? What defraudeth life? death. Wine was made in gladness, not in drunken-ness, at \add [or from]\add* the beginning. 
\p  
\v 28 Wine drunken measurably \em is\em* full out joying of soul and of body. Sober drink is \sls (the)\sls* health of \sls (the)\sls* soul and of \sls (the)\sls* body. 
\p  
\v 29 Wine drunken much maketh voiding, and ire \add [or wrath]\add*, and many fallings, \em or mischiefs\em*. 
\p  
\v 30 Wine drunken much \em is\em* bitterness of \sls (the)\sls* soul. Strength of drunkenness and hurting of an unprudent man maketh virtue less, and making wounds. 
\p  
\v 31 In the feast of wine, reprove thou not a neighbour; and despise thou not him in his mirth. Say thou not words of shame \add [or of reproof]\add* to him; and oppress thou not him in \add [again]\add*-asking. 
\c 32  
\cl CHAPTER 32 
\p  
\v 1 They have set thee a governor, do not thou be enhanced \sls (or exalted)\sls*; be thou among them as one of them. Have thou \sls (the)\sls* care of them, and so behold thou; and when all thy care is filled, sit thou to meat \add [or \+sls (to)\+sls* rest]\add*. 
\p  
\v 2 That thou be glad for them, and take the ornament of grace; and get \sls (a)\sls* crown, and \sls (the)\sls* dignity of \sls (the)\sls* congregation \sls (or assembly)\sls*. 
\p  
\v 3 Speak thou, the greater man in birth; for why the word of him that loveth cunning, \sls (or knowing, or knowl-edge)\sls* become thee first; and hinder thou not \sls (the)\sls* music. 
\p  
\v 4 Where hearing is not, shed \add [or pour]\add* thou not out a word; and do not thou be enhanced uncovenably \sls (or inopportunely)\sls* in thy wisdom. 
\p  
\v 5 A gem of carbuncle in the ornament of gold; and comparison of musics in the feast of wine. 
\p  
\v 6 As in the making \add [or \+sls (the)\+sls* forging]\add* of gold is a signet of smaragdus \sls (or emerald)\sls*, so the number of musics \em is\em* in merry and measurable \add [or temper-ate]\add* wine. 
\p  
\v 7 Hear thou \add [\+sls (while)\+sls* being]\add* still, and good grace shall come to thee for reverence. Young man, speak thou scarcely in \sls (or for)\sls* thy cause, \sls (only)\sls* when need is. If thou art asked twice, the head have thine answer. 
\p  
\v 8 In many things be thou as uncunning \sls (or as unknowing)\sls*, and hear thou \add [\+sls (while)\+sls* being]\add* still \sls (al)\sls*to-gether, and asking \add [or seeking]\add*. 
\p  
\v 9 And presume thou not to speak in the midst of great men; and where eld \add [or old]\add* men be, speak thou not much. 
\p  
\v 10 Lightning shall go before hail, and grace shall go before shamefastness, and good grace shall come to thee for reverence. 
\p  
\v 11 And in the hour of rising, trifle thee not, \em that is, make thee no tarrying in arraying, either trifling of hairs, as women do\em*; forsooth run thou before first into thine house, and there call thou thee to \em answer\em*\add [or and there be thou called to]\add*, and there play thou. 
\p  
\v 12 And do thy conceits \add [or thy conceivings]\add*, \em that is, perform thy good purpose conceived there\em*, and not in sins, and in a proud word. 
\p  
\v 13 On all these things, bless thou the Lord, that made thee, and filling thee greatly of \sls (or with)\sls* all his goods. 
\p  
\v 14 He that dreadeth God, shall take his teaching; and they that wake to him, shall find blessing. 
\p  
\v 15 He that seeketh the law, shall be filled thereof; and he that doeth traitorously, shall be caused to stumble therein. 
\p  
\v 16 They that dread God, shall find just doom; and shall kindle rightful-ness \add [or rightwisenesses]\add* as \sls (a)\sls* light. 
\p  
\v 17 A sinful man, \em that is, obstinate in sin\em*, shall eschew blaming \add [or shall shun correction]\add*; and after his will \sls (or according to his desire)\sls*, he shall find comparison. 
\p  
\v 18 A man of counsel shall not lose \add [or destroy]\add* understanding; \sls (but)\sls* a man alien and proud shall not dread dreading. Yea, after that he hath done with that \em dread\em* without counsel, and he shall be reproved by his pursuings \add [or his followings]\add*. 
\p  
\v 19 Son, do thou nothing without counsel; and after the deed thou shalt not repent. 
\p  
\v 20 Go thou not in the way of falling, and offend \sls (or stumble)\sls* thou not against \sls (the)\sls* stones \add [or and thou shalt not offend \+sls (or stumble)\+sls* against \+sls (the)\+sls* stones]\add*. 
\p  
\v 21 Betake thou not thee to a travail-ous way, lest thou set slander to thy soul \sls (or thou cause thy own soul to stumble)\sls*; 
\p  
\v 22 and be thou ware of thy sons, and perceive thou \add [or take heed]\add* of thy menials. 
\p  
\v 23 In all thy work believe thou by \sls (or in the)\sls* faith of thy soul; for why this is the keeping of \sls (the)\sls* command-ments. 
\p  
\v 24 He that believeth to \sls (or in)\sls* God, taketh heed to the commandments; and he that trusteth in him, shall not be made less, \em either deceived\em*. 
\c 33  
\cl CHAPTER 33 
\p  
\v 1 Evils shall not come to him that dreadeth God; but God shall keep \sls (or shall guard)\sls* him in temptation, and shall deliver \add [him]\add* from evils. 
\p  
\v 2 A wise man hateth not the commandments, and rightfulnesses \add [or rightwisenesses]\add*; and he shall not be hurtled down, as in the tempest of a ship \sls (or as a ship in a tempest)\sls*. 
\p  
\v 3 A wise man believeth in the law of God, and the law \em is\em* faithful to him. 
\p  
\v 4 He that maketh open asking, shall make ready \add [or shall prepare]\add* a word; and so he shall pray, and shall be heard, and he shall keep \sls (the)\sls* teach-ing, and then he shall answer. 
\p  
\v 5 The entrails of a fool \em be\em* as a wheel of a cart, and his thoughts as an axle able to turn about. 
\p  
\v 6 An horse a stallion, so and a friend a scorner, neigheth under each \sls (one)\sls* sitting above. 
\p  
\v 7 Why a day overcometh a day, and again the light \em overcometh\em* light, and a year \em overcometh\em* a year, \sls (and)\sls* the sun \em overcometh\em* the sun? 
\p  
\v 8 Those be parted of \sls (or separated by)\sls* the cunning \sls (or the knowing)\sls* of the Lord, by the sun made, and keeping the commandment of God. 
\p  
\v 9 And it \add [or he]\add* shall change \add [the]\add* times and the feast days of them, and in those \em times the Jews\em* hallowed holy days, or holidays, at an hour. God enhanced and magnified of those \em holy days\em* or \em holidays\em*; and of those he setted \add [or put]\add* into the number of days; 
\p  
\v 10 and \em God made\em* all men of firm earth, and of nesh earth \add [or soil]\add*, whereof Adam was formed. 
\p  
\v 11 In the multitude of \sls (the)\sls* cunning \sls (or the knowing)\sls* of the Lord, he parted them, and changed the ways of them. 
\p  
\v 12 \sls (Some)\sls* Of them \em God\em* blessed, and enhanced \sls (or exalted)\sls*; and \sls (some)\sls* of them he hallowed, and chose to \sls (or for)\sls* himself \add [or presented]\add*; \sls (some)\sls* of them he cursed, and made low, and turned them from the departing \add [or to the severing]\add* of them. 
\p  
\v 13 As \sls (the)\sls* clay of a potter \em is\em* in the hand of him, to make \add [or to form]\add* and dispose, \sls (so)\sls* that all the ways thereof \em be\em* after the ordinance of him \add [or after his disposition]\add*; so a man \em is\em* in the hand of him that made him; and he shall yield to him by \add [or after]\add* his doom. 
\p  
\v 14 Against evil is good, and against life \em is\em* death; so and a sinner \em is\em* against a just man \add [or the rightwise]\add*. 
\p  
\v 15 And so behold thou into all the works of the Highest; two things against twain, and one thing against one \add [or two against two, one against one]\add*. 
\p  
\v 16 And I the last waked, and as he that gathereth dregs of grapes, after the gatherers of grapes. And I hoped in the blessing of God; and as he that gathereth grapes, I filled the presser. 
\p  
\v 17 Behold ye, for I travailed not to \sls (or for)\sls* me alone, but to \add [or for]\add* all that seek cunning, \sls (or knowing, or knowledge)\sls*. 
\p  
\v 18 Great men, and all peoples hear ye me; and ye governors of the church, perceive with ears. 
\p  
\v 19 Give thou not power over thee in thy life to a son, and to a woman \add [or a wife]\add*, to a brother, and to a friend; and give thou not thy possession to another man, lest peradventure it repent thee, and thou beseech for those \sls (again)\sls*. 
\p  
\v 20 While thou art alive, \add [or livest]\add*, and breathest yet, each man shall not change thee. 
\p  
\v 21 For it is better, that thy sons pray thee, than that thou behold into the hands of thy sons. 
\p  
\v 22 In all thy works be thou sove-reign; give thou not a wem into thy glory. 
\p  
\v 23 In the day of \sls (the)\sls* ending of \sls (the)\sls* days of thy life, and in the time of thy going out \add [or thy death]\add*, part \add [or deal \+sls (out)\+sls*]\add* thine heritage. 
\p  
\v 24 Meats, and a rod, and a burden to an ass; bread, and chastising \add [or disci-pline]\add*, and work to \sls (or for)\sls* a servant. 
\p  
\v 25 He worketh in, \em or under\em*, chastis-ing, and seeketh to have rest; slake or slack thou \sls (thine)\sls* hands to him, and he seeketh freedom. 
\p  
\v 26 A yoke and bridle bow down an hard neck; and busy workings bow down a servant. Torment and stocks to \sls (or for)\sls* an evil-willed servant; 
\p  
\v 27 send thou him into working, lest he be idle; for why idleness hath taught much malice. 
\p  
\v 28 Ordain thou \add [or set]\add* him in work, for so it becometh him; \sls (so)\sls* that if he obeyeth not, bow thou down him in stocks, 
\p  
\v 29 and make thou not \em him\em* large over any man, \em that is, give thou not to him power over any man\em*, but without doom, do thou nothing grievous \add [or heavy]\add*. 
\p  
\v 30 If a faithful servant is to thee, be he as thy soul \add [or thy life]\add* to thee; treat thou him so as a brother, for thou hast bought him in \sls (or with)\sls* the blood of life. 
\p  
\v 31 If thou hurtest him unjustly, he shall be turned into fleeing away \add [or into flight]\add*; and if he enhancing goeth away, thou knowest not whom thou shalt seek, and in what way thou shalt seek him. 
\c 34  
\cl CHAPTER 34 
\p  
\v 1 Vain hope and a leasing \sls (or a lie)\sls*, to an unwise man; and dreams \add [or swevens]\add* enhance unprudent men. 
\p  
\v 2 As he that taketh \add [or catcheth \+sls (at)\+sls*]\add* a shadow, and pursueth wind, so and he that taketh heed to leasings seen, \add [or to the seen leasings]\add*, \em or in vain dreams\em*. 
\p  
\v 3 After this thing \em is\em* the sight of dreams \add [or swevens]\add*; before the face of a man \em is\em* the likeness of another man. 
\p  
\v 4 What shall be cleansed of him that is unclean \add [or Of the unclean, what shall be cleansed]\add*, and what true thing shall be said of a liar? 
\p  
\v 5 False divining of error, and false divinings by chittering \sls (or chattering)\sls* of birds, and dreams of witches, \sls (all)\sls* is vanity. And as \em the heart\em* of a woman travailing of \add [or bearing \+sls (a)\+sls*]\add* child, thine heart suffereth fantasies; 
\p  
\v 6 no but visitation is sent out of \sls (or from)\sls* the Highest, give thou not thine heart in \sls (or to)\sls* those \em dreams\em*. 
\p  
\v 7 For why dreams have made many men for to err, and men hoping in those fell down. \add [Many men forsooth swevens made to err, and \+sls (they)\+sls* fell away hoping in them.]\add* 
\p  
\v 8 The word of the law \em of God and of his prophets\em*, shall be made perfect without leasing \sls (or without lies)\sls*; and wisdom in the mouth of a faithful man shall be made plain. 
\p  
\v 9 What knoweth he, that is not assayed? A man assayed in many things, shall think many things; and he that learned many things, shall tell out understanding. 
\p  
\v 10 He that is not assayed \add [or not expert \+sls (or experienced)\+sls*]\add*, knoweth few things; forsooth he that is a fool in many things, shall multiply malice. 
\p  
\v 11 What manner things know he, that is not assayed? He that is not planted, \em that is, hath not set root of \+sls (or in)\+sls* understanding, and desire in \+sls (or for)\+sls* good\em*, shall be plenteous in wickedness \add [or shall abound \+sls (in)\+sls* shrewdness \+sls (or in depravity)\+sls*]\add*. I saw many things in telling out, and full many customs of words. 
\p  
\v 12 Sometime I was in peril unto death, for the cause of these things; and I was delivered by the grace of God. 
\p  
\v 13 The spirit of them that dread God is sought, and shall be blessed in the beholding of him. For why the hope of them \em is\em* into \em God\em* saving them; and the eyes of the Lord \em be\em* into \sls (or upon)\sls* them, that love him. 
\p  
\v 14 He that dreadeth God, shall not tremble \add [or quake]\add* for anything, and he shall not dread; for why \em God\em* is his hope. 
\p  
\v 15 The soul of him that dreadeth the Lord, is blessed. To whom beholdeth he, and who is his strength? 
\p  
\v 16 The eyes of the Lord \em be\em* on them that dread him. \em God is\em* a defender of might, steadfastness \add [or firmament]\add* of virtue, covering of \sls (or from)\sls* heat, and a shadowing place of \sls (or at)\sls* midday; beseeching of offending, \em that is, hearing beseeching for offenses\em*, and help of \sls (or from)\sls* falling, 
\p  
\v 17 enhancing the soul, and lighten-ing the eyes, and giving health, and life, and blessing. 
\p  
\v 18 The offering of him that offereth of wicked thing, \em that is, of thing gotten unjustly\em*, is defouled; and the scornings of unjust men be not well pleasant \add [or well-pleasing]\add*. 
\p  
\v 19 The Lord alone \em is\em* to them that abide him in the way of truth, and of rightfulness \add [or of rightwiseness]\add*. The Highest approveth not \sls (of)\sls* the gifts of wicked men, neither beholdeth in \sls (or on)\sls* the offerings of wicked men, neither in \sls (or for)\sls* the multitude of their sacrifices he shall do \add [or shall have]\add* mercy to \sls (or for their)\sls* sins. 
\p  
\v 20 He that offereth sacrifice of the chattel \add [or substance]\add* of poor men, \em is\em* as he that slayeth the son in the sight of his father. 
\p  
\v 21 The bread of needy men is the life of a poor man; he that defraudeth him, is a man of blood. 
\p  
\v 22 He that taketh away bread \sls (earn-ed)\sls* in \sls (or with)\sls* sweat, \em is\em* as he that slayeth his neighbour. He that shed-deth out blood, and he that doeth fraud to an hired man, be brethren. 
\p  
\v 23 One building, and one destroy-ing; what profiteth it to them, no but travail? 
\p  
\v 24 One praying, and one cursing; whose voice shall the Lord hear? 
\p  
\v 25 What profiteth the washing of him, that is washed for a dead body, and toucheth again a dead body? 
\p  
\v 26 So a man that fasteth in his sins, and again doing the same sins, what profiteth he in meeking himself? who shall hear his prayer? 
\c 35  
\cl CHAPTER 35 
\p  
\v 1 He that keepeth the word \em of God\em*, multiplieth prayer. Wholeful \add [or Wholesome]\add* sacrifice is to take heed to \sls (or of)\sls* the commandments, and to depart \add [or go away]\add* from all wicked-ness. And to offer the pleasing of sacrifice for unrightfulnesses \add [or \+sls (for)\+sls* unrightwisenesses]\add*, and beseeching for sins, \em is\em* to go away from unrightful-ness \add [or unrightwiseness]\add*. 
\p  
\v 2 He that offereth purest flour of wheat, shall yield grace, \em that is, shall give a pleasant \+sls (or a pleasing)\+sls* service to God\em*; and he that doeth mercy, offereth a sacrifice. 
\p  
\v 3 It is well pleasant \add [or well-pleas-ing]\add* to the Lord, to go away from wickedness; and prayer \em is\em* to go away from unrightfulness \add [or unrightwise-ness]\add*. 
\p  
\v 4 Thou shalt not appear void \sls (or empty)\sls* before the sight of God; 
\p  
\v 5 for why all these things be done for the behests, \sls (or for the commands, or the commandments)\sls* of God. 
\p  
\v 6 The offering of a just man \add [or of the rightwise]\add* maketh fat the altar, and is \sls (the)\sls* odour of sweetness in the sight of the Highest. 
\p  
\v 7 The sacrifice of a just man is acceptable, and the Lord shall not for-get the mind \sls (or the memory)\sls* of him. 
\p  
\v 8 With good will yield thou glory to God, and make thou not less the first fruits of thine hands. 
\p  
\v 9 In each gift \add [or In all gifts]\add* make glad thy cheer, and in full out joying hallow thy tithes. 
\p  
\v 10 Give thou to the Highest after his \add [free]\add* gift, \em that is, after the quantity of thy goods, which thou hast of \+sls (or from)\+sls* God\em*; and with good eye make thou the findings of thine hands, \em that is, with rightful intent, ordain thy good works, to the praising of God and not of man\em*. 
\p  
\v 11 For why the Lord is a yielder, and he shall yield sevenfold so much \add [or as much]\add* to thee. 
\p  
\v 12 Do not thou offer shrewd \sls (or de-praved)\sls* gifts; for he shall not receive those \add [or them]\add*. And do not thou behold an unjust \add [or the unrightwise]\add* sacrifice; for the Lord is judge, and glory, \em or taking\em*, \sls (or favouring)\sls* of person\sls (s)\sls* is not at \add [or with]\add* him. 
\p  
\v 13 The Lord shall not take a person against a poor man \sls (or The Lord will not favour some person over a poor person)\sls*; and he shall hear the prayer of him that is hurt. 
\p  
\v 14 He shall not despise the prayers of a fatherless child, neither a widow, if she sheddeth \add [or poured]\add* out \sls (the)\sls* speech of wailing. 
\p  
\v 15 Whether the tears of a widow go not down to the cheek, and the crying of her on him that leadeth forth those \em tears\em*? For why those ascend from the cheek unto heaven, and the Lord hearing shall not delight in those \add [or in them]\add*. 
\p  
\v 16 He that worshippeth God in delighting, shall be received; and his prayer shall nigh unto the clouds. 
\p  
\v 17 The prayer of him that meeketh himself shall pierce \sls (the)\sls* clouds, and till it nigheth \sls (or approacheth)\sls*, he shall not be comforted, and he shall not go away, till the Highest behold \sls (him)\sls*. And the Lord shall not be far \add [or long away]\add*, but he shall judge just \add [or rightwise]\add* men, and shall make doom; 
\p  
\v 18 and the Strongest shall not have patience in those \add [or \+sls (towards)\+sls* them]\add*, that \sls (or till)\sls* he trouble the back\sls (s)\sls* of them. And he shall yield vengeance to \sls (the)\sls* folks \add [or \+sls (the)\+sls* Gentiles]\add*, till he take away the fullness \add [or the plenty]\add* of proud men, and trouble \sls (al)\sls*to-gether the sceptres of wicked men; 
\p  
\v 19 till he yield to men after their deeds, and after the works of Adam\f + \fr 35:19 \ft \+em By (or For) Hebrews, this word ‘Adam’ signifieth man commonly\+em*.\f*, and after the presumption of him; till he deem the doom of his people, and shall delight just \add [or rightwise]\add* men in his mercy. 
\p  
\v 20 The mercy of God \em is\em* fair in the time of tribulation, as clouds of rain in the time of dryness \add [or of drought]\add*. 
\c 36  
\cl CHAPTER 36 
\p  
\v 1 God of all things, have thou mercy on us; and behold thou us, and show to us the light of thy merciful doings. 
\p  
\v 2 And send thy dread on heathen men, that sought not thee, \sls (so)\sls* that they know that no God is, no but thou; that they tell out thy great \add [worthy]\add* deeds. 
\p  
\v 3 Raise \add [up]\add* thine hand on heathen men aliens, \sls (so)\sls* that they see thy power. 
\p  
\v 4 For as thou were hallowed in us in the sight of them, so in our sight thou shalt be magnified in them; 
\p  
\v 5 \sls (so)\sls* that they know thee, as and we have known \sls (thee)\sls*, that none other is God, except thee, Lord. 
\p  
\v 6 Make thou new signs, and change thou marvels; glorify the hand, and the right arm. 
\p  
\v 7 Raise \add [up]\add* thou strong vengeance, and shed out ire \add [or pour out wrath]\add*; take away the adversary, and torment the enemy. 
\p  
\v 8 Haste thou the time, and have thou mind on the end, \sls (so)\sls* that they tell out thy marvels. 
\p  
\v 9 And he that is saved, be devour-ed in the ire of flame; and they that treat worst thy people, find perdition. 
\p  
\v 10 All-break thou the head\sls (s)\sls* of princes, and of enemies, saying, None other is \add [or There is none other]\add*, except us. 
\p  
\v 11 Gather thou together all the lineages of Jacob, and know they that no God is, no but thou \add [or there is no God but thou]\add*, \sls (so)\sls* that they tell out thy great deeds; and thou shalt inherit them, as at the beginning. 
\p  
\v 12 Have thou mercy on thy people, on which thy name is called in to help; and on Israel, whom thou madest even to thy first engendered \add [or \+sls (be)\+sls*gotten]\add* son. 
\p  
\v 13 Have thou mercy on Jerusalem, the city of thine hallowing, on the city of thy rest. 
\p  
\v 14 \add [Full]\add*-fill thou Zion with thy virtues, that may not be told out \add [or untellable]\add*, and \em fill\em* thy people with thy glory. 
\p  
\v 15 Give thou witnessing, that at \add [or from]\add* the beginning they were thy creatures; and raise thou \sls (the)\sls* prayers, which the former prophets spake in thy name. 
\p  
\v 16 Lord, give thou meed \sls (or reward)\sls* to them that abide thee, \sls (so)\sls* that thy prophets be found true \add [or faithful]\add*; 
\p  
\v 17 and hear thou the prayer of thy servants. After the blessing of Aaron give thou to thy people, and \sls (ad)\sls*dress \sls (or direct)\sls* thou us into the way of rightfulness; \sls (so)\sls* that all men know, that dwell in \sls (or on the)\sls* earth, that thou art God, the beholder of worlds. 
\p  
\v 18 The womb shall eat all meat\sls (s)\sls*, and \em one\em* meat is better than \em another\em* meat. 
\p  
\v 19 Cheeks touch meat almost, and an unwise heart \em receiveth\em* false \add [or leasing \+sls (or lying)\+sls*]\add* words. 
\p  
\v 20 A shrewd \sls (or depraved)\sls* heart shall give heaviness, and a wise man shall against-stand \add [or withstand]\add* it. 
\p  
\v 21 A woman shall take each knave \add [or male]\add* child, and \sls (or but)\sls* a daughter is \add [or there is a daughter]\add* better than a son. 
\p  
\v 22 The fairness of a woman maketh glad the face of her husband, and \sls (so)\sls* she shall bring desire \sls (for herself)\sls* over all the covetousness \add [or \+sls (the)\+sls* lust]\add* of \sls (her)\sls* man. 
\p  
\v 23 If there is a tongue of healing, \add [or of curing, \+sls (or of caring)\+sls*]\add*, there is also \sls (one)\sls* of assuaging, and of mercy; \sls (and)\sls* the husband of her is not after \sls (or like most of)\sls* the \sls (other)\sls* sons of men. 
\p  
\v 24 He that hath in possession a good woman, beginneth \sls (a)\sls* possession; she is an help like \sls (to)\sls* him\sls (self)\sls*, and a pillar as \sls (or of)\sls* rest. 
\p  
\v 25 Where an hedge is not, the possession shall be ravished \sls (or snatched)\sls* away \add [or broken]\add*; and where a woman is not, a needy man waileth. 
\p  
\v 26 To whom believeth he that hath no nest, and boweth down wherever it is dark, as a thief girt \add [or girded up]\add*, skipping out from city into city? 
\c 37  
\cl CHAPTER 37 
\p  
\v 1 Each friend shall say, And I have coupled friendship; but that \add [or there]\add* is a friend, a friend by name alone. 
\p  
\v 2 Whether sorrow is not till to death? Forsooth a fellow of \sls (the)\sls* table and a friend shall be turned to enmity. 
\p  
\v 3 A! the worst \add [or O! most shrewd \+sls (or depraved)\+sls*]\add* presumption, whereof art thou made to cover dry malice, and the guilefulness thereof \add [or the treachery of it]\add*? 
\p  
\v 4 A fellow of \sls (the)\sls* table shall be merry with a friend in delightings, and in the day of tribulation he shall be \sls (an)\sls* adversary. 
\p  
\v 5 A fellow of \sls (the)\sls* table shall have sorrow with a friend, for cause \add [or because]\add* of the womb \sls (or the belly)\sls*; and he shall take \sls (up a)\sls* shield against an enemy. 
\p  
\v 6 Forget thou not thy friend in thy soul, and be thou not unmindful of him in thy works. Do not thou take counsel with the father of thy wife; and hide thou counsel from them that have envy to thee. 
\p  
\v 7 Each counsellor showeth counsel, but there is a counsellor to, \add [or in]\add*, \sls (or only for)\sls* himself. 
\p  
\v 8 Keep thy soul from an evil counsellor; first know thou, what is his need, and what he shall think in his soul; lest peradventure he send a stake, \add [or he put a pole, or a pale]\add* into the earth, 
\p  
\v 9 and say to thee, Thy way is good, and \sls (then)\sls* he stand again-ward, to see what shall befall to thee. 
\p  
\v 10 With an unreligious man, treat thou\f + \fr 37:10 \ft \+em The author of this book speaketh here\+em* (and also in verse 11 below) \+em in scorn, and understandeth the contrary of his saying\+em*.\f*\sls (not)\sls* of \sls (or about)\sls* holiness, and with an unjust \add [or unrightwise]\add* man, \sls (not)\sls* of \sls (or about)\sls* rightfulness \add [or rightwiseness]\add*\f + \fr 37:10 \ft In verse 12 of the Early Version, but not in the Later Version, the following sentence appears: Do thou not counsel with him that hath thee suspect, and from men envying to thee, hide thou thy counsel. See verse 10 of the KJV.\f*, 
\p  
\v 11 and with a woman, \sls (not)\sls* of \sls (or about)\sls* these things which she hateth \add [or envieth]\add*. With a fearedful man, treat thou \sls (not)\sls* of \sls (or about)\sls* battle, with a merchant, \sls (not)\sls* of \sls (or about)\sls* carrying over of merchandises \em to chapping\em*\add [or \+sls (about)\+sls*\+sls (ex)\+sls*changing]\add*; with a buyer, \sls (not)\sls* of \sls (or about)\sls* selling, with an envious man, \sls (not)\sls* of \sls (or about)\sls* graces to be done; with an unpiteous man, \sls (not)\sls* of \sls (or about)\sls* pity, with an unhonest man, \sls (not)\sls* of \sls (or about)\sls* honesty, with a workman of the field \add [or the field worker]\add*, \sls (not)\sls* of \sls (or about)\sls* each work; with a work-man hired by the year \add [or the annual worker]\add*, \sls (not)\sls* of \sls (or about)\sls* the ending of the year, with a slow servant, \sls (not)\sls* of \sls (or about)\sls* much working. Give thou not attention \add [or Take thou not heed]\add* to these men in all counsel, 
\p  
\v 12 but be thou busy with an holy man, whomever thou knowest \sls (is)\sls* keeping God’s dread, whose soul is after thy soul. Whoever doubteth in darknesses, shall not have sorrow with thee. 
\p  
\v 13 And establish thou the heart of good counsel with thee; for why another thing is not more than it \sls (is)\sls* to thee. 
\p  
\v 14 The soul of an holy man telleth out truths sometime; more than seven beholders \add [or lookers about]\add*, sitting on high for to behold. 
\p  
\v 15 And in all these things beseech thou the Highest, that he \sls (ad)\sls*dress \sls (or direct)\sls* thy way in truth. 
\p  
\v 16 Before all works a soothfast \sls (or a true)\sls* word go before thee; and a stead-fast counsel \em go\em* before each deed. 
\p  
\v 17 A wicked, \add [or shrewd, \+sls (or de-praved)\+sls*]\add* word shall change the heart, 
\p  
\v 18 of which \em heart\em* four parts come forth; good and evil, life and death; and a busy tongue is lord of those. 
\p  
\v 19 A wise man hath taught many men, and \sls (or but)\sls* he is \sls (not)\sls* sweet to his \sls (own)\sls* soul. 
\p  
\v 20 He that speaketh sophistically, \em either by sophism\em*, is hateful; he shall be defrauded in each thing. 
\p  
\v 21 For why grace is not given of \sls (or from)\sls* the Lord to him, for he is defrauded of all wisdom. 
\p  
\v 22 A wise man is wise to his \sls (own)\sls* soul, and the fruits of his wit be worthy to be praised. 
\p  
\v 23 A wise man teacheth his people, and the fruits of his wit be faithful. 
\p  
\v 24 A wise man shall be filled with blessings, and they that see him shall praise \em him\em*. 
\p  
\v 25 The life of a man \em is\em* in the number of days; but the days of Israel be unnumberable. 
\p  
\v 26 A wise man in the people shall inherit honour, and his name shall be living without end. 
\p  
\v 27 Son, assay thy soul in thy life; and if it is wicked, give thou not power to it; 
\p  
\v 28 for why not all things speed to \sls (or be expedient for)\sls* all men, and not each kind pleaseth each soul. 
\p  
\v 29 Do not thou be greedy in each eating, and shed thou not out thee \add [or pour thee not out] [up]\add* on each meat. 
\p  
\v 30 For in many meats shall be sickness, and greediness shall nigh unto choler. 
\p  
\v 31 Many men died for \sls (or from)\sls* gluttony; but he that is abstinent, shall increase \add [or add \+sls (to)\+sls*]\add*\sls (his)\sls* life. 
\c 38  
\cl CHAPTER 38 
\p  
\v 1 Honour thou a leech \sls (or Honour a physician)\sls*, for need; for why the Highest hath made \add [or formed]\add* him. 
\p  
\v 2 For why all medicine is of \sls (or from)\sls* God; and he shall take of \sls (or receive from)\sls* the king a gift. 
\p  
\v 3 The cunning of a leech shall enhance his head \sls (or The knowledge of a physician shall exalt or lift up his head)\sls*; and he shall be praised in the sight of great men. 
\p  
\v 4 The Highest hath made \add [or \+sls (hath)\+sls* formed]\add*\sls (out)\sls* of the earth medicine; and a prudent man shall not loathe it. 
\p  
\v 5 Whether bitter water was not made sweet of \sls (or by)\sls* a tree? The virtue of those things \em came by experience\em* to the knowing of men; 
\p  
\v 6 and the Highest gave cunning \sls (or knowing)\sls* to men, for to be honoured in his marvels. 
\p  
\v 7 A man healing \add [or curing]\add* in \sls (or with)\sls* these things, shall assuage sorrow, 
\p  
\v 8 and an ointment-maker shall make pigments of sweetness, and shall make anointings of health; and his works shall not be ended. For why the peace of God \em is\em* on the face of \sls (the)\sls* earth. 
\p  
\v 9 My son, despise not thyself in thy sickness; but pray thou \sls (to)\sls* the Lord, and he shall heal \add [or cure]\add* thee. 
\p  
\v 10 Turn thou away from sin, and \sls (ad)\sls*dress \sls (or direct)\sls* thine hands, and cleanse thine heart from all sin. 
\p  
\v 11 Give thou sweetness, and the mind \sls (or a memorial)\sls* of clean \add [or tried]\add* flour of wheat, and make thou \sls (a)\sls* fat offering; 
\p  
\v 12 and give thou place to a leech \sls (or to a physician)\sls*. For the Lord made him, and depart he not \add [or go he not away]\add* from thee; for his works be needful to thee. 
\p  
\v 13 For why \sls (a)\sls* time is \sls (or shall be)\sls*, when thou shalt fall into the hands of them. 
\p  
\v 14 Forsooth they shall beseech the Lord, that he \sls (ad)\sls*dress \sls (or direct)\sls* the work of them, and health for their living. 
\p  
\v 15 He that trespasseth in the sight of him, that made him, shall fall into the hands of the leech \sls (or the physician)\sls*. 
\p  
\v 16 Son, bring thou forth tears on, \sls (or over, or for)\sls* a dead man, and thou as suffering hard things begin to weep; and by \add [or after]\add* doom, \sls (or according to custom)\sls*, cover thou the body of him, and despise thou not his bury-ing. 
\p  
\v 17 But for backbiting, bear thou bitterly the mourning of him \sls (for)\sls* one day; and be thou comforted for sorrow \add [or take comfort for heavi-ness]\add*. And make thou mourning after his merit \add [or deserving]\add*\sls (for)\sls* one day, either twain \add [or two]\add*, for backbiting. 
\p  
\v 18 For why death hast\sls (en)\sls*eth of \sls (or from)\sls* sorrow, and covereth virtue \sls (or strength)\sls*; and the sorrow of heart boweth the head. 
\p  
\v 19 Sorrow dwelleth in leading away; and the chattel \add [or the substance]\add* of a needy man \em is\em* after his heart. 
\p  
\v 20 Give thou not thine heart in sorrow, but put it away from thee; and have thou mind on the last things, 
\p  
\v 21 and do not thou forget. For why no \sls (re)\sls*turning is \em from death to this present life\em*, and thou shalt nothing profit to this \em dead man\em*\add [or]\add* and to this thou shalt nothing profit; and thou shalt harm worst thyself. 
\p  
\v 22 Be thou mindful of my doom \sls (or Remember my judgement)\sls*; for also thine shall be thus, to me yesterday, and to thee today. 
\p  
\v 23 In the rest of a dead man, make thou his mind \sls (or his memory)\sls* to have rest; and comfort thou him, in the going out of his spirit. 
\p  
\v 24 Write thou wisdom in the time of voidness; and he that is made less in \sls (doing)\sls* deeds, shall perceive wisdom; for he shall be filled of \add [or with]\add* wisdom. 
\p  
\v 25 He that holdeth the plow \sls (or the plough)\sls*, and he that hath glory in a goad, driveth oxes \add [or oxen]\add* with a prick, and he liveth in the works of those \add [or them]\add*; and his telling \em is\em* in the sons of bulls. 
\p  
\v 26 He shall give his heart to turn furrows; and his waking \em shall be\em* about the fatness of \sls (the)\sls* kine. 
\p  
\v 27 So each carpenter, and principal workman, that passeth the night as the day; that engraveth images en-graved \add [or the which graved graven brooches]\add*, and the busyness of him diverseth \add [or varieth]\add* the painture; he shall give his heart \add [in]\add* to the likeness of painture \sls (or of painting)\sls*, and by his waking he performeth the work. 
\p  
\v 28 So a smith sitting beside the anfelt \sls (or the anvil)\sls*, and beholding the work of iron, the heat of fire burneth his fleshes; and he striveth in the heat of the furnace. The voice of a hammer maketh new his ear; and his eye \em is\em* against \sls (or towards)\sls* the like-ness of a vessel. He shall give his heart into the performing of \sls (the)\sls* works; and by his waking he shall adorn unperfection, \em that is, matter \+sls (or material)\+sls* which he bringeth to perfection of form\em*. 
\p  
\v 29 So a potter sitting at his work, turning a wheel with his feet, which is put ever\add [more]\add* in busyness for his work; and all his working is unnumberable. 
\p  
\v 30 In his arm he shall form \sls (the)\sls* clay; and before his feet he shall bow \sls (down)\sls* his virtue \sls (or strength)\sls*. He shall give his heart to end perfectly something; and by his waking he shall cleanse the furnace. 
\p  
\v 31 All these men hoped in their hands; and each man is wise in his craft. 
\p  
\v 32 A city is not builded without all these men. And they shall not dwell \add [in]\add*, neither go \add [in]\add*; 
\p  
\v 33 and they shall not skip over into the church. They shall not sit on the seat of a judge; and they shall not understand the testament of doom, neither they shall make open teach-ing and doom; and they shall not be found in parables. 
\p  
\v 34 But they shall confirm the creature \sls (or the nature)\sls* of the world, and their prayer \em is\em* the working of craft; 
\c 39  
\cl CHAPTER 39 
\p  
\v 1 and they give their soul, and they ask together \add [or together seeking]\add* in the law of the Highest. A wise man shall seek out the wisdom of all \sls (the)\sls* eld \add [or old]\add* men; and he shall give attention in \sls (or to the)\sls* prophets. 
\p  
\v 2 He shall keep the telling\sls (s)\sls* of \sls (the)\sls* named men; and he shall enter \sls (al)\sls*together into the hard sentences \add [or the slynesses]\add* of parables. 
\p  
\v 3 He shall seek out the privy things of proverbs; and he shall be conver-sant in the hid things of parables. 
\p  
\v 4 He shall minister in the midst of great men; and he shall appear in the sight of the chief judge. He shall pass into the land of alien folks; for he shall assay goods, and evils in all \em things\em*. 
\p  
\v 5 He shall give his heart to wake early to the Lord that made him; and he shall beseech in the sight of the Highest. He shall open his mouth in prayer; and he shall beseech for his trespasses. 
\p  
\v 6 For if the great Lord will \sls (or desire to)\sls*, he shall fill him with the spirit of understanding. And he shall send the words of his wisdom, as rains; and in prayer he shall acknowl-edge to the Lord. 
\p  
\v 7 And he, \em that is, the Lord\em*, shall \sls (ad)\sls*dress \sls (or direct)\sls* his counsel, and teaching; and shall counsel in his hid things. 
\p  
\v 8 He shall make open the wisdom of his teaching; and he shall have glory in the law of the testament of the Lord. 
\p  
\v 9 Many men shall praise his wisdom; and it shall not be done away till into the world. His mind shall not go away \add [or The memory of him shall not go away]\add*; and his name shall be sought from generation into generation. 
\p  
\v 10 Folks shall tell out his wisdom; and the church shall tell \add [out]\add* his praising. 
\p  
\v 11 If his name dwelleth, he shall leave more than a thousand; and if he resteth, it shall profit to him. 
\p  
\v 12 Yet I shall take counsel to tell out, for I am \add [full]\add*-filled as with madness; and \em mine inner spirit\em* saith in voice, 
\p  
\v 13 Ye fruits of God, hear me, and make ye fruit, as roses planted on \sls (or by)\sls* the rivers of waters. 
\p  
\v 14 Have ye odour of sweetness, as the Lebanon \em hath\em*. Bring forth flowers, as a lily; give ye odour, and make ye boughs into grace. And praise ye together a song; and bless ye the Lord in his works. 
\p  
\v 15 Give ye great honour to his name, and acknowledge ye to him in the voice of your lips, in songs of lips, and in harps; and thus ye shall say in acknowledging, 
\p  
\v 16 All the works of the Lord be full good. 
\p  
\v 17 Forsooth water as an heap \em of stones\em* stood at his word; and as receptacles of waters in the word of his mouth. 
\p  
\v 18 For why peaceableness is made in his commandment; and no default \add [or less\+sls (en)\+sls*ing]\add* is in the health of him, \em that is, in \+sls (the)\+sls* saving made by him\em*. 
\p  
\v 19 The works of each \add [or all]\add* flesh \em be\em* before him; and nothing is hid from his eyes. 
\p  
\v 20 He beholdeth from the world till into the world; and nothing is won-derful \add [or is marvellous]\add* in his sight. 
\p  
\v 21 It is not to say, What is this thing, either, What is that thing? for why all things shall be sought in their time. 
\p  
\v 22 The blessing of him shall flow as a flood; 
\p  
\v 23 and as the great flood filled greatly the earth, so his ire \add [or wrath]\add* shall inherit in folks, that sought not him. 
\p  
\v 24 As he turned waters into dryness-es \add [or into drought]\add*, and the earth was dried, and his ways were \sls (ad)\sls*dressed \sls (or directed)\sls* to the ways of them; so offensions \sls (or stumbling blocks)\sls* in his ire \add [or in \+sls (his)\+sls* wrath]\add*\em be \+sls (ad)\+sls* dressed \+sls (or directed)\+sls*\em* to sinners. 
\p  
\v 25 Good things were made at the beginning to \sls (or for)\sls* good men; so good things and evil \em be made\em* to \sls (or for)\sls* worst men. 
\p  
\v 26 The beginning of needful \add [or necessary]\add* thing\sls (s)\sls* to the life of men, \sls (be)\sls* water, fire, and iron, and salt, and milk, and bread of clean \add [or tried]\add* flour of wheat, and honey, and a cluster of grape\sls (s)\sls*, and oil, and cloth\sls (es)\sls*\add [or clothing]\add*. 
\p  
\v 27 All these things shall turn to holy men into goods; so and to unfaithful \add [or unpious]\add* men and to sinners into evils. 
\p  
\v 28 Spirits be that be made \add [or formed]\add* to \sls (or for)\sls* vengeance; and in their madness they confirmed their torments. And in the time of ending they shall shed \add [or pour]\add* out virtue; and they shall confound \sls (or confuse)\sls* the strong vengeance of him that made them. 
\p  
\v 29 Fire, hail, hunger, and death; all these things be made \add [or be formed]\add* to \sls (or for)\sls* vengeance; 
\p  
\v 30 the teeth of beasts, and scorpions, and serpents, and a sword punishing wicked men into destroying. 
\p  
\v 31 In the commandments of him, those \add [or they]\add* shall eat, and those \add [or they]\add* shall be made ready on the earth in need; and in their times those \add [or they]\add* shall not \sls (over)\sls*-pass one word. 
\p  
\v 32 Therefore from the beginning I was confirmed \sls (or certain)\sls*; and I counselled, and thought, and left \sls (it all)\sls* written \sls (down)\sls*. 
\p  
\v 33 All the works of the Lord \em be\em* good; and each work shall serve in his \sls (or its)\sls* hour. 
\p  
\v 34 It is not to say, This is worse than that; for why all things shall be \sls (ap)\sls*proved in their time. 
\p  
\v 35 And now in all the heart and mouth praise ye together, and bless ye the name of the Lord. 
\c 40  
\cl CHAPTER 40 
\p  
\v 1 Great occupation is made to all men, and an heavy yoke on the sons of Adam, from the day of the going out of the womb of their mother, till into the day of burying into the mother of all men, \em that is, into the earth\em*. 
\p  
\v 2 The thoughts of them, and the dreads of \sls (the)\sls* heart, \sls (the)\sls* findings of abiding, and the day of ending; 
\p  
\v 3 from him that sitteth before on a glorious seat \sls (or a throne of glory)\sls*, unto a man made low into earth and ashes; 
\p  
\v 4 from him that useth jacinth, \sls (or hyacinth)\sls*, \add [or blue silk]\add*, and beareth a crown, unto him that is covered with raw linen cloth \sls (or a linen cloak)\sls*, 
\p  
\v 5 madness \sls (or anger)\sls*, envy, noise, doubting, and dread of death, wrath-fulness dwelling continually, and strife; and in the time of resting \add [or repast]\add* in the bed, the sleep of night changeth his cunning \sls (or his know-ing, or his knowledge)\sls*. 
\p  
\v 6 Forsooth a little \em is\em* as nought in rest; beholding \em is\em* of him in sleep as in the day. He is disturbed \sls (or is troubled)\sls* in the sight of his heart, as he that escapeth \add [or escaped]\add* in the day of battle. 
\p  
\v 7 He rose up in the day of his health, \sls (or his deliverance)\sls*, and dread-ing not at any dread, 
\p  
\v 8 with all flesh, from man unto beast, and sevenfold \sls (more)\sls*, \em that is, grievous punishment, shall come\em* on sinners. 
\p  
\v 9 At these things, death, blood, striving \add [or strife]\add*, and sword, oppressings, hunger, and sorrow, and beatings; 
\p  
\v 10 all these things be made on wicked men, and the great flood was made for them. 
\p  
\v 11 For why all \sls (the)\sls* things that be of the earth, shall \sls (re)\sls*turn into the earth; and all \sls (the things that be of the)\sls* waters shall \sls (re)\sls*turn into the sea. 
\p  
\v 12 All gift, \em given for \+sls (the)\+sls* destroying of rightfulness\em*, and wickedness, \em done for gift\em*, shall be done away; and faith shall stand into the world \sls (for ever-more)\sls*. 
\p  
\v 13 The riches \add [or The substances]\add* of unjust men shall be made dry \add [or dried \+sls (up)\+sls*]\add* as a flood; and shall sound as a great thunder in \sls (the)\sls* rain. 
\p  
\v 14 \em An unjust man\em* shall be glad in opening his hands; so trespassers \add [or law-breakers]\add* shall fail in the end. 
\p  
\v 15 The sons of \sls (the)\sls* sons of wicked \add [or unpious]\add* men shall not multiply branches; and \sls (be like)\sls* unclean roots sown on the cop \sls (or the top)\sls* of a stone. 
\p  
\v 16 Greenness beside each water; and at the brink of the flood \sls (or bank of the river)\sls*, it shall be drawn out by the root before all \sls (the)\sls* hay. 
\p  
\v 17 Grace as paradise in blessings; and mercy dwelleth into the world. 
\p  
\v 18 The life of a workman sufficient to himself shall be made sweet; and thou shalt find treasure therein. 
\p  
\v 19 \sls (The)\sls* Building of a city shall con-firm a name; and a woman without wem \add [or undefouled]\add* shall be reckon-ed above \add [or over]\add* this, \em for why her steadfastness shall stand without end\em*. 
\p  
\v 20 Wine and music make glad the heart; and \sls (or but the)\sls* love of wisdom \em gladdeth\em* above \add [or over]\add* ever either. 
\p  
\v 21 Pipes and psaltery make sweet melody; and \sls (or but)\sls* a sweet tongue \sls (is)\sls* above \add [or over]\add* ever either. 
\p  
\v 22 An eye shall desire grace and fair-ness; and green sowings above these things \add [or over these green tilthes]\add*. 
\p  
\v 23 A friend and \add [a meat]\add*-fellow coming together in time; and \sls (or but)\sls* a woman with a man \sls (is)\sls* above \add [or over]\add* ever either. 
\p  
\v 24 Brethren into help in the time of tribulation \em comfort much\em*; and \sls (or but)\sls* mercy shall deliver more than they \add [or over them]\add*. 
\p  
\v 25 Gold and silver, and setting of feet; and \sls (or but)\sls* counsel well-pleas-ing \em is\em* above \add [or over]\add* ever either. 
\p  
\v 26 Riches and virtues enhance the heart; and \sls (or but)\sls* the dread of the Lord \sls (is)\sls* more than this. Making less \add [or less\+sls (en)\+sls*ing]\add* is not in the dread of the Lord; and in that \em dread\em* it is not to seek help. 
\p  
\v 27 The dread of the Lord \em is\em* as \sls (a)\sls* paradise of blessing; and \em the blessings of God\em* covered him above all glory. 
\p  
\v 28 Son, in the time of thy life, be thou not needy, \em that is, in \+sls (the)\+sls* time of \+sls (thy)\+sls* present life, granted to thee to work well, be thou not idle\em*; for it is better to die, then to be needy, \em that is, it is better to die bodily, then to be idle, by which a man dieth ghostly \+sls (or spiritually)\+sls*\em*. 
\p  
\v 29 A man beholding into another man’s board, his life is not in the thought of lifelode \sls (or about liveli-hood)\sls*; for he sustaineth his life with other men’s meats. Forsooth a chas-tised man and learned \add [or disciplined and taught]\add*, shall keep himself. 
\p  
\v 30 Neediness shall be defouled \add [or made]\add* in the mouth of an unprudent, \em or \+sls (a)\+sls* slow and idle\em*, man; and \sls (or but)\sls* fire shall burn in his womb. 
\c 41  
\cl CHAPTER 41 
\p  
\v 1 A! \add [or O!]\add* death, thy mind is full bitter to an unjust \add [or an unrightwise]\add* man, and having peace in his riches; to a restful \add [or quiet]\add* man, and whose ways be \sls (ad)\sls*dressed \sls (or directed)\sls* in all things, \em that is, hath prosperity in all temporal things\em*, and yet mighty to take meat. 
\p  
\v 2 A! \add [or O!]\add* death, thy doom \sls (or thy judgement)\sls* is good to a needy man, and which is made less in strengths, and faileth for age, and to whom is care of all things, and unbelieveful, that loseth \sls (or destroyeth)\sls* wisdom. 
\p  
\v 3 Do not thou dread the doom of death, \em that is, set thou thee in such a state, \+sls (so)\+sls* that the doom of death be good to \+sls (or for)\+sls* thee\em*; have thou mind what things were before thee, and what things shall come on \sls (or after)\sls* thee; this doom \em is\em* of the Lord to each man. 
\p  
\v 4 And those things that shall come on \sls (or after)\sls* thee in the good pleasance \sls (or through the good pleasure)\sls* of the Highest; whether ten years, either an hundred, either a thousand. For why none accusing \sls (or excusing)\sls* of life is in hell \sls (or in the grave)\sls*, \em that is, no man may excuse him \+sls (self)\+sls* there, in alleging \+sls (the)\+sls* goodness of \+sls (his)\+sls* life\em*. 
\p  
\v 5 The sons of abominations be the sons of sinners; and they that dwell beside the houses of wicked men. 
\p  
\v 6 The heritage of the sons of sinners shall perish; and the continuance of shame \add [or reproof]\add* with the seed of them. 
\p  
\v 7 \sls (The)\sls* Sons \sls (will)\sls*\sls (com)\sls*plain of a wicked father; for they be in shame \add [or in reproof]\add* for him. 
\p  
\v 8 Woe to you, ye wicked men, that have forsaken the law of the Highest. 
\p  
\v 9 And if ye be born, ye shall be born in cursedness; and if ye be dead, your part shall be in cursedness. 
\p  
\v 10 All things that be of the earth, shall \sls (re)\sls*turn into the earth; so wicked men \em shall turn\em* from cursing into perdition. 
\p  
\v 11 The mourning of men \em is\em* in \sls (or for)\sls* the body of them; but the name of wicked men shall be done away. 
\p  
\v 12 Have thou busyness of \sls (or for)\sls* a good name; for why this shall dwell more with thee, than a thousand treasures great and precious. 
\p  
\v 13 The number of days \em is the term\em* of \sls (a)\sls* good life; but a good name shall dwell without end. 
\p  
\v 14 Sons, keep ye teaching in peace; for why wisdom hid, and treasure unseen, what profit is in ever either? 
\p  
\v 15 Better is a man that hideth his folly, than a man that hideth his wisdom. 
\p  
\v 16 Nevertheless \sls (re)\sls*turn ye again in these things that come forth of \sls (or from)\sls*\add [or go out of]\add* my mouth. For it is not good to keep all unreverence, and not all things please all men in faith. 
\p  
\v 17 Be ye ashamed of fornication, before father, and before mother; and of a leasing \sls (or of a lie)\sls*, before a justice, and before a mighty man; 
\p  
\v 18 and of trespass, before a prince, and before a judge; and of wicked-ness, before a synagogue, and a people; and of unrightfulness, or unrightwiseness, before a fellow, and a friend; 
\p  
\v 19 and of theft, in the place wherein thou dwellest; of the truth and the testament of God; of sitting \add [down]\add* at the meat in loaves; and of the blem-ishing \add [or darkening]\add* of \add [the]\add* gift \sls (or of giving)\sls*, and \sls (of)\sls* taking \add [of \+sls (the)\+sls* taken]\add*; 
\p  
\v 20 of stillness, before them that greet \add [or saluting]\add*\sls (thee)\sls*; of the beholding of a lecherous woman; and of the turning away of the cheer \sls (or the face)\sls* of a cousin. 
\p  
\v 21 Turn thou not away thy face from thy neighbour; and \em be thou ware\em* of taking away a part, and not restoring \sls (it)\sls*. Behold thou not the woman of another man; 
\p  
\v 22 and ensearch thou not her hand-maid, neither stand thou at her bed. Be thou ware of friends, of the words of upbraiding \add [or of reproof]\add*; and when thou hast given, upbraid thou not. 
\p  
\v 23 Double thou not a word of hearing, \sls (and)\sls* of the showing of an hid word; 
\p  
\v 24 and thou shalt be verily \sls (or truly)\sls* without shame \add [or confusion]\add*, and thou shalt find grace in the sight of all men. 
\c 42  
\cl CHAPTER 42 
\p  
\v 1 Be thou not \sls (a)\sls*shamed for all these things; and take \add [or accept]\add* thou not a person, \sls (so)\sls* that thou do trespass. 
\p  
\v 2 \em Be thou ware\em* of the law and testament of the Highest, of doom to justify a wicked man; \add [of the law of the Highest, and of the testament of doom, to justify the unpious;]\add* 
\p  
\v 3 of the word of fellows, and of way-goers, and of the giving of \sls (the)\sls* heritage of friends; 
\p  
\v 4 of the evenness of balance, and of weights, of the getting of many things, and of few things; 
\p  
\v 5 of \sls (the)\sls* corruption of buying, and of merchants, and of much chastising \add [or much discipline]\add* of sons; and of a worst servant, to make the side to bleed. 
\p  
\v 6 A sealing, \em either closing\em*, is good on a wicked woman. Where be many hands, close thou \sls (up)\sls*; 
\p  
\v 7 and whatever thing thou shalt betake \sls (or receive)\sls*, number thou, and weigh thou; forsooth describe thou, \em either write \+sls (down)\+sls*\em*, each gift, and taking \sls (or receiving in)\sls*. 
\p  
\v 8 \em Abstain thou\em* from the teaching of an unwitty \sls (or unwise)\sls* man, and fool, and of elder men that be deemed of \sls (or by the)\sls* young men; and thou shalt be learned in all things, and thou shalt be commendable \add [or \+sls (ap)\+sls*prov-able \+sls (or approved)\+sls*]\add* in the sight of all men. 
\p  
\v 9 An hid daughter of a father is waking \add [or watch\+sls (ing)\+sls*]\add* and busyness of \sls (or for)\sls* him; she shall take away sleep; lest peradventure she be made \sls (an)\sls* adulteress in her young waxing age, and lest she dwelling with the husband, be made hateful; 
\p  
\v 10 lest anytime she be defouled in her virginity \add [or be polluted in her maidenhood]\add*, and be found with child in the keeping of her father; lest peradventure she dwelling with the husband, do trespass, either certainly be made barren. 
\p  
\v 11 Ordain thou keeping \add [or ward]\add* on a lecherous daughter, lest any time she make thee to come into shame \add [or reproof]\add* to \add [thine]\add* enemies, of backbiting in the city, and of casting out of the people; and she make thee ashamed in the multitude of people. 
\p  
\v 12 Do not thou take heed to each man \sls (or to each person)\sls* in the fair-ness, \em that is, in delighting in the beholding of his \+sls (or their)\+sls* fairness\em*; and do not thou dwell in the midst of women. 
\p  
\v 13 For why a moth cometh forth of \sls (or from)\sls* clothes, and \sls (the)\sls* wicked-ness of a man \em cometh forth\em* of \sls (or from)\sls* a woman. 
\p  
\v 14 For why the wickedness of a man is better, \em that is, less evil\em*, than a woman doing well, and a woman shaming into shame \sls (or reproach)\sls*\f + \fr 42:14 \ft See note above, for Chapter 25, verse 13.\f*. 
\p  
\v 15 Therefore be thou mindful of the works of the Lord; and I shall tell \sls (out)\sls* the works of the Lord, which I saw, in the words of the Lord. 
\p  
\v 16 The sun lightening \add [or shining through]\add* beheld by all things; and the work thereof is full of the glory of the Lord. 
\p  
\v 17 Whether the Lord made not holy men to tell out all his marvels, which the Lord Almighty steadfast in his glory shall confirm? 
\p  
\v 18 He shall ensearch the depth, and the heart of men; and he shall think in \sls (or on)\sls* the fellness, \add [or the sly wit, or guile]\add*, of them. For the Lord knew all cunning \sls (or all knowing or knowl-edge)\sls*, and beheld into the sign\sls (s)\sls* of the world; 
\p  
\v 19 telling \add [out]\add* those things that be passed, and those things that shall come; showing the steps of hid things. 
\p  
\v 20 And no thought passeth him \sls (by)\sls*, and no word hideth itself from him. 
\p  
\v 21 He made fair the great works of his wisdom, which is before the world, and till into the world; neither anything is increased \add [or added]\add*, neither is decreased \add [or less\+sls (en)\+sls*ed]\add*, and he hath no need to the counsel of any \add [man]\add*. 
\p  
\v 22 All his works be full desirable, and to behold, as a sparkle which is. 
\p  
\v 23 All these things live, and dwell into the world \sls (or evermore)\sls*; and all things obey to him in all need. 
\p  
\v 24 All things \em be\em* double, one against one; and he made not anything to fail. 
\p  
\v 25 He shall confirm the goods of each \add [or of everything]\add*; and who shall be filled, seeing his glory? 
\c 43  
\cl CHAPTER 43 
\p  
\v 1 The firmament of highness is the fairness thereof \add [or The firmament of the height is the fairness of him]\add*; the fairness of heaven in the sight of glory. 
\p  
\v 2 The sun in beholding, telling in going out, \em is\em* a wonderful vessel, the work of \sls (the)\sls* high \em God\em*\add [or the \+sls (Most)\+sls* High]\add*. 
\p  
\v 3 In the time of midday it burneth the earth; and who shall be able to suffer \sls (or to endure)\sls* in the sight of his \sls (or its)\sls* heat? 
\p  
\v 4 Keeping a furnace in the works of heat; the sun burning hills in three manners, sending out beams of fire \add [or blasting out fiery beams]\add*, and shining again with his \sls (or its)\sls* beams, blindeth \sls (the)\sls* eyes. 
\p  
\v 5 The Lord \em is\em* great, that made it; and in the words of him it hast\sls (en)\sls*ed \sls (its)\sls* journey \add [or hied the way]\add*. 
\p  
\v 6 And the moon in all \em men\em*\add [or things]\add* in his \sls (or its)\sls* time \em is\em*\sls (a)\sls* show-ing of time, and a sign of the world. 
\p  
\v 7 A sign of the feast \add [or holy]\add* day \em is taken\em* of \sls (or from)\sls* the moon; the light which is made little in the end. 
\p  
\v 8 The month is increasing by \add [or after]\add* the name thereof, wonderfully into the ending. A vessel of castles \sls (or of the hosts)\sls* in high things, shining gloriously in the firmament of heaven. 
\p  
\v 9 The fairness of heaven \em is\em* the glory of stars; the Lord on high lighteneth the world. 
\p  
\v 10 In \sls (or At)\sls* the words of the Holy \sls (One)\sls*, those \sls (or they)\sls* shall stand at the doom; and those shall not fail in their wakings \add [or their watches]\add*. 
\p  
\v 11 See thou the rainbow, and bless thou him that made it; it is full fair in his \sls (or its)\sls* shining. 
\p  
\v 12 It went about heaven in the compass \add [or the circuit]\add* of his \sls (or its)\sls* glory; the hands of \sls (the)\sls* high \em God\em*\add [or the \+sls (Most)\+sls* High]\add* opened it. 
\p  
\v 13 By his commandment he hast\sls (en)\sls*-ed the snow; and he hast\sls (en)\sls*eth to send out the lightnings of his doom. 
\p  
\v 14 Therefore \sls (the)\sls* treasures were opened, and clouds fled out \add [or flew away]\add* as bees \add [or birds]\add*. 
\p  
\v 15 In his greatness he setted \add [the]\add* clouds; and stones of hail were broken. 
\p  
\v 16 Hills shall be moved in \sls (or at)\sls* his sight; and the south wind shall blow in \sls (or at)\sls* his will. 
\p  
\v 17 The voice of his thunder shall beat \add [or beateth]\add* the earth; the tem-pest of the north, and the gathering together of \sls (the)\sls* wind. And as a bird putting down to sit sprinkleth \sls (or scattereth the)\sls* snow, and the coming down of that \em snow is\em* as a locust drenching \sls (or drowning)\sls* down. 
\p  
\v 18 The eye shall wonder \add [or marvel]\add* on the fairness of \sls (the)\sls* whiteness thereof; and an heart dreadeth \add [or the heart quaketh]\add* on the rain thereof. 
\p  
\v 19 He shall shed \add [or pour]\add* out frost as salt on the earth; and while \em the wind\em* bloweth, it shall be made as \sls (the)\sls* cops \sls (or tops)\sls* of a briar \add [or the bramble \+sls (bush)\+sls*]\add*. 
