\p  
\v 9 Which were received in a whirlwind of fire, in a chariot of horses of fire. 
\p  
\v 10 Which art written in the dooms of \sls (their)\sls* times, to please, \add [or assuage]\add*, \sls (or appease)\sls* the wrathfulness of the Lord, to reconcile the heart of the father to the son, and to restore the lineages of Jacob. 
\p  
\v 11 They be blessed, that saw thee, and were made fair in thy friendship; for why we live only in life, but after death our name shall not be such. 
\p  
\v 12 Elijah, that was covered in \sls (or with)\sls* a whirlwind; and his spirit was \add [full]\add*-filled in\sls (to)\sls* Elisha. \em Elisha\em* in his days dreaded not the prince, and no man overcame him by power \add [or by might]\add*; 
\p  
